{"title_page": "Yaakov Lorberbaum", "text_new": "'''Yaakov ben Yaakov Moshe Lorberbaum of Lissa''' (1760-1832) (known in [[English language|English]] as '''Jacob ben Jacob Moses of Lissa''', '''Jacob Lorberbaum''' or '''Jacob Lisser''',<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\">{{JewishEncyclopedia|inline=1|article=JACOB BEN JACOB MOSES OF LISSA|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/8417-jacob-ben-jacob-moses-of-lissa|author=[[Solomon Schechter]] and [[Max Schloessinger]]|accessdate=March 14, 2012}}</ref> [[Hebrew]]: '''\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05d1\u05df \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05de\u05e9\u05d4 \u05de\u05dc\u05d9\u05e1\u05d0''') was a [[Rabbi]] and [[Posek]]. He is most commonly known as the \"Ba'al HaChavas Da'as\" or \"Ba'al HaNesivos\" for his most well-known works, or as the \"[[Leszno|Lissa]] Rav\" for the city in which he was [[Chief Rabbi]].\n\n==Biography==\nLorberbaum was the great-grandson of the Chacham Tzvi, Rabbi [[Zvi Ashkenazi]];<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/> he was therefore related to Rabbi [[Jacob Emden]]. According to one tradition, his father, Rabbi [[Yaakov Moshe Lorberbaum|Yaakov Moshe]], died before he was born, and his relative, Rabbi Yosef Teomim, the rabbi of Bursztyn, brought him up. This accounts for the common name that both father and son share. Another tradition states that before he was born, his father fell ill, and dreamed that he would recover in the merit of the son that would be born to him. In the merit of his future son, the father took his name-to-be.<ref>\"M'Gedolei HaTorah V'HaChassidus\" (Bromberg) vol. 12 pg. 10</ref>. Yet another legend told, is that at his naming ceremony his father was preoccupied with his learning and thought they asked for his own name. He studied under Rabbi [[Meshulam Igra]].<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/>\n\nHe was head of the ''[[Beth din|Beis Din]]'' in [[Kalush, Ukraine]].<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/> In 1809, he agreed to become the Rav in [[Leszno|Lissa]] (today known as Leszno, Poland), where he enlarged his [[Yeshiva]]'s enrollment. Hundreds of scholars came to study there in the years of his leadership. Among his students were Rabbi [[Elijah Gutmacher]], Rabbi [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]], and [[Aleksander (Hasidic dynasty)|Rabbi Shraga Feivel Danziger]].\n\nAlong with Rabbi [[Akiva Eiger]] and Rabbi Eiger's son-in-law, the [[Moses Sofer|Chasam Sofer]], Rabbi Lorberbaum vehemently fought against the [[maskilim]], the reformers of the [[haskalah|Jewish Enlightenment]]. In 1822, he left Lissa and returned to Kalish, where he wrote many of his works. He lived there for ten years.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/><ref>{{cite web | first=Mark B | last=Greenspan | title=Divrei Moshe: An Introduction to Commentary 'Ma\u2019aseh Nissim' | url = http://www.oceansidejc.org/Haggadah/Haggadah-5764.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nHe was widely respected as a [[posek]], and is one of three authorities on whom Rabbi [[Shlomo Ganzfried]] based his [[posek|rulings]] in the ''[[Shlomo Ganzfried#Kitzur Shulchan Aruch|Kitzur Shulchan Aruch]]'', the well known precis of [[Halacha|Jewish law]].  Similarly, the ''[[Chochmat Adam]]'', by Rabbi [[Avraham Danzig]], was written in consultation with Rabbi Lorberbaum (as well as Rabbi [[Chaim Volozhin]]).\n\nHis status was such that it is reported that Rabbi Eiger once fainted when he was honored with an [[Torah reading#Aliyot|Aliyah]] in the lieu of Rav Yaakov. (See ''Shimusha Shel Torah'', Rabbi Meir Tzvi Bergman).\n\nRabbi Lorberbaum died in [[Stryi|Stryj]] (then in [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]]) on 25 May 1832.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/>\n\n==Works==\nReb Yaakov wrote many works of [[Torah]] on [[Talmud]] and on [[Halacha]] (Jewish law).\n \n*Works on Talmud include:\n** ''Toras Gittin,'' commentary on ''[[Shulchan Aruch]]'', ''[[Even HaEzer]],'' 119-155, and chiddushim on the Talmudic treatise [[Gittin]] ([[Frankfort-on-the-Oder]], 1813; Warsaw, 1815)\n** ''Beis Yaakov,'' commentary on ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''Even HaEzer'', 66-118, and on the Talmudic tractate [[Ketubot (Talmud)|Ketubot]] (Grubeschow, 1823)\n** ''Emes L'Yaakov'' (on [[Talmudic lore]])\n** He also published his late father's works on the Talmud, including his famous novellae to Tractate [[Keritot]]\n*Works of Halacha include:\n** ''Chavas Daas,'' commentary on ''[[Shulchan Aruch]]'', ''[[Yoreh Deah]]'', 69-201; the earlier sections of ''Yoreh Deah'' (1-68) are very briefly dealt with in the form of an introduction to the work ([[Lemberg]], 1799; [[Dyhernfurth]], 1810, and often since in editions of the ''Yoreh Deah'', as the [[Vilna]] 1894 ed.). In it the works of earlier commentators are discussed and somewhat [[pilpul|pilpulistically]] developed.\n** ''Mekor chayim,'' commentary on ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''[[Orach Chayim]]'', 429 and following, with notes on the commentaries ''[[Turei Zahav]]'' and ''[[Avraham Gombiner|Magen Avraham]]''; the second part contains chiddushim on [[Keritot]] ([[Zolkiev]], 1807; Frankfort-on-the-Oder, 1813; [[Warsaw]], 1825; Dyhernfurth, 1827)\n** ''Nesivos HaMishpat'' on ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''[[Choshen Mishpat]]'', in two parts (Dyhernfurth, Lemberg; Zolkiev, 1809, 1816; [[Sudilkov]], 1830; and often since in Lemberg editions of ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''Choshen Mishpa\u1e6d''). It is said that Nesivos HaMishpat was made famous by the strong attacks in it against the ''Ketzos HaChoshen'' of Rabbi [[Aryeh Leib Heller]].\n** ''Kehillas Yaakov,'' a collection of discussions and notes on several legal points in the ''Even HaEzer'' and ''Orach Chayim''\n** ''Derech Chaim'' on ''Orach Chayim'' (Zolkiev, 1828; [[Altona, Hamburg|Altona]], 1831). This compendium is very popular and was frequently reprinted in the larger Hebrew prayer-books. These ''[[halachah|dinim]]'' are taken either from later exponents of the Law as contained in the works ''[[Turei Zahav]]'', ''[[Avraham Gombiner|Magen Abraham]]'', ''[[Pri Megadim]]'', etc., or from his own decisions. The sources from which he borrowed are usually indicated.\n*Other works by Rabbi Lorberbaum include:\n** ''Imrei Yosher'', includes ''Tzror HaMor'' and ''Palgei Mayim,'' commentaries on [[Song of Songs]] and [[Book of Lamentations|Lamentations]], under the general title ''Imrei Yosher'' (ib. 1815 and 1819). Rabbi Lorberbaum had intended to write commentaries on the [[Five Megillot]] also under this title.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/>\n** ''Talumos Chochmah,'' commentary on [[Ecclesiastes]] (Lemberg, 1804; Dyhernfurth, 1819)\n** ''Megillas S'tarim,'' commentary on the [[Book of Esther]]\n** ''Masei Nissim'', a commentary on the [[Pesach Haggadah]], with the text and a short compendium of the Passover ritual (''Kitzur Dinim''; Zolkiev, 1807, 1835; [[Minsk]], 1816; Dyhernfurth, 1817, and later) \n** ''Nachalas Yaakov'' ([[Breslau]], 1849), published by his cousin<ref>As stated clearly in his introduction; and not his grandson, as the Jewish Encyclopedia has it.</ref> Naphtali Z. Chachamowicz after his death, comprising sermons on the [[Parsha|Torah Portion]], [[halacha|halachic decisions]], [[responsa]], and his last will.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/> In this famous [[ethical will]] he asked that his sons devote time every day to learn at least one page of [[Gemara]].\n\n==Jewish Encyclopedia bibliography==\nThis article incorporates text from the ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'', a publication now in the [[public domain]]. The following bibliography is referred to in the ''Jewish Encyclopedia'' article:\n*[[Isaac Benjacob]], ''Otzar ha-Sefarim''\n*[[Abraham Dob Berusch Flahm]], ''Ebel Yachid'', Warsaw, 1833;\n*[[Fuenn]], ''Keneset Yisrael'', i. 554;\n*[[Julius F\u00fcrst]], ''Bibl. Jud.'' ii. 21 et seq.;\n*[[Moritz Steinschneider]], ''Cat. Bodl.'' col. 1229;\n*[[Aaron Walden]], ''Shem ha-Gedolim he-\u1e24adash'';\n*[[Joseph Zedner]], ''Cat. Hebr. Books Brit. Mus.'' p.&nbsp;304.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=55&letter=J Jacob Ben Jacob Moses of Lissa], jewishencyclopedia.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loberbaum, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:1760 births]]\n[[Category:1832 deaths]]\n[[Category:Later Acharonim]]\n[[Category:People from Leszno]]\n[[Category:Exponents of Jewish law]]\n", "text_old": "'''Yaakov ben Yaakov Moshe Lorberbaum of Lissa''' (1760-1832) (known in [[English language|English]] as '''Jacob ben Jacob Moses of Lissa''', '''Jacob Lorberbaum''' or '''Jacob Lisser''',<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\">{{JewishEncyclopedia|inline=1|article=JACOB BEN JACOB MOSES OF LISSA|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/8417-jacob-ben-jacob-moses-of-lissa|author=[[Solomon Schechter]] and [[Max Schloessinger]]|accessdate=March 14, 2012}}</ref> [[Hebrew]]: '''\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05d1\u05df \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05de\u05e9\u05d4 \u05de\u05dc\u05d9\u05e1\u05d0''') was a [[Rabbi]] and [[Posek]]. He is most commonly known as the \"Ba'al HaChavas Da'as\" or \"Ba'al HaNesivos\" for his most well-known works, or as the \"[[Leszno|Lissa]] Rav\" for the city in which he was [[Chief Rabbi]].\n\n==Biography==\nRabbi Lorberbaum was the great-grandson of the Chacham Tzvi, Rabbi [[Zvi Ashkenazi]];<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/> he was therefore related to Rabbi [[Jacob Emden]]. According to one tradition, his father, Rabbi [[Yaakov Moshe Lorberbaum|Yaakov Moshe]], died before he was born, and his relative, Rabbi Yosef Teomim, the rabbi of Bursztyn, brought him up. This accounts for the common name that both father and son share. Another tradition states that before he was born, his father fell ill, and dreamed that he would recover in the merit of the son that would be born to him. In the merit of his future son, the father took his name-to-be.<ref>\"M'Gedolei HaTorah V'HaChassidus\" (Bromberg) vol. 12 pg. 10</ref>. Yet another legend told, is that at his naming ceremony his father was preoccupied with his learning and thought they asked for his own name. He studied under Rabbi [[Meshulam Igra]].<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/>\n\nHe was head of the ''[[Beth din|Beis Din]]'' in [[Kalush, Ukraine]].<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/> In 1809, he agreed to become the Rav in [[Leszno|Lissa]] (today known as Leszno, Poland), where he enlarged his [[Yeshiva]]'s enrollment. Hundreds of scholars came to study there in the years of his leadership. Among his students were Rabbi [[Elijah Gutmacher]], Rabbi [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]], and [[Aleksander (Hasidic dynasty)|Rabbi Shraga Feivel Danziger]].\n\nAlong with Rabbi [[Akiva Eiger]] and Rabbi Eiger's son-in-law, the [[Moses Sofer|Chasam Sofer]], Rabbi Lorberbaum vehemently fought against the [[maskilim]], the reformers of the [[haskalah|Jewish Enlightenment]]. In 1822, he left Lissa and returned to Kalish, where he wrote many of his works. He lived there for ten years.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/><ref>{{cite web | first=Mark B | last=Greenspan | title=Divrei Moshe: An Introduction to Commentary 'Ma\u2019aseh Nissim' | url = http://www.oceansidejc.org/Haggadah/Haggadah-5764.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nHe was widely respected as a [[posek]], and is one of three authorities on whom Rabbi [[Shlomo Ganzfried]] based his [[posek|rulings]] in the ''[[Shlomo Ganzfried#Kitzur Shulchan Aruch|Kitzur Shulchan Aruch]]'', the well known precis of [[Halacha|Jewish law]].  Similarly, the ''[[Chochmat Adam]]'', by Rabbi [[Avraham Danzig]], was written in consultation with Rabbi Lorberbaum (as well as Rabbi [[Chaim Volozhin]]).\n\nHis status was such that it is reported that Rabbi Eiger once fainted when he was honored with an [[Torah reading#Aliyot|Aliyah]] in the lieu of Rav Yaakov. (See ''Shimusha Shel Torah'', Rabbi Meir Tzvi Bergman).\n\nRabbi Lorberbaum died in [[Stryi|Stryj]] (then in [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]]) on 25 May 1832.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/>\n\n==Works==\nReb Yaakov wrote many works of [[Torah]] on [[Talmud]] and on [[Halacha]] (Jewish law).\n \n*Works on Talmud include:\n** ''Toras Gittin,'' commentary on ''[[Shulchan Aruch]]'', ''[[Even HaEzer]],'' 119-155, and chiddushim on the Talmudic treatise [[Gittin]] ([[Frankfort-on-the-Oder]], 1813; Warsaw, 1815)\n** ''Beis Yaakov,'' commentary on ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''Even HaEzer'', 66-118, and on the Talmudic tractate [[Ketubot (Talmud)|Ketubot]] (Grubeschow, 1823)\n** ''Emes L'Yaakov'' (on [[Talmudic lore]])\n** He also published his late father's works on the Talmud, including his famous novellae to Tractate [[Keritot]]\n*Works of Halacha include:\n** ''Chavas Daas,'' commentary on ''[[Shulchan Aruch]]'', ''[[Yoreh Deah]]'', 69-201; the earlier sections of ''Yoreh Deah'' (1-68) are very briefly dealt with in the form of an introduction to the work ([[Lemberg]], 1799; [[Dyhernfurth]], 1810, and often since in editions of the ''Yoreh Deah'', as the [[Vilna]] 1894 ed.). In it the works of earlier commentators are discussed and somewhat [[pilpul|pilpulistically]] developed.\n** ''Mekor chayim,'' commentary on ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''[[Orach Chayim]]'', 429 and following, with notes on the commentaries ''[[Turei Zahav]]'' and ''[[Avraham Gombiner|Magen Avraham]]''; the second part contains chiddushim on [[Keritot]] ([[Zolkiev]], 1807; Frankfort-on-the-Oder, 1813; [[Warsaw]], 1825; Dyhernfurth, 1827)\n** ''Nesivos HaMishpat'' on ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''[[Choshen Mishpat]]'', in two parts (Dyhernfurth, Lemberg; Zolkiev, 1809, 1816; [[Sudilkov]], 1830; and often since in Lemberg editions of ''Shulchan Aruch'', ''Choshen Mishpa\u1e6d''). It is said that Nesivos HaMishpat was made famous by the strong attacks in it against the ''Ketzos HaChoshen'' of Rabbi [[Aryeh Leib Heller]].\n** ''Kehillas Yaakov,'' a collection of discussions and notes on several legal points in the ''Even HaEzer'' and ''Orach Chayim''\n** ''Derech Chaim'' on ''Orach Chayim'' (Zolkiev, 1828; [[Altona, Hamburg|Altona]], 1831). This compendium is very popular and was frequently reprinted in the larger Hebrew prayer-books. These ''[[halachah|dinim]]'' are taken either from later exponents of the Law as contained in the works ''[[Turei Zahav]]'', ''[[Avraham Gombiner|Magen Abraham]]'', ''[[Pri Megadim]]'', etc., or from his own decisions. The sources from which he borrowed are usually indicated.\n*Other works by Rabbi Lorberbaum include:\n** ''Imrei Yosher'', includes ''Tzror HaMor'' and ''Palgei Mayim,'' commentaries on [[Song of Songs]] and [[Book of Lamentations|Lamentations]], under the general title ''Imrei Yosher'' (ib. 1815 and 1819). Rabbi Lorberbaum had intended to write commentaries on the [[Five Megillot]] also under this title.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/>\n** ''Talumos Chochmah,'' commentary on [[Ecclesiastes]] (Lemberg, 1804; Dyhernfurth, 1819)\n** ''Megillas S'tarim,'' commentary on the [[Book of Esther]]\n** ''Masei Nissim'', a commentary on the [[Pesach Haggadah]], with the text and a short compendium of the Passover ritual (''Kitzur Dinim''; Zolkiev, 1807, 1835; [[Minsk]], 1816; Dyhernfurth, 1817, and later) \n** ''Nachalas Yaakov'' ([[Breslau]], 1849), published by his cousin<ref>As stated clearly in his introduction; and not his grandson, as the Jewish Encyclopedia has it.</ref> Naphtali Z. Chachamowicz after his death, comprising sermons on the [[Parsha|Torah Portion]], [[halacha|halachic decisions]], [[responsa]], and his last will.<ref name=\"Jewish Encyclopedia\"/> In this famous [[ethical will]] he asked that his sons devote time every day to learn at least one page of [[Gemara]].\n\n==Jewish Encyclopedia bibliography==\nThis article incorporates text from the ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'', a publication now in the [[public domain]]. The following bibliography is referred to in the ''Jewish Encyclopedia'' article:\n*[[Isaac Benjacob]], ''Otzar ha-Sefarim''\n*[[Abraham Dob Berusch Flahm]], ''Ebel Yachid'', Warsaw, 1833;\n*[[Fuenn]], ''Keneset Yisrael'', i. 554;\n*[[Julius F\u00fcrst]], ''Bibl. Jud.'' ii. 21 et seq.;\n*[[Moritz Steinschneider]], ''Cat. Bodl.'' col. 1229;\n*[[Aaron Walden]], ''Shem ha-Gedolim he-\u1e24adash'';\n*[[Joseph Zedner]], ''Cat. Hebr. Books Brit. Mus.'' p.&nbsp;304.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=55&letter=J Jacob Ben Jacob Moses of Lissa], jewishencyclopedia.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loberbaum, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:1760 births]]\n[[Category:1832 deaths]]\n[[Category:Later Acharonim]]\n[[Category:People from Leszno]]\n[[Category:Exponents of Jewish law]]\n", "name_user": "TRM001", "label": "safe", "comment": "syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yaakov_Lorberbaum"}
{"title_page": "Tomorrow series", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Tomorrow'' series}}\n{{Infobox book series\n| name             = ''Tomorrow'' series\n| image            = Tomorrow When The War Began Front Cover.JPG\n| caption          = ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'''s front cover\n| books            = {{Plainlist|\n*''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began]]'' (1993)\n*''[[The Dead of the Night]]'' (1994)\n*''The Third Day, the Frost'' (1995)\n*''Darkness, Be My Friend'' (1996)\n*''Burning for Revenge'' (1997)\n*''The Night is for Hunting'' (1998)\n*''The Other Side of Dawn'' (1999)\n}}\n| author           = [[John Marsden (writer)|John Marsden]]\n| title_orig       = \n| translator       =\n| illustrator      = \n| cover_artist     = \n| country          = Australia\n| language         = English\n| genre            = [[Action (fiction)|Action]], [[Adventure novel]]\n| publisher        = [[Macmillan Publishers|Pan Macmillan]] (Australia)\n| pub_date         = 1993 \u2013 1999\n| media_type       = Print ([[Hardcover]] & [[Paperback]])\n| number_of_books  = 7\n| list_books       = \n| preceded by      = \n| followed by      = The Ellie Chronicles\n}}\nThe '''''Tomorrow'' series''' is a [[Heptalogy|series of seven]] [[young adult fiction|young adult]] [[invasion literature|invasion novels]] written by [[Australian]] writer [[John Marsden (writer)|John Marsden]], detailing the invasion and occupation of Australia by a foreign power. The novels are related from the [[first-person narrative|first-person]] perspective by Ellie Linton, a teenage girl, who is part of a small band of teenagers waging a [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla]] war on the enemy soldiers in the region around their fictional home town of Wirrawee. The name of the series is derived from the title of the first book, ''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began]]''.\n\nThe books in the series were originally published from 1993\u201399, by [[Pan Macmillan]] and have been reprinted sixteen times. A sequel series, ''The Ellie Chronicles'', was later published from 2003\u201306. The follow-up series concerns itself largely with the attempts of society and the protagonist to regain a normal level of functioning in the face of the psychological damage sustained during the war.\n\nIn the original series (1993\u201399) the identity of the invading force is never specified, which is most likely by explicit intent of the author. In the sequel series (2003\u201306) the invading force is specified as a coalition of highly populous South Asian nations, who see the vast underdeveloped spaces and natural resources of Australia as a way to tackle their [[human overpopulation]] problem, and the series features multinational colonies of enemy civilians being set up in conquered territory. Few parts of the war outside Ellie's immediate perspective are covered; the reader is not informed exactly how much of the country is under enemy control, though a radio broadcast early in the series confirms that several major costal cities, and much of the inland area has been seized by the invading forces. Furthermore, how well the war is going for the [[Australian Defence Force|Australian military]] is not covered, however, it's strongly inferred that they suffer heavy losses. \n\n''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' and its sequels are one of the most popular and critically acclaimed series of novels aimed at young readers in Australian literature history.<ref name=\"publishersweekly.com\">6 August 2008 [http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6341932.html Tomorrow Series Relaunched for Today's Readers] Publishersweekly.com</ref> It has sold over 3 million copies in Australia and has been translated into five languages.<ref name=\"publishersweekly.com\"/><ref name=\"sf\">[http://www.sfsite.com/12b/tom47.htm Bibliographer Researches Australian Children's Books] [http://www.nla.gov.au/ National Library of Australia] {{ISSN|1039-3498}}, no. 58, August 2002</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Dead of the Night]]'' (1994)\n* ''The Third Day, the Frost'' (1995) <small> (published in the U.S. and Canada as ''A Killing Frost'')</small>\n* ''Darkness, Be My Friend'' (1996)\n* ''Burning for Revenge'' (1997)\n* ''The Night is for Hunting'' (1998)\n* ''The Other Side of Dawn'' (1999)\n\n==Plot summary==\nEllie goes out camping in [[the bush]] for a week with her friends Homer, Lee, Kevin, Corrie, Robyn, and Fiona. They find a way into a large, vegetated sinkhole in a remote area of bush the locals call \"Hell\", and camp there for the week. During this time they see large numbers of planes flying through the night without lights, and though it is mentioned in conversation the following morning, they think little of it.\n\nWhen they return home they find that all the people are missing and their pets and livestock are dead or dying. They come to realise that Australia has been invaded and their family and friends have been taken prisoner. Avoiding capture by enemy soldiers, as well as retrieving Robyn and Lee who were stuck in the town and picking up one of their school friends Chris, the group return to Hell. After short period of recovery they start making plans to fight back.\n\nOver the course of the first three books in the series, the group succeeds in destroying a bridge that leads into Wirrawee, an enemy convoy, several houses that are being used by the enemy as a center of operations, and a nearby strategic harbour. After the harbour raid, the surviving members of the group are eventually captured and placed in a maximum security prison in Stratton. During an air-raid by the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] the group escapes but loses yet another member while doing so. They encounter a downed RNZAF pilot and arrange to be evacuated to New Zealand.\n\nBook four, ''Darkness, Be My Friend'', takes place several months later. The group is trying to live a normal life in New Zealand with other refugees, but are haunted by their memories of the war (which is still ongoing). They are approached by the [[New Zealand Defence Force]], who are seeking Australian guerrillas to act as guides for saboteur units that are being dropped into occupied Australian territory. The group returns to Wirrawee, their hometown, accompanied by a platoon of New Zealand troops. However the New Zealanders go missing while on a mission to destroy Wirrawee Airfield (which is being used as a major military airbase). Alone behind enemy lines once more, the group decides to attack the Airfield themselves but a combination of poor planning and bad luck causes them to fail. They return, depressed, to Hell.\n\nSoon after, through sheer luck, the group find themselves perfectly positioned to attempt another attack on the Airfield. This time they succeed and manage to destroy a majority of planes on the airfield. After the attack, the group find their way to the nearby city of Stratton. There they encounter a tribe of feral (and hostile) children, who have been living on the streets and hiding from enemy troops since the war began. The group rescue five of the children who have been captured by an enemy patrol and escape back to Hell. For a time the group looks after the children. During this time strained relationships are mended and the soul-destroying effects of the war are tempered by a chance to do something positive. However, this period does not last. A patrol ambushes the group near their base and after defeating their attackers in a prolonged firefight the group realises that they are no longer safe in Hell and make contact with New Zealand immediately.\n\nThey discover that the war is entering its final days and that groups of [[partisan (military)|partisan]]s like themselves are being asked to cause as much chaos behind enemy lines as possible while New Zealand and its allies launch an all-out offensive. The group arranges for the feral children to be evacuated to New Zealand and are provided with [[plastic explosives]] to carry out their task.\n\nThe group attacks a service station frequented by enemy convoys and are separated in the aftermath. Ellie is shot in the leg and taken prisoner. While interned, she discovers the location of her mother and father. She escapes and is reunited with her mother whom she stays with until news breaks that the war is over \u2013 Australia signs a [[peace treaty]] with the occupying power, resulting in the formation of a new nation on the continent for the invading forces and settlers.\n\nIt transpires that Wirrawee is on the Australian side of the border. Ellie, her mother and her father return to their farm and, like all the other survivors of the war, begin picking up the pieces of their lives.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===The group===\n;Ellie Linton: The main protagonist and narrator of the series. Ellie was born and raised on a cattle and sheep farm not far from the edge of the country town of Wirrawee. She is loyal to her friends, to her family, she loves the Australian bush and the life on the land. Ellie prides herself on being the strongest member (and therefore one of the leaders) of the group. Nevertheless, she is often scared and uncertain of her actions and tries to hide what she perceives to be these moments of weakness from her friends.\n\n;Corrie Mackenzie: Ellie's best friend since childhood. It was Corrie who first suggested going on a camping trip into Hell. Corrie was shot and mortally wounded at the end of the first book. Corrie's death affects the group deeply, especially Ellie who eventually comes to terms with the loss in book four, ''Darkness, Be My Friend''.\n\n;Homer Yannos: Ellie's neighbour and close friend. Homer is forceful and domineering and has trouble dealing with other strong personalities. Prior to the war Homer appeared to be a wild and irresponsible boy. The war reveals him to be a strong leader. However, on occasions where he is not in control Homer reverts to his immature ways. As the war progresses he gradually relies on Ellie to get the group to safety.\n\n;Fiona Maxwell: Commonly referred to as 'Fi' by the group, she had a sheltered upbringing before the war. Fi was shown early on to be the least physically capable of the group. Despite this Fi manages to find the courage within herself to complete the tasks she has been set, though she rarely takes an active role in planning the group's attacks. Fi becomes Ellie's confidante after Corrie's departure and acts as the most rational member of the group after Robyn. She develops a slow romance with the wild Homer.\n\n;Lee Takkam: Prior to the war Lee was a studious, somewhat lonely boy. During the war Lee demonstrates an aptitude for violence, a tendency to act impulsively and a strong desire for vengeance, especially after finding out his parents were killed. He develops a relationship with Ellie.\n\n;Robyn Mathers: A friend of Ellie and Corrie's with really strong held religious beliefs. Robyn is calm under pressure and is a capable leader. She regards herself as a [[pacifist]] and refuses to participate in any activities where she will be required to directly take a life. Despite this she is convinced that what the group is doing is right and enjoys the adrenaline rush that being in dangerous situations gives her. She eventually is killed in an act of heroism in book three, \"The Third Day, The Frost\", where she blows herself up in order to kill Major Harvey once and for all.\n\n;Kevin Holmes: Corrie's boyfriend, Kevin fancies himself a tough guy but is shown to have difficulty handling high pressure situations. Kevin is separated from the group at the end of book one, ''Tomorrow, When the War Began''. When he is reunited with them again near the beginning of book three, ''Third Day, The Frost'', he is shocked to see how brutal the war has made his friends. His knowledge of explosives enables the group to successfully attack the Cobbler's Bay harbor.\n\n;Chris Lang: Prior to the war Chris was an introverted, but well liked boy. Chris was one of the few not taken prisoner when enemy forces seized Wirrawee. The group encounter him soon after returning from Hell and he decides to join with them. Although regarded as a genius by all of his friends, Chris is unable to apply that genius to the group's current situation. As the war wears on he withdraws more and more into his own head, into his world of illicit substances, depression and poetry.\n\n===Others===\n;Major Harvey:A former school deputy principal who was once in the [[Australian Army Reserve|Army Reserve]], Harvey is introduced as the leader of Harvey's Heroes, a group of adult partisans. It is later revealed that Harvey was working with the invaders and that the Harvey's Heroes organisation was established to deliver would-be resistance fighters into the hands of the invaders. As such he plays as a primary antagonist to the group.\n\n;Colonel Finley:An officer of the [[New Zealand Army]]'s [[New Zealand Intelligence Corps|Intelligence Corps]]. Finley supervised the group's recovery and well-being during their time in New Zealand, and later becomes their ''de facto'' commanding officer when the group returned to Wirrawee.\n\n;Gavin: A young deaf boy who was part of a gang of war orphans, led by a dictatorial boy called Aldo, living in Stratton since the war began. Of the children the group rescue, only Gavin had occupied a position amongst Aldo's inner circle. Being used to a position of power, Gavin immediately establishes himself as the leader of the children. He initially doesn't trust Ellie and her friends but soon comes to feel affection and respect for them.\n\n==Themes==\nIn his book ''John Marsden: Darkness, Shadow, and Light'' John Noell Moore, associate professor of English at [[The College of William & Mary]], identifies several significant themes of the series; the transition from innocence to experience; the power of the Australian landscape; understanding the past as a way of dealing with the present and preparing for the future; and writing and storytelling and how they shape identity.<ref name=DarkShadow>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=John Noell|title=John Marsden; Darkness, Shadow and Light|year=2010|publisher=Scarcrow Press|location=Blue Ridge Summit, PA, USA|isbn=9780810877436|pages=199}}</ref>\n\nThe transition from innocence to experience is shown in transformations in Ellie's thinking and her changing notions towards leadership and courage as the series progresses.<ref name=DarkShadow /> Ellie's reasons for chronicling her experiences also develop throughout the series. She starts out recording for the group who don't want to die unnoticed and forgotten and continues writing for herself to better understand her own thoughts and feelings. Later on she writes to recreate the past which has become a lost world to her and preserve the lessons that she has learnt from it.<ref name=DarkShadow /> The Australian bush becomes \"a symbol of stability in a world that seems to be disintegrating\". Its presence gives hope to the characters throughout the series.<ref name=DarkShadow />\n\nOther notable themes in the series are the role of family and friendship; sexual maturation and the conflicting worldviews of teenagers and adults.<ref name=DarkShadow />\n\n==Inspiration==\nJohn Marsden was inspired to write ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' while watching an [[ANZAC Day]] march.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}  A large number of teenagers were in attendance, paying respect to the sacrifices made by the past generations. He wondered how they might react if they were placed in the same position that their grandparents were at their age. He felt that the popular media's view of the average young person as \"illiterate, drug crazed, suicidal, alcoholic, criminal, promiscuous, a dole [[wiktionary:bludger#Noun|bludger]], or all of the above\" was wrong.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=70}} It seemed to him that like the generations before them modern teenagers would \"dig deep and find reserves of initiative, maturity, responsibility and even heroism\".{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=70}}\n\nWith ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' and its sequels Marsden set out to write an \"old fashioned adventure story\". To do this Marsden looked to the authors he had read most avidly as a teenager, thriller writers such as [[Ian Fleming]], [[Desmond Bagley]], [[John Buchan]], [[Hammond Innes]] and [[Alistair MacLean]]. He sought to emulate their approaches to timing, pacing and building tension and suspense and combine them with \"the new teenage genres, where feelings, relationships and character development were all-important.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Wardle|first=Lisa|title=John Marsden \u2013 Author Interview Series|url=http://lisa-wardle.blogspot.com.au/2011/06/john-marsden-author-interview-series.html|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Marsden|first=John|title=Write of Passage|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/write-of-passage-20100820-138mu.html#ixzz21ERVL160|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe inspiration for the rural setting of the series was what Marsden saw as the disappearance of the bush tales that he had enjoyed growing up. He had noticed that many novels for young people published in recent decades were about issues arising for families and children living in the suburbs.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}  In ''Marsden on Marsden'' he writes:\n\n:\"I\u2019ve written some of these novels myself, and I know and appreciate the need for them, but I thought it was a pity that we had gotten so far away from the bush and country novels that were popular in earlier generations, and I quite consciously set out to revive that genre.\"{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=74}}\n\nMarsden cites the works of Australian Children's Author [[Mary Grant Bruce]] as major influence on the series. In his introduction to the ''John Marsden Presents: Australian Children's Classics'' imprint of Bruce's 1940 novel ''Peter and Co'' Marsden notes the book's similarities to his series. Both are stories about groups of young people battling enemy forces intent on the invasion of Australia.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grant Bruce|first=Mary|title=Peter and Co (John Marsden Presents: Australian Children's Classics)|year=2001|publisher=Pan Australia}}</ref> Marsden states that while he didn't intentionally set out to emulate ''Peter and Co'' when he wrote ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' he does see many of his memories of the novel reflected in his work.\n\nEllie, the Tomorrow series central protagonist was modelled after the \"courageous and resourceful\" farm girl Norah from Mary Grant Bruce's Billabong series of novels.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=74}} The series follows the fortunes of the Linton family, the owners of a large cattle station in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], during first half of the 20th century. In the Tomorrow Series it is implied that Ellie is the great-granddaughter of Norah's brother Jim.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=100}} The character was also inspired by Charlotte Austin, a student who Marsden had taught and admired for her resourcefulness, honesty and \"gutsy approach to life\".{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=73}}\n\nThe character of Homer was based on a number of students from rural backgrounds that Marsden had taught. He noticed that many of these students, who at home drove cars, ploughed fields, harvested crops, worked as shearers and more, had trouble adjusting to an environment where they \"were not trusted to change a light globe or put a Band-Aid on a cut\".{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=76}} These students became frustrated and angry and their immature behaviour was the result.\n\nRobyn was modelled after Marsden's own sister, a deeply committed Christian. Marsden was inspired to write the character when he noticed that while many teenagers identified themselves as Christians this group was not represented at all in fiction written for them.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}  Chris was an approximation of Marsden himself as a teen. Though unlike Chris, Marsden never used drugs.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}\n\nWhen asked why young people related to the characters in his books, Ellie in particular, Marsden speculated that, like himself, they found their strength and self-reliance inspirational.<ref name=RollerC>{{cite web|title=''Interviews, John Marsden'' |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rollercoaster/therap/interviews/s1532838.htm|work=Rollercoaster|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> In an interview with [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s Rollercoaster website he explained what inspired him to highlight these virtues in his work:\n\n:\"I've always been attracted to strong people in real life and in fiction. As a kid I read a lot of books like ''[[The Naked Island (book)|The Naked Island]]'' about [[Russell Braddon]] and his experiences on the [[Burma-Thai railway|Burma-Thai Railway]] and ''[[The Cattle King]]'', which is the biography of [[Sidney Kidman]], and they had a profound impact on me and I read those books many times. So I think the idea of people overcoming adversity by using their own resources was strongly imprinted in me by those books, because those guys had nothing except their own strength and their own mind power. There's something noble about that.\"<ref name=RollerC />\n\n==Similarities to other John Marsden novels==\n* In Marsden's 1988 novel ''The Journey'' the main character finds a hut belonging to a dead hermit. A similar sequence occurs in ''Tomorrow, When the War Began''.\n* In ''Out of Time'' (1990) the protagonist's country, implied to be Australia, is at war with an unspecified enemy. The protagonist has a sister called Ellie.\n* An Australia type nation is invaded in John Marsden and [[Shaun Tan|Shaun Tan's]] picture book ''The Rabbits'' (1998)\n* ''Home and Away'' (2008), a picture book by John Marsden and Matt Ottley, tells the story of a family fleeing from a war-torn Australia. Their story is similar to the story of how Lee's mother came to Australia as a refugee.\n\n==Reception==\nUpon publication, the series was met with overwhelmingly positive reviews. Critics praised the series for its insightful look at a wide range of issues and suspense filled narrative. ''[[The Age]]'' proclaimed the series \"the best series for Australian teens of all time...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/books/07-the-other-side-of-dawn|title=The Tomorrow Series \u2013 Your source for everything about John Marsden's series, Tomorrow, When the War Began and the upcoming Tomorrow movies. Waiting for Tomorrow #2: The Dead of the Night! \u00bb 07 THE OTHER SIDE OF DAWN|work=Tomorrow-series.eu|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> and said \"like ancient myths the stories confront the purpose of life, death, betrayal, killing, love, hate, revenge, selfishness, sacrifice and... faith\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=knV6PwAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Darkness, Be My Friend \u2013 John Marsden \u2013 Google Books|work=Books.google.com.au|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Horn Book Magazine]]'' found the series \"riveting\" and said \"thoughtful explorations of the nature of fear, bravery and violence add depth and balance to the edge-of-the-seat-action and intense first person narration\".<ref name=\"Knoth\">{{cite journal|last=Knoth|first=Maeve Visser|title=The Dead of Night|journal=Horn Book Magazine|issn=0018-5078}}</ref> Georges T. Dodds from the SF Site described the series as \"an elevation of adventure literature to heights that are only achieved once or twice in a generation\".<ref name=Dodds2>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfsite.com/02b/tom51.htm|title=The Tomorrow Series, Part 2|last=Dodds|first=George T.|year=1998}}</ref> He praised Marsden's depictions of [[Combat stress reaction|combat stress]] and action sequences, which he found reminiscent of [[John Buchan]]'s work in ''[[The Thirty-Nine Steps]]''.<ref name=Dodds1>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfsite.com/12b/tom47.htm|title=The Tomorrow Series, Part 1|last=Dodds|first=George T.|year=1998}}</ref> ''Viewpoint'', Australia's major Young Adult fiction review journal, described the series as \"a war story told with storytelling skills that [[Alistair MacLean]] used to display\".<ref name=\"Marsden2010\">{{cite book|author=John Marsden|title=Tomorrow, When the War Began: Tomorrow 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-d_y93KxPJQC&pg=PA287|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=1 September 2010|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74262-455-6|page=287}}</ref> Gregory Maguire of the ''[[New York Times]]'' found the series to be \"intense\" and \"compulsively readable\", but criticised the books for their episodic structures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/07/19/reviews/980719.rv123835.html|work=New York Times|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nFive of the seven books in the ''Tomorrow'' series (excluding ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' and ''The Night is for Hunting'') were listed by the [[Children's Book Council of Australia]] as a notable title for older readers for its respective year of publication.<ref name=CMIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.det.wa.edu.au/education/cmis/eval/fiction/authors/at13.htm#marsden|title=Authors & Illustrators \u2013 M|work=Det.wa.edu.au|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> The first novel is recommended by the New South Wales [[Board of Studies]] as a text to be studied in English classes during Stage 5 (Years 9 and 10).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boardofstudies.nsw.edu.au/syllabus_sc/pdf_doc/fiction_film_text_support.pdf|title=Fiction, Film and other Texts: A support document for the English Years 7\u201310 Syllabus|publisher=Board of Studies|page=25|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> In 2013, ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' was voted Australia's favorite Australian book in a poll run by  ''Get Reading!'', an annual campaign run by the Australian Government to encourage Australians to read.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getreading.com.au/frequently-asked-questions/|title=Get Reading! Frequently Asked Questions|accessdate=1 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326004429/http://www.getreading.com.au/frequently-asked-questions/|archive-date=26 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"getreading.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.getreading.com.au/book_list/australias-top-100-favourite-homegrown-reads/|title=Australia\u2019s Top 100 Favourite Homegrown Reads|accessdate=1 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903224604/http://www.getreading.com.au/book_list/australias-top-100-favourite-homegrown-reads|archive-date=3 September 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe series has also received accolades from outside Australia. The [[American Library Association]] recognised ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' as one of the best young adult novels published in the United States in 1996, then again in 2000 as one of the best 100 books for teenage readers published since 1966.<ref name=\"ala1996\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/bestbooksya/1996bestbooks.cfm|title=ALA 1996 Best Books for Young Adults|year=1996|work=[[Young Adult Library Services Association]]|accessdate=21 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317142628/http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/bestbooksya/1996bestbooks.cfm|archivedate=17 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=alabestteens>{{cite web|author=Nancy Mcgilloway|url=http://home.comcast.net/~antaylor1/alabestteens.html|title=AMERICAN LIBRARY ASSOCIATION'S 100 BEST BOOKS FOR TEENS|work=Home.comcast.net|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> In 1999, ''The Third Day, The Frost'' won the [[Buxtehude Bull]], a prestigious German prize for young adult literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buxtehuder-bulle.de/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=73&lang=en|title=The Buxtehude Bull \u2013 Youth Book Award (Jugendbuchpreis) \u2013 The Winners \u2013 The Winner 2008 \u2013 Markus Zusak \u2013 Die B\u00fccherdiebin|work=Buxtehuder-bulle.de|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> In 2000, the Swedish Government arranged for the translation and distribution of ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' to every child of appropriate age in the country because it was thought the book would be enjoyed by reluctant readers.<ref name=\"judyoz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judyoz.com/ccp0-display/john-marsden-books-tomorrow-ellie-novels-australian-fiction.html|title=John Marsden Australia Author Biography and Booklist|work=The Bookshelf of Oz|accessdate=19 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===List of awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Notes\n|-\n| ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' || 1993|| \n* Winner, Australian Multicultural Children's Book Award 1994<ref name=\"contemp\">{{cite web|title=Marsden, John 1950\u2013 \u2013 Contemporary Authors, New Revision Series|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3416500092.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105234118/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3416500092.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 November 2012|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Selected, [[American Library Association]] list of Best Books for Young Adults 1996<ref name=\"ala1996\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Selected, [[American Library Association]] list of 100 Best Books for Teens 1966\u20132000<ref name=alabestteens />\n* Selected, [[American Library Association]] list of Popular Paperbacks for Young Adults 1998, Nominated 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/1998popularpaperbacks.cfm|title=ALA 1998 Popular Paperbacks for Young Adults|year=1998|work=[[Young Adult Library Services Association]]|accessdate=21 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206114830/http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/1998popularpaperbacks.cfm|archivedate=6 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/nominations.cfm|title=ALA Nominations|date=18 October 2010|work=[[American Library Association]] Young Adult Library Services Association|accessdate=21 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117042835/http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/nominations.cfm|archivedate=17 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Winner, [[The Horn Book Magazine|Fanfare Horn Book Best Book]] 1996<ref name=\"librarything\">{{cite web|title=Tomorrow When The War Began by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/112269|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Winner, Children's Yearly Best-Ever Reads (CYBER) Best Book for Older Readers 2000, 2001, 2002<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"CYBER\">{{cite web|title=Australian Children's Choice Awards|work=CMIS|url=http://www.det.wa.edu.au/education/cmis/eval/fiction/awards/aw1.htm|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Selected, [[Whitcoulls]] top 100 books, 2008 (No. 63)<ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Selected, [[COOL Award]]s (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 1995<ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Winner, KOALA (Kids Own Australian Literature Awards) 1995<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Winner, YABBA (Young Australian Best Book Award) 1995<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 1995<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Winner, [[BILBY Award]]s (Books I Love Best Yearly) 1998<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Nominated, South Carolina Book Award 1998<ref name=\"Houghton\">{{cite web|title=Tomorrow When The War Began|work=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Publishing Company|url=http://www.hmhbooks.com/catalog/titledetail.cfm?titleNumber=590906|accessdate=20 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727231957/http://www.hmhbooks.com/catalog/titledetail.cfm?titleNumber=590906|archive-date=27 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Winner, New South Wales Talking Book Award<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Voted Australia's favorite Australian book in ''Get Reading's'' Australia's Top 100 Favourite Homegrown Reads poll, 2013.<ref name=\"getreading.com.au\"/>\n\n|-\n| ''The Dead of the Night'' || 1994|| \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1995<ref name=CMIS />\n* Selected, COOL Awards (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 1998<ref name=\"librarythingdotn\">{{cite web|title=The Dead of the Night by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/112147|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''The Third Day, the Frost'' || 1995|| \n* Winner, [[Buxtehude Bull]] Prize 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomorrow-movies.com/the-books|title=The Books Tomorrow-Movies \u2013 The No. 1 Fansite for John Marsden's 'Tomorrow, When The War Began', the Tomorrow Series and the upcoming Tomorrow Movies|accessdate=20 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009141429/http://www.tomorrow-movies.com/the-books/|archive-date=9 October 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"TripAtlas\">{{cite web|url=http://tripatlas.com/Tomorrow_series|title=TripAtlas \u2013 About Tomorrow Series|work=TripAtlas|accessdate=20 October 2010}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1996<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 1998<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Selected, [[COOL Award]]s (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 1999<ref name=\"librarythingtdtf\">{{cite web|title=The Third Day, The Frost by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/358415|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Also titled ''A Killing Frost''{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n|-\n| ''Darkness, Be My Friend'' || 1996 || \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1997<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n|-\n| ''Burning for Revenge'' || 1997 || \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1998<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n* Winner, Nielsen BookData/[[Australian Booksellers Association]] Book of the Year Award 1997<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksellers.org.au/aba-awards/98-the-neilsen-bookdata-bookseller-choice-award|title=The Nielsen BookData Booksellers' Choice Award - Australian Booksellers Association|website=www.booksellers.org.au|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 1999<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n|-\n| ''The Night is for Hunting'' || 1998 ||\n* Selected, [[COOL Award]]s (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 2000<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarythingtnifh\">{{cite web|title=The Night is for Hunting (The Tomorrow Series #6) by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/358404|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 2000<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Shortlisted, Nielsen BookData/[[Australian Booksellers Association]] Book of the Year Award 1999<ref name=\"TripAtlas\" />\n|-\n| ''The Other Side of Dawn'' || 1999 || \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 2000<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n* Winner, YABBA (Young Australian Best Book Award) 2000<ref name=\"TripAtlas\" />\n|}\n\n==Sequel series: ''The Ellie Chronicles''==\nFollowing on from the ''Tomorrow'' series, Marsden released a sequel trilogy titled ''The Ellie Chronicles''; ''While I Live'' (2003), ''Incurable'' (2005), and ''Circle of Flight'' (2006). The three books detail Ellie's struggles in post-war life in Wirrawee. Ellie finds herself running the family farm after the murder of her parents, and dealing with Gavin, the deaf boy she rescued during the war. Shortly after the death of her parents, Ellie faces bankruptcy and turns to Homer's parents, Mr. and Mrs. Yannos, for help. In addition, a group called \"Liberation\", headed by the mysterious \"Scarlet Pimple\" (a play of words on \"[[The Scarlet Pimpernel]]\"), are conducting secret border raids against the new nation.\n\n==Adaptations==\n===Film===\n{{Main|Tomorrow, When the War Began (film)}}\nIn June 2009, [[Screen Australia]] announced that it would fund the development of the feature film ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'', written and directed by screenwriter [[Stuart Beattie]] (''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]], [[Collateral (film)|Collateral]], [[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]''), and produced by Andrew Mason for Ambience Entertainment, reportedly to begin production in late 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=840471|title=John Marsden book to be made into film|work=[[Nine News]]|date=22 July 2009|accessdate=28 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912012709/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=840471|archivedate=12 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3iecfa450e38f03b772d4e458e999c8f5c |title=Stuart Beattie looks to 'Tomorrow' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=15 June 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619081417/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3iecfa450e38f03b772d4e458e999c8f5c |archivedate=19 June 2009 }}</ref><ref name=screenaustralia>{{Cite news|url=http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/news_and_events/2009/mr_090616_approvals.asp|title=Screen Australia announces funding for five features including ''Wog Boy 2: Kings of Mykonos'' and ''Tomorrow When the War Began''|work=[[Screen Australia]]|date=16 June 2009|accessdate=28 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028193357/http://screenaustralia.gov.au/news_and_events/2009/mr_090616_approvals.asp|archivedate=28 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Raymond Terrace]] in the [[Hunter Region]] of [[New South Wales]], was chosen as a major location for producing the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.portstephensexaminer.com.au/news/local/news/general/terrace-on-centre-stage/1618590.aspx|title=Terrace on centre stage|work=Port Stephens Examiner|date=9 September 2009|accessdate=16 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013115504/http://www.portstephensexaminer.com.au/news/local/news/general/terrace-on-centre-stage/1618590.aspx|archive-date=13 October 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was released in Australian cinemas on 2 September 2010. Reception for the movie was mixed. Review aggregate website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 64% of critics have given the film a positive review, with an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 5.6 out of 10. Reviewers frequently cited a poor script and poor acting as flaws.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tomorrow_when_the_war_began|title=Tomorrow, When the War Began (2010)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[IGN|IGN Entertainment]]|accessdate=15 April 2011}}</ref> The film was a success in Australia but \"failed to find an international audience\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://if.com.au/2011/08/04/article/Killer-Elite-producer-Michael-Boughen-sentenced-on-tax-charges/YJYAHZVENB.html|title=UPDATED: Killer Elite producer Michael Boughen sentenced on tax charges|work=If.com.au|accessdate=22 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326085951/http://if.com.au/2011/08/04/article/Killer-Elite-producer-Michael-Boughen-sentenced-on-tax-charges/YJYAHZVENB.html|archivedate=26 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\n{{main|Tomorrow, When the War Began (TV series)}}\nA television adaption of the ''Tomorrow'' series has been produced, though the cast from the [[Tomorrow, When the War Began (film)|film adaption]] will not be reprising their roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womansday.com.au/entertainment/tv-soaps-books/tomorrow-when-the-world-began-tv-series-in-the-works-12410|title=Tomorrow when the world began TV series in the works!|author=Chloe Lal|date=1 May 2015|work=Woman's Day}}</ref> The series consists of six episodes and airs on [[ABC3]].<ref name=\"casting\">{{Cite web |url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/tomorrow-when-the-war-began-tv-series-casting-call-info/ |title=Tomorrow, When The War Began TV Series Casting Call Info |author=Nadia |date=1 May 2015 |website=The Tomorrow Series |access-date=7 June 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/tv-series-adaption-will-air-on-abc3/ |title=Tomorrow, When The War Began TV Series Adaptation Will Air on ABC3 |author=Nadia |date=13 May 2015 |website=The Tomorrow Series |access-date=7 June 2015 }}</ref> Filming took place from 14 September to 13 November 2015 in [[Melbourne]], and premiered on 23 April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=That's a wrap for Tomorrow, When The War Began - The Series!|url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/thats-a-wrap-for-tomorrow-when-the-war-began-the-series/|website=tomorrow-series.eu|accessdate=24 November 2015|date=13 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/tomorrow-war-began-series-new-trailer-air-date/|title=Tomorrow, When The War Began - The Series New Trailer & Air Date!|website=tomorrow-series.eu|accessdate=14 March 2016|date=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature |Speculative fiction }} \n* [[World War III in popular culture]]\n* ''[[How I Live Now]]''\n* ''[[Red Dawn]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Marsden|first=John|title=Marsden on Marsden|year=2000|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74334-634-1|ref=harv}}\n\n{{John Marsden}}\n\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomorrow series}}\n[[Category:Tomorrow series]]\n[[Category:Australian young adult novels]]\n[[Category:War novels]]\n[[Category:Young adult novel series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Tomorrow'' series}}\n{{Infobox book series\n| name             = ''Tomorrow'' series\n| image            = Tomorrow When The War Began Front Cover.JPG\n| caption          = ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'''s front cover\n| books            = {{Plainlist|\n*''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began]]'' (1993)\n*''[[The Dead of the Night]]'' (1994)\n*''The Third Day, the Frost'' (1995)\n*''Darkness, Be My Friend'' (1996)\n*''Burning for Revenge'' (1997)\n*''The Night is for Hunting'' (1998)\n*''The Other Side of Dawn'' (1999)\n}}\n| author           = [[John Marsden (writer)|John Marsden]]\n| title_orig       = \n| translator       =\n| illustrator      = \n| cover_artist     = \n| country          = Australia\n| language         = English\n| genre            = [[Action (fiction)|Action]], [[Adventure novel]]\n| publisher        = [[Macmillan Publishers|Pan Macmillan]] (Australia)\n| pub_date         = 1993 \u2013 1999\n| media_type       = Print ([[Hardcover]] & [[Paperback]])\n| number_of_books  = 7\n| list_books       = \n| preceded by      = \n| followed by      = The Ellie Chronicles\n}}\nThe '''''Tomorrow'' series''' is a [[Heptalogy|series of seven]] [[young adult fiction|young adult]] [[invasion literature|invasion novels]] written by [[Australian]] writer [[John Marsden (writer)|John Marsden]], detailing the invasion and occupation of Australia by a foreign power. The novels are related from the [[first-person narrative|first-person]] perspective by Ellie Linton, a teenage girl, who is part of a small band of teenagers waging a [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla]] war on the enemy soldiers in the region around their fictional home town of Wirrawee. The name of the series is derived from the title of the first book, ''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began]]''.\n\nThe books in the series were originally published from 1993\u201399, by [[Pan Macmillan]] and have been reprinted sixteen times. A sequel series, ''The Ellie Chronicles'', was later published from 2003\u201306. The follow-up series concerns itself largely with the attempts of society and the protagonist to regain a normal level of functioning in the face of the psychological damage sustained during the war.\n\nIn the original series (1993\u201399) the identity of the invading force is never specified, which is most likely by explicit intent of the author. In the sequel series (2003\u201306) the invading force is specified as a coalition of highly populous South Asian nations, who see the vast underdeveloped spaces and natural resources of Australia as a way to tackle their [[human overpopulation]] problem, and the series features multinational colonies of enemy civilians being set up in conquered territory. Few parts of the war outside Ellie's immediate perspective are covered; the reader is not informed exactly how much of the country is under enemy control, though a radio broadcast early in the series confirms that several major costal cities, and much of the inland area has been seized by the invading forces. Furthermore, how well the war is going for the [[Australian Defence Force|Australian military]] is not covered, however, it's strongly inferred that they suffer heavy losses. \n\n''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' and its sequels are one of the most popular and critically acclaimed series of novels aimed at young readers in Australian literature history.<ref name=\"publishersweekly.com\">6 August 2008 [http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6341932.html Tomorrow Series Relaunched for Today's Readers] Publishersweekly.com</ref> It has sold over 3 million copies in Australia and has been translated into five languages.<ref name=\"publishersweekly.com\"/><ref name=\"sf\">[http://www.sfsite.com/12b/tom47.htm Bibliographer Researches Australian Children's Books] [http://www.nla.gov.au/ National Library of Australia] {{ISSN|1039-3498}}, no. 58, August 2002</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Dead of the Night]]'' (1994)\n* ''The Third Day, the Frost'' (1995) <small> (published in the U.S. and Canada as ''A Killing Frost'')</small>\n* ''Darkness, Be My Friend'' (1996)\n* ''Burning for Revenge'' (1997)\n* ''The Night is for Hunting'' (1998)\n* ''The Other Side of Dawn'' (1999)\n\n==Plot summary==\nEllie goes out camping in [[the bush]] for a week with her friends Homer, Lee, Kevin, Corrie, Robyn, and Fiona. They find a way into a large, vegetated sinkhole in a remote area of bush the locals call \"Hell\", and camp there for the week. During this time they see large numbers of planes flying through the night without lights, and though it is mentioned in conversation the following morning, they think little of it.\n\nWhen they return home they find that all the people are missing and their pets and livestock are dead or dying. They come to realise that Australia has been invaded and their family and friends have been taken prisoner. Avoiding capture by enemy soldiers, as well as retrieving Robyn and Lee who were stuck in the town and picking up one of their school friends Chris, the group return to Hell. After short period of recovery they start making plans to fight back.\n\nOver the course of the first three books in the series, the group succeeds in destroying a bridge that leads into Wirrawee, an enemy convoy, several houses that are being used by the enemy as a center of operations, and a nearby strategic harbour. After the harbour raid, the surviving members of the group are eventually captured and placed in a maximum security prison in Stratton. During an air-raid by the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] the group escapes but loses yet another member while doing so. They encounter a downed RNZAF pilot and arrange to be evacuated to New Zealand.\n\nBook four, ''Darkness, Be My Friend'', takes place several months later. The group is trying to live a normal life in New Zealand with other refugees, but are haunted by their memories of the war (which is still ongoing). They are approached by the [[New Zealand Defence Force]], who are seeking Australian guerrillas to act as guides for saboteur units that are being dropped into occupied Australian territory. The group returns to Wirrawee, their hometown, accompanied by a platoon of New Zealand troops. However the New Zealanders go missing while on a mission to destroy Wirrawee Airfield (which is being used as a major military airbase). Alone behind enemy lines once more, the group decides to attack the Airfield themselves but a combination of poor planning and bad luck causes them to fail. They return, depressed, to Hell.\n\nSoon after, through sheer luck, the group find themselves perfectly positioned to attempt another attack on the Airfield. This time they succeed and manage to destroy a majority of planes on the airfield. After the attack, the group find their way to the nearby city of Stratton. There they encounter a tribe of feral (and hostile) children, who have been living on the streets and hiding from enemy troops since the war began. The group rescue five of the children who have been captured by an enemy patrol and escape back to Hell. For a time the group looks after the children. During this time strained relationships are mended and the soul-destroying effects of the war are tempered by a chance to do something positive. However, this period does not last. A patrol ambushes the group near their base and after defeating their attackers in a prolonged firefight the group realises that they are no longer safe in Hell and make contact with New Zealand immediately.\n\nThey discover that the war is entering its final days and that groups of [[partisan (military)|partisan]]s like themselves are being asked to cause as much chaos behind enemy lines as possible while New Zealand and its allies launch an all-out offensive. The group arranges for the feral children to be evacuated to New Zealand and are provided with [[plastic explosives]] to carry out their task.\n\nThe group attacks a service station frequented by enemy convoys and are separated in the aftermath. Ellie is shot in the leg and taken prisoner. While interned, she discovers the location of her mother and father. She escapes and is reunited with her mother whom she stays with until news breaks that the war is over \u2013 Australia signs a [[peace treaty]] with the occupying power, resulting in the formation of a new nation on the continent for the invading forces and settlers.\n\nIt transpires that Wirrawee is on the Australian side of the border. Ellie, her mother and her father return to their farm and, like all the other survivors of the war, begin picking up the pieces of their lives.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===The group===\n;Ellie Linton: The main protagonist and narrator of the series. Ellie was born and raised on a cattle and sheep farm not far from the edge of the country town of Wirrawee. She is loyal to her friends, to her family, she loves the Australian bush and the life on the land. Ellie prides herself on being the strongest member (and therefore one of the leaders) of the group. Nevertheless, she is often scared and uncertain of her actions and tries to hide what she perceives to be these moments of weakness from her friends.\n\n;Corrie Mackenzie: Ellie's best friend since childhood. It was Corrie who first suggested going on a camping trip into Hell. Corrie was shot and mortally wounded at the end of the first book. Corrie's death affects the group deeply, especially Ellie who eventually comes to terms with the loss in book four, ''Darkness, Be My Friend''.\n\n;Homer Yannos: Ellie's neighbour and close friend. Homer is forceful and domineering and has trouble dealing with other strong personalities. Prior to the war Homer appeared to be a wild and irresponsible boy. The war reveals him to be a strong leader. However, on occasions where he is not in control Homer reverts to his immature ways. As the war progresses he gradually relies on Ellie to get the group to safety.\n\n;Fiona Maxwell: Commonly referred to as 'Fi' by the group, she had a sheltered upbringing before the war. Fi was shown early on to be the least physically capable of the group. Despite this Fi manages to find the courage within herself to complete the tasks she has been set, though she rarely takes an active role in planning the group's attacks. Fi becomes Ellie's confidante after Corrie's departure and acts as the most rational member of the group after Robyn. She develops a slow romance with the wild Homer.\n\n;Lee Takkam: Prior to the war Lee was a studious, somewhat lonely boy. During the war Lee demonstrates an aptitude for violence, a tendency to act impulsively and a strong desire for vengeance, especially after finding out his parents were killed. He develops a relationship with Ellie.\n\n;Robyn Mathers: A friend of Ellie and Corrie's with really strong held religious beliefs. Robyn is calm under pressure and is a capable leader. She regards herself as a [[pacifist]] and refuses to participate in any activities where she will be required to directly take a life. Despite this she is convinced that what the group is doing is right and enjoys the adrenaline rush that being in dangerous situations gives her.\n\n;Kevin Holmes: Corrie's boyfriend, Kevin fancies himself a tough guy but is shown to have difficulty handling high pressure situations. Kevin is separated from the group at the end of book one, ''Tomorrow, When the War Began''. When he is reunited with them again near the beginning of book three, ''Third Day, The Frost'', he is shocked to see how brutal the war has made his friends. His knowledge of explosives enables the group to successfully attack the Cobbler's Bay harbor.\n\n;Chris Lang: Prior to the war Chris was an introverted, but well liked boy. Chris was one of the few not taken prisoner when enemy forces seized Wirrawee. The group encounter him soon after returning from Hell and he decides to join with them. Although regarded as a genius by all of his friends, Chris is unable to apply that genius to the group's current situation. As the war wears on he withdraws more and more into his own head, into his world of illicit substances, depression and poetry.\n\n===Others===\n;Major Harvey:A former school deputy principal who was once in the [[Australian Army Reserve|Army Reserve]], Harvey is introduced as the leader of Harvey's Heroes, a group of adult partisans. It is later revealed that Harvey was working with the invaders and that the Harvey's Heroes organisation was established to deliver would-be resistance fighters into the hands of the invaders. As such he plays as a primary antagonist to the group.\n\n;Colonel Finley:An officer of the [[New Zealand Army]]'s [[New Zealand Intelligence Corps|Intelligence Corps]]. Finley supervised the group's recovery and well-being during their time in New Zealand, and later becomes their ''de facto'' commanding officer when the group returned to Wirrawee.\n\n;Gavin: A young deaf boy who was part of a gang of war orphans, led by a dictatorial boy called Aldo, living in Stratton since the war began. Of the children the group rescue, only Gavin had occupied a position amongst Aldo's inner circle. Being used to a position of power, Gavin immediately establishes himself as the leader of the children. He initially doesn't trust Ellie and her friends but soon comes to feel affection and respect for them.\n\n==Themes==\nIn his book ''John Marsden: Darkness, Shadow, and Light'' John Noell Moore, associate professor of English at [[The College of William & Mary]], identifies several significant themes of the series; the transition from innocence to experience; the power of the Australian landscape; understanding the past as a way of dealing with the present and preparing for the future; and writing and storytelling and how they shape identity.<ref name=DarkShadow>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=John Noell|title=John Marsden; Darkness, Shadow and Light|year=2010|publisher=Scarcrow Press|location=Blue Ridge Summit, PA, USA|isbn=9780810877436|pages=199}}</ref>\n\nThe transition from innocence to experience is shown in transformations in Ellie's thinking and her changing notions towards leadership and courage as the series progresses.<ref name=DarkShadow /> Ellie's reasons for chronicling her experiences also develop throughout the series. She starts out recording for the group who don't want to die unnoticed and forgotten and continues writing for herself to better understand her own thoughts and feelings. Later on she writes to recreate the past which has become a lost world to her and preserve the lessons that she has learnt from it.<ref name=DarkShadow /> The Australian bush becomes \"a symbol of stability in a world that seems to be disintegrating\". Its presence gives hope to the characters throughout the series.<ref name=DarkShadow />\n\nOther notable themes in the series are the role of family and friendship; sexual maturation and the conflicting worldviews of teenagers and adults.<ref name=DarkShadow />\n\n==Inspiration==\nJohn Marsden was inspired to write ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' while watching an [[ANZAC Day]] march.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}  A large number of teenagers were in attendance, paying respect to the sacrifices made by the past generations. He wondered how they might react if they were placed in the same position that their grandparents were at their age. He felt that the popular media's view of the average young person as \"illiterate, drug crazed, suicidal, alcoholic, criminal, promiscuous, a dole [[wiktionary:bludger#Noun|bludger]], or all of the above\" was wrong.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=70}} It seemed to him that like the generations before them modern teenagers would \"dig deep and find reserves of initiative, maturity, responsibility and even heroism\".{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=70}}\n\nWith ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' and its sequels Marsden set out to write an \"old fashioned adventure story\". To do this Marsden looked to the authors he had read most avidly as a teenager, thriller writers such as [[Ian Fleming]], [[Desmond Bagley]], [[John Buchan]], [[Hammond Innes]] and [[Alistair MacLean]]. He sought to emulate their approaches to timing, pacing and building tension and suspense and combine them with \"the new teenage genres, where feelings, relationships and character development were all-important.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Wardle|first=Lisa|title=John Marsden \u2013 Author Interview Series|url=http://lisa-wardle.blogspot.com.au/2011/06/john-marsden-author-interview-series.html|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Marsden|first=John|title=Write of Passage|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/write-of-passage-20100820-138mu.html#ixzz21ERVL160|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe inspiration for the rural setting of the series was what Marsden saw as the disappearance of the bush tales that he had enjoyed growing up. He had noticed that many novels for young people published in recent decades were about issues arising for families and children living in the suburbs.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}  In ''Marsden on Marsden'' he writes:\n\n:\"I\u2019ve written some of these novels myself, and I know and appreciate the need for them, but I thought it was a pity that we had gotten so far away from the bush and country novels that were popular in earlier generations, and I quite consciously set out to revive that genre.\"{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=74}}\n\nMarsden cites the works of Australian Children's Author [[Mary Grant Bruce]] as major influence on the series. In his introduction to the ''John Marsden Presents: Australian Children's Classics'' imprint of Bruce's 1940 novel ''Peter and Co'' Marsden notes the book's similarities to his series. Both are stories about groups of young people battling enemy forces intent on the invasion of Australia.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grant Bruce|first=Mary|title=Peter and Co (John Marsden Presents: Australian Children's Classics)|year=2001|publisher=Pan Australia}}</ref> Marsden states that while he didn't intentionally set out to emulate ''Peter and Co'' when he wrote ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' he does see many of his memories of the novel reflected in his work.\n\nEllie, the Tomorrow series central protagonist was modelled after the \"courageous and resourceful\" farm girl Norah from Mary Grant Bruce's Billabong series of novels.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=74}} The series follows the fortunes of the Linton family, the owners of a large cattle station in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], during first half of the 20th century. In the Tomorrow Series it is implied that Ellie is the great-granddaughter of Norah's brother Jim.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=100}} The character was also inspired by Charlotte Austin, a student who Marsden had taught and admired for her resourcefulness, honesty and \"gutsy approach to life\".{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=73}}\n\nThe character of Homer was based on a number of students from rural backgrounds that Marsden had taught. He noticed that many of these students, who at home drove cars, ploughed fields, harvested crops, worked as shearers and more, had trouble adjusting to an environment where they \"were not trusted to change a light globe or put a Band-Aid on a cut\".{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=76}} These students became frustrated and angry and their immature behaviour was the result.\n\nRobyn was modelled after Marsden's own sister, a deeply committed Christian. Marsden was inspired to write the character when he noticed that while many teenagers identified themselves as Christians this group was not represented at all in fiction written for them.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}  Chris was an approximation of Marsden himself as a teen. Though unlike Chris, Marsden never used drugs.{{sfn|Marsden|2000|p=}}\n\nWhen asked why young people related to the characters in his books, Ellie in particular, Marsden speculated that, like himself, they found their strength and self-reliance inspirational.<ref name=RollerC>{{cite web|title=''Interviews, John Marsden'' |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rollercoaster/therap/interviews/s1532838.htm|work=Rollercoaster|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> In an interview with [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s Rollercoaster website he explained what inspired him to highlight these virtues in his work:\n\n:\"I've always been attracted to strong people in real life and in fiction. As a kid I read a lot of books like ''[[The Naked Island (book)|The Naked Island]]'' about [[Russell Braddon]] and his experiences on the [[Burma-Thai railway|Burma-Thai Railway]] and ''[[The Cattle King]]'', which is the biography of [[Sidney Kidman]], and they had a profound impact on me and I read those books many times. So I think the idea of people overcoming adversity by using their own resources was strongly imprinted in me by those books, because those guys had nothing except their own strength and their own mind power. There's something noble about that.\"<ref name=RollerC />\n\n==Similarities to other John Marsden novels==\n* In Marsden's 1988 novel ''The Journey'' the main character finds a hut belonging to a dead hermit. A similar sequence occurs in ''Tomorrow, When the War Began''.\n* In ''Out of Time'' (1990) the protagonist's country, implied to be Australia, is at war with an unspecified enemy. The protagonist has a sister called Ellie.\n* An Australia type nation is invaded in John Marsden and [[Shaun Tan|Shaun Tan's]] picture book ''The Rabbits'' (1998)\n* ''Home and Away'' (2008), a picture book by John Marsden and Matt Ottley, tells the story of a family fleeing from a war-torn Australia. Their story is similar to the story of how Lee's mother came to Australia as a refugee.\n\n==Reception==\nUpon publication, the series was met with overwhelmingly positive reviews. Critics praised the series for its insightful look at a wide range of issues and suspense filled narrative. ''[[The Age]]'' proclaimed the series \"the best series for Australian teens of all time...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/books/07-the-other-side-of-dawn|title=The Tomorrow Series \u2013 Your source for everything about John Marsden's series, Tomorrow, When the War Began and the upcoming Tomorrow movies. Waiting for Tomorrow #2: The Dead of the Night! \u00bb 07 THE OTHER SIDE OF DAWN|work=Tomorrow-series.eu|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> and said \"like ancient myths the stories confront the purpose of life, death, betrayal, killing, love, hate, revenge, selfishness, sacrifice and... faith\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=knV6PwAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Darkness, Be My Friend \u2013 John Marsden \u2013 Google Books|work=Books.google.com.au|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Horn Book Magazine]]'' found the series \"riveting\" and said \"thoughtful explorations of the nature of fear, bravery and violence add depth and balance to the edge-of-the-seat-action and intense first person narration\".<ref name=\"Knoth\">{{cite journal|last=Knoth|first=Maeve Visser|title=The Dead of Night|journal=Horn Book Magazine|issn=0018-5078}}</ref> Georges T. Dodds from the SF Site described the series as \"an elevation of adventure literature to heights that are only achieved once or twice in a generation\".<ref name=Dodds2>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfsite.com/02b/tom51.htm|title=The Tomorrow Series, Part 2|last=Dodds|first=George T.|year=1998}}</ref> He praised Marsden's depictions of [[Combat stress reaction|combat stress]] and action sequences, which he found reminiscent of [[John Buchan]]'s work in ''[[The Thirty-Nine Steps]]''.<ref name=Dodds1>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfsite.com/12b/tom47.htm|title=The Tomorrow Series, Part 1|last=Dodds|first=George T.|year=1998}}</ref> ''Viewpoint'', Australia's major Young Adult fiction review journal, described the series as \"a war story told with storytelling skills that [[Alistair MacLean]] used to display\".<ref name=\"Marsden2010\">{{cite book|author=John Marsden|title=Tomorrow, When the War Began: Tomorrow 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-d_y93KxPJQC&pg=PA287|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=1 September 2010|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74262-455-6|page=287}}</ref> Gregory Maguire of the ''[[New York Times]]'' found the series to be \"intense\" and \"compulsively readable\", but criticised the books for their episodic structures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/07/19/reviews/980719.rv123835.html|work=New York Times|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nFive of the seven books in the ''Tomorrow'' series (excluding ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' and ''The Night is for Hunting'') were listed by the [[Children's Book Council of Australia]] as a notable title for older readers for its respective year of publication.<ref name=CMIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.det.wa.edu.au/education/cmis/eval/fiction/authors/at13.htm#marsden|title=Authors & Illustrators \u2013 M|work=Det.wa.edu.au|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> The first novel is recommended by the New South Wales [[Board of Studies]] as a text to be studied in English classes during Stage 5 (Years 9 and 10).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boardofstudies.nsw.edu.au/syllabus_sc/pdf_doc/fiction_film_text_support.pdf|title=Fiction, Film and other Texts: A support document for the English Years 7\u201310 Syllabus|publisher=Board of Studies|page=25|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> In 2013, ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' was voted Australia's favorite Australian book in a poll run by  ''Get Reading!'', an annual campaign run by the Australian Government to encourage Australians to read.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getreading.com.au/frequently-asked-questions/|title=Get Reading! Frequently Asked Questions|accessdate=1 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326004429/http://www.getreading.com.au/frequently-asked-questions/|archive-date=26 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"getreading.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.getreading.com.au/book_list/australias-top-100-favourite-homegrown-reads/|title=Australia\u2019s Top 100 Favourite Homegrown Reads|accessdate=1 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903224604/http://www.getreading.com.au/book_list/australias-top-100-favourite-homegrown-reads|archive-date=3 September 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe series has also received accolades from outside Australia. The [[American Library Association]] recognised ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' as one of the best young adult novels published in the United States in 1996, then again in 2000 as one of the best 100 books for teenage readers published since 1966.<ref name=\"ala1996\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/bestbooksya/1996bestbooks.cfm|title=ALA 1996 Best Books for Young Adults|year=1996|work=[[Young Adult Library Services Association]]|accessdate=21 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317142628/http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/bestbooksya/1996bestbooks.cfm|archivedate=17 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=alabestteens>{{cite web|author=Nancy Mcgilloway|url=http://home.comcast.net/~antaylor1/alabestteens.html|title=AMERICAN LIBRARY ASSOCIATION'S 100 BEST BOOKS FOR TEENS|work=Home.comcast.net|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> In 1999, ''The Third Day, The Frost'' won the [[Buxtehude Bull]], a prestigious German prize for young adult literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buxtehuder-bulle.de/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=73&lang=en|title=The Buxtehude Bull \u2013 Youth Book Award (Jugendbuchpreis) \u2013 The Winners \u2013 The Winner 2008 \u2013 Markus Zusak \u2013 Die B\u00fccherdiebin|work=Buxtehuder-bulle.de|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> In 2000, the Swedish Government arranged for the translation and distribution of ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' to every child of appropriate age in the country because it was thought the book would be enjoyed by reluctant readers.<ref name=\"judyoz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judyoz.com/ccp0-display/john-marsden-books-tomorrow-ellie-novels-australian-fiction.html|title=John Marsden Australia Author Biography and Booklist|work=The Bookshelf of Oz|accessdate=19 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===List of awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Notes\n|-\n| ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'' || 1993|| \n* Winner, Australian Multicultural Children's Book Award 1994<ref name=\"contemp\">{{cite web|title=Marsden, John 1950\u2013 \u2013 Contemporary Authors, New Revision Series|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3416500092.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105234118/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3416500092.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 November 2012|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Selected, [[American Library Association]] list of Best Books for Young Adults 1996<ref name=\"ala1996\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Selected, [[American Library Association]] list of 100 Best Books for Teens 1966\u20132000<ref name=alabestteens />\n* Selected, [[American Library Association]] list of Popular Paperbacks for Young Adults 1998, Nominated 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/1998popularpaperbacks.cfm|title=ALA 1998 Popular Paperbacks for Young Adults|year=1998|work=[[Young Adult Library Services Association]]|accessdate=21 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206114830/http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/1998popularpaperbacks.cfm|archivedate=6 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/nominations.cfm|title=ALA Nominations|date=18 October 2010|work=[[American Library Association]] Young Adult Library Services Association|accessdate=21 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117042835/http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/yalsa/booklistsawards/popularpaperback/nominations.cfm|archivedate=17 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Winner, [[The Horn Book Magazine|Fanfare Horn Book Best Book]] 1996<ref name=\"librarything\">{{cite web|title=Tomorrow When The War Began by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/112269|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Winner, Children's Yearly Best-Ever Reads (CYBER) Best Book for Older Readers 2000, 2001, 2002<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"CYBER\">{{cite web|title=Australian Children's Choice Awards|work=CMIS|url=http://www.det.wa.edu.au/education/cmis/eval/fiction/awards/aw1.htm|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Selected, [[Whitcoulls]] top 100 books, 2008 (No. 63)<ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Selected, [[COOL Award]]s (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 1995<ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Winner, KOALA (Kids Own Australian Literature Awards) 1995<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Winner, YABBA (Young Australian Best Book Award) 1995<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 1995<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Winner, [[BILBY Award]]s (Books I Love Best Yearly) 1998<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarything\" />\n* Nominated, South Carolina Book Award 1998<ref name=\"Houghton\">{{cite web|title=Tomorrow When The War Began|work=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Publishing Company|url=http://www.hmhbooks.com/catalog/titledetail.cfm?titleNumber=590906|accessdate=20 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727231957/http://www.hmhbooks.com/catalog/titledetail.cfm?titleNumber=590906|archive-date=27 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Winner, New South Wales Talking Book Award<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Voted Australia's favorite Australian book in ''Get Reading's'' Australia's Top 100 Favourite Homegrown Reads poll, 2013.<ref name=\"getreading.com.au\"/>\n\n|-\n| ''The Dead of the Night'' || 1994|| \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1995<ref name=CMIS />\n* Selected, COOL Awards (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 1998<ref name=\"librarythingdotn\">{{cite web|title=The Dead of the Night by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/112147|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''The Third Day, the Frost'' || 1995|| \n* Winner, [[Buxtehude Bull]] Prize 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomorrow-movies.com/the-books|title=The Books Tomorrow-Movies \u2013 The No. 1 Fansite for John Marsden's 'Tomorrow, When The War Began', the Tomorrow Series and the upcoming Tomorrow Movies|accessdate=20 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009141429/http://www.tomorrow-movies.com/the-books/|archive-date=9 October 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"TripAtlas\">{{cite web|url=http://tripatlas.com/Tomorrow_series|title=TripAtlas \u2013 About Tomorrow Series|work=TripAtlas|accessdate=20 October 2010}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1996<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 1998<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Selected, [[COOL Award]]s (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 1999<ref name=\"librarythingtdtf\">{{cite web|title=The Third Day, The Frost by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/358415|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Also titled ''A Killing Frost''{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n|-\n| ''Darkness, Be My Friend'' || 1996 || \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1997<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n|-\n| ''Burning for Revenge'' || 1997 || \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 1998<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n* Winner, Nielsen BookData/[[Australian Booksellers Association]] Book of the Year Award 1997<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksellers.org.au/aba-awards/98-the-neilsen-bookdata-bookseller-choice-award|title=The Nielsen BookData Booksellers' Choice Award - Australian Booksellers Association|website=www.booksellers.org.au|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 1999<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n|-\n| ''The Night is for Hunting'' || 1998 ||\n* Selected, [[COOL Award]]s (Canberra's Own Outstanding List) 2000<ref name=\"contemp\" /><ref name=\"librarythingtnifh\">{{cite web|title=The Night is for Hunting (The Tomorrow Series #6) by John Marsden|work=Library Thing|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/358404|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n* Winner, WAYRBA (West Australian Young Readers' Books Award) 2000<ref name=\"contemp\" />\n* Shortlisted, Nielsen BookData/[[Australian Booksellers Association]] Book of the Year Award 1999<ref name=\"TripAtlas\" />\n|-\n| ''The Other Side of Dawn'' || 1999 || \n* Notable Book, [[Children's Book Council of Australia|CBCA]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Older Readers]] 2000<ref name=\"CMIS\" />\n* Winner, YABBA (Young Australian Best Book Award) 2000<ref name=\"TripAtlas\" />\n|}\n\n==Sequel series: ''The Ellie Chronicles''==\nFollowing on from the ''Tomorrow'' series, Marsden released a sequel trilogy titled ''The Ellie Chronicles''; ''While I Live'' (2003), ''Incurable'' (2005), and ''Circle of Flight'' (2006). The three books detail Ellie's struggles in post-war life in Wirrawee. Ellie finds herself running the family farm after the murder of her parents, and dealing with Gavin, the deaf boy she rescued during the war. Shortly after the death of her parents, Ellie faces bankruptcy and turns to Homer's parents, Mr. and Mrs. Yannos, for help. In addition, a group called \"Liberation\", headed by the mysterious \"Scarlet Pimple\" (a play of words on \"[[The Scarlet Pimpernel]]\"), are conducting secret border raids against the new nation.\n\n==Adaptations==\n===Film===\n{{Main|Tomorrow, When the War Began (film)}}\nIn June 2009, [[Screen Australia]] announced that it would fund the development of the feature film ''Tomorrow, When the War Began'', written and directed by screenwriter [[Stuart Beattie]] (''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]], [[Collateral (film)|Collateral]], [[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]''), and produced by Andrew Mason for Ambience Entertainment, reportedly to begin production in late 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=840471|title=John Marsden book to be made into film|work=[[Nine News]]|date=22 July 2009|accessdate=28 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912012709/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=840471|archivedate=12 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3iecfa450e38f03b772d4e458e999c8f5c |title=Stuart Beattie looks to 'Tomorrow' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=15 June 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619081417/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3iecfa450e38f03b772d4e458e999c8f5c |archivedate=19 June 2009 }}</ref><ref name=screenaustralia>{{Cite news|url=http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/news_and_events/2009/mr_090616_approvals.asp|title=Screen Australia announces funding for five features including ''Wog Boy 2: Kings of Mykonos'' and ''Tomorrow When the War Began''|work=[[Screen Australia]]|date=16 June 2009|accessdate=28 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028193357/http://screenaustralia.gov.au/news_and_events/2009/mr_090616_approvals.asp|archivedate=28 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Raymond Terrace]] in the [[Hunter Region]] of [[New South Wales]], was chosen as a major location for producing the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.portstephensexaminer.com.au/news/local/news/general/terrace-on-centre-stage/1618590.aspx|title=Terrace on centre stage|work=Port Stephens Examiner|date=9 September 2009|accessdate=16 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013115504/http://www.portstephensexaminer.com.au/news/local/news/general/terrace-on-centre-stage/1618590.aspx|archive-date=13 October 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was released in Australian cinemas on 2 September 2010. Reception for the movie was mixed. Review aggregate website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 64% of critics have given the film a positive review, with an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 5.6 out of 10. Reviewers frequently cited a poor script and poor acting as flaws.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tomorrow_when_the_war_began|title=Tomorrow, When the War Began (2010)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[IGN|IGN Entertainment]]|accessdate=15 April 2011}}</ref> The film was a success in Australia but \"failed to find an international audience\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://if.com.au/2011/08/04/article/Killer-Elite-producer-Michael-Boughen-sentenced-on-tax-charges/YJYAHZVENB.html|title=UPDATED: Killer Elite producer Michael Boughen sentenced on tax charges|work=If.com.au|accessdate=22 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326085951/http://if.com.au/2011/08/04/article/Killer-Elite-producer-Michael-Boughen-sentenced-on-tax-charges/YJYAHZVENB.html|archivedate=26 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\n{{main|Tomorrow, When the War Began (TV series)}}\nA television adaption of the ''Tomorrow'' series has been produced, though the cast from the [[Tomorrow, When the War Began (film)|film adaption]] will not be reprising their roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womansday.com.au/entertainment/tv-soaps-books/tomorrow-when-the-world-began-tv-series-in-the-works-12410|title=Tomorrow when the world began TV series in the works!|author=Chloe Lal|date=1 May 2015|work=Woman's Day}}</ref> The series consists of six episodes and airs on [[ABC3]].<ref name=\"casting\">{{Cite web |url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/tomorrow-when-the-war-began-tv-series-casting-call-info/ |title=Tomorrow, When The War Began TV Series Casting Call Info |author=Nadia |date=1 May 2015 |website=The Tomorrow Series |access-date=7 June 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/tv-series-adaption-will-air-on-abc3/ |title=Tomorrow, When The War Began TV Series Adaptation Will Air on ABC3 |author=Nadia |date=13 May 2015 |website=The Tomorrow Series |access-date=7 June 2015 }}</ref> Filming took place from 14 September to 13 November 2015 in [[Melbourne]], and premiered on 23 April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=That's a wrap for Tomorrow, When The War Began - The Series!|url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/thats-a-wrap-for-tomorrow-when-the-war-began-the-series/|website=tomorrow-series.eu|accessdate=24 November 2015|date=13 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tomorrow-series.eu/en/tomorrow-war-began-series-new-trailer-air-date/|title=Tomorrow, When The War Began - The Series New Trailer & Air Date!|website=tomorrow-series.eu|accessdate=14 March 2016|date=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature |Speculative fiction }} \n* [[World War III in popular culture]]\n* ''[[How I Live Now]]''\n* ''[[Red Dawn]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Marsden|first=John|title=Marsden on Marsden|year=2000|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74334-634-1|ref=harv}}\n\n{{John Marsden}}\n\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomorrow series}}\n[[Category:Tomorrow series]]\n[[Category:Australian young adult novels]]\n[[Category:War novels]]\n[[Category:Young adult novel series]]\n", "name_user": "Mmmmmwatchasay", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe group", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tomorrow_series"}
{"title_page": "Ainu cuisine", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{expand Japanese|\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6599\u7406|date=March 2013}}\n{{more footnotes|date=May 2012}}\n{{cleanup lang|date=May 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Ainu ohaw.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ohaw]], traditional Ainu soup]]\n'''Ainu cuisine''' is the [[cuisine]] of the ethnic [[Ainu people|Ainu]] in [[Japan]].  The cuisine differs markedly from that of the majority [[Yamato people]] of [[Japan]].  Raw meat like [[sashimi]], for example, is rarely served in Ainu cuisine, which instead uses methods such as [[boiling]], [[roasting]] and [[Curing (food preservation)|curing]] to prepare meat. Also unlike Japanese cuisine, traditional Ainu cuisine did not use [[miso]], soy sauce, or sugar, though these seasonings make an appearance in modern Ainu cuisine.<ref name=\"ipetaberu2014\">{{cite book |title=\u30a4\u30da\u98df\u3079\u308b |date=2014 |publisher=\u5317\u6d77\u9053\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u6587\u5316\u7814\u7a76\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc |url=http://www.hm.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/pon_kanpisosi3.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|30}}  The island of [[Hokkaid\u014d]] in northern Japan is where most Ainu live today; however, they once inhabited most of the [[Kuril islands]], the southern half of [[Sakhalin island]], and parts of northern Honsh\u016b Island.\n\nThere are very few Ainu restaurants in the world, though some do exist such as [[Ashiri Kotan Nakanoshima]] in [[Sapporo]], and [[Poron'no]] and [[Marukibune]] in [[Akan, Hokkaid\u014d|Ainu Kotan, Hokkaid\u014d]].\n\n==Overview==\nTraditional Ainu cuisine used meats obtained through fishing and hunting such as salmon and deer, wild plants gathered in the mountains such as ''[[cardiocrinum cordatum]]'' bulbs (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'') and [[acorn]]s, as well as various grains and potatoes obtained through farming. Another feature is its liberal use of oils as flavoring.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\">{{Cite book|title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u8a8c|last=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6587\u5316\u4fdd\u5b58\u5bfe\u7b56\u5354\u8b70\u4f1a|first=|publisher=\u7b2c\u4e00\u6cd5\u898f\u51fa\u7248|year=1970|isbn=|location=|asin=B000J9FZ8E}}</ref>{{rp|406\u2013420}}<ref name=\"shokutokokoro2003\">\u56fd\u5b66\u9662\u5927\u5b66\u65e5\u672c\u6587\u5316\u7814\u7a76\u6240 \u300e\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u98df\u3068\u3053\u3053\u308d - \u305d\u306e\u30eb\u30fc\u30c4\u3068\u884c\u65b9\u300f \u6176\u53cb\u793e\u30012003\u5e745\u6708\u3002{{ISBN|4874492339}}</ref> Due to the Ainu's reliance on local game and fauna, not all areas used all the same ingredients, instead utilizing what was most available.<ref name=\"ipetaberu2014\"/>{{rp|4}}\n\nIn addition to salt, the fats (''{{lang|ain|sum}}'') from cod, sardines, herring, shark, seal, whale (''{{lang|ain|humpesum}}),'' [[sika deer]] (''{{lang|ain|yuksum}}''), and bear (''{{lang|ain|pasum}}'') are used to flavor dishes.<ref name=\"ainurekishi1968\">{{cite book |page=98|last1=\u66f4\u79d1 |first1=\u6e90\u8535 |title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u6c11\u4fd7 |date=1968 |publisher=\u793e\u4f1a\u601d\u60f3\u793e |asin=B000JA5YH0}}</ref>{{rp|9}} Miso and soy sauce have also been used in modern times. Soup stocks may be made using kelp (''[[kombu]]''), animal bone, and dried fish. Seasoning and spices include ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'' (''[[allium ochotense]]''), berries from the Amur corktree (''[[phellodendron amurense]]''), and wavy bittercress (''[[cardamine flexuosa]]'').<ref>\u66f4\u79d1\u6e90\u8535 \u300e\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u4f1d\u8aac\u96c6\u300f \u307f\u3084\u307e\u66f8\u623f\u30011981\u5e74</ref>\n\n== Ingredients ==\n[[File:C.n.yesoensis--modified.jpg|right|thumb|''{{lang|ain|Yuk}}'', sika deer.]]\n\n[[File:2005 RUSSIA Ozernoy Gulf 0121 small.jpg|right|thumb|''{{lang|ain|Tukar}}'', seal. The Ainu of Sakhalin had various uses for its fat.]]\n\n[[File:Dolly 2.jpg|right|thumb|''{{lang|ain|Ciporkeso}}'', Japanese char. Native to Hokkaido, and a member of the Dolly Varden trout species.]]\n\n[[File:Allium ochotense, edible wild plants, Hokkaido Japan.jpg|right|thumb|Traditionally, women usually gathered wild plants such as ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}''.]]\n\n===Game===\n\nThe most predominate game animal was the sika deer.<ref name=\"\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u98df\u6587\u5316\">{{cite book |last1=\u5cb8\u4e0a |first1=\u4f38\u5553 |last2=\u6728\u539f |first2=\u4ec1\u7f8e |last3=\u845b\u91ce |first3=\u6d69\u662d |last4=\u4f50\u3005\u6728 |first4=\u53f2\u90ce |last5=\u624b\u585a |first5=\u85ab |last6=\u5409\u7530 |first6=\u7766 |title=\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u98df\u6587\u531620 |date=1995 |publisher=\u8fb2\u5c71\u6f01\u6751\u6587\u5316\u5354\u4f1a |isbn=978-4540050060 |pages=93}}</ref> Deer were hunted using poisoned arrows as well as by herding them off cliffs and gathering them from where they fell.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|337}} In the past, deer were so common and easily hunted in Hokkaid\u014d that it was said one could \u201cput the pot on the fire, then go hunting\u201d.<ref name=\"ainurekishi1968\"/>{{rp|89}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Brown bear]] (''{{lang|ain|kimun kamuy}}'')\n*[[Chipmunk]] (''{{lang|ain|ruop}}'')\n*[[Eurasian jay]] (''{{lang|ain|parkew}}'')\n*[[Eurasian tree sparrow]] (''{{lang|ain|amameciri}}'')\n*[[Ezo red fox]] (''{{lang|ain|cironnup}}'')\n*[[Hazel Grouse]] (''{{lang|ain|humiruy}}'')\n*[[Japanese marten]] (''{{lang|ain|hoinu}}'')\n*[[Mallard]] (''{{lang|ain|kopeca}}'')\n*[[Oriental turtle dove]] (''{{lang|ain|kusuyep}}'')\n*[[Rabbit]] (''{{lang|ain|isopo kamuy}}'')\n*[[Raccoon dog]] (''{{lang|ain|moyuk}}'')\n*[[Sika deer]] (''{{lang|ain|yuk}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Fish and sea creatures===\nThe Ainu fished at sea in [[dugout canoe]]s using harpoons to hunt a variety of large marine animals and used nets and fishing rods to bring in smaller creatures.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|136\u2013139}} Beached whales were particularly prized, as generally it was impossible to bring a whale in using canoes and harpoons. However, there were some instances of whaling in Funka Bay using harpoons coated with wolfsbane poison, aided by the gentle tides.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|356\u2013360}} The Ainu also used a number of tools including fishing rods, nets, traps (''{{lang|ain|uray}}''), and fishing baskets (''{{lang|ain|raomap}}'') to catch freshwater fish.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\">{{cite book |last1=\u8429\u4e2d |first1=\u7f8e\u679d |last2=\u85e4\u6751 |first2=\u4e45\u548c |last3=\u6751\u6728 |first3=\u7f8e\u5e78 |last4=\u7551\u4e95 |first4=\u671d\u5b50 |last5=\u53e4\u539f |first5=\u654f\u5f18 |title=\u805e\u304d\u66f8\u304d \u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u98df\u4e8b |date=1992 |publisher=\u8fb2\u5c71\u6f01\u6751\u6587\u5316\u5354\u4f1a |isbn=9784540920042 }}</ref>{{rp|136\u2013139}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*''[[Bathyraja]] lindbergi'' (''{{lang|ain|uttap}}'')\n*[[Capelin]] (''{{lang|ain|susam}}'')\n*[[Cod]] (''{{lang|ain|erekus}}'')\n*[[Crucian carp]] (''{{lang|ain|rampara}}'')\n*[[Dolphin]] (''{{lang|ain|tannup}}'')\n*[[Flounder]] (''{{lang|ain|samampe}}'')\n*[[Fur seal]] (''{{lang|ain|unew}}'')\n*[[dace|Japanese dace]] (''{{lang|ain|supun}}'')\n*[[Japanese fluvial sculpin]] (''{{lang|ain|cimikani}}'')\n*[[Japanese huchen]] (''{{lang|ain|ciray}}'')\n*[[Hypomesus japonicus|Japanese smelt]] (''{{lang|ain|tokikar}}'')\n*[[Masu salmon]] (''{{lang|ain|icankot}}'')\n*[[Ocean sunfish]] (''{{lang|ain|kinapo}}'')\n*[[Pacific herring]] (''{{lang|ain|heroki}}'')\n*[[Pond loach]] (''{{lang|ain|cicira}}'')\n*[[Salmon]] (''{{lang|ain|kamuycep}}'')\n*[[Saffron cod]] (''{{lang|ain|komay}}'')\n*[[Sardine]] (''{{lang|ain|iwashi}}'')\n*[[Sea Lion]] (''{{lang|ain|etaspe}}'')\n*[[Pinniped|Seal]] (''{{lang|ain|tukar}}'')\n*[[Shark]] (''{{lang|ain|same}}'')\n*[[Sturgeon]] (''{{lang|ain|yupe}}'')\n*[[Swordfish]] (''{{lang|ain|sirkap}}'')\n*[[Trout]] (''{{lang|ain|icaniw}}'')\n*[[Whitespotted char]] (''{{lang|ain|tuksis}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Gathered plants===\nWhile men were responsible for hunting and fishing, women were responsible for gathering edible plants, beginning in early spring. Tools used during gathering trips into the mountains included the ''{{lang|ain|saranip}}'' (a bag woven from the fibers of the [[Tilia japonica|Japanese lime tree]]), the ''{{lang|ain|menoko makiri}}'' (a small women's knife), ''{{lang|ain|itani}}'' (a type of digging stick), and the ''{{lang|ain|shitap}}'' (a small pick made from deer horn).<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|367\u2013374}} One of the most important mountain plants gathered in spring was the [[Siberian onion]] (''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}''), which is very similar to [[Allium tricoccum|wild leek]]s found in Canada and the United States in taste, texture, and appearance. Large quantities of ''[[cardiocrinum cordatum]]'' bulbs (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'') were gathered in summer as they were important as a preserved food.\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n'''Spring'''\n*''Anemone flaccida'' (''{{lang|ain|ohaw kina}}'' or ''{{lang|ain|pukusakina}}'')\n*[[Angelica]] (''{{lang|ain|cihue}}'')\n*[[Butterbur]] (''{{lang|ain|makayo}}'')\n*[[Pteridium aquilinum|Bracken]] (''{{lang|ain|warumbi}}'')\n*[[Cow parsnip]] (''{{lang|ain|pittok}}'')\n*[[Hog peanut]] (''{{lang|ain|eha}}'')\n*[[Petasites japonicus|Japanese butterbur]] (''{{lang|ain|korkoni}}'')\n*[[Japanese mugwort]] (''{{lang|ain|noya}}'')\n*[[Japanese spikenard]] (''{{lang|ain|cimakina}}'')\n*[[Codonopsis lanceolata|Lance asiabell]] roots (''{{lang|ain|topmuk}}'')\n*[[Allium macrostemon|Long-stamen chive]] bulbs (''{{lang|ain|mempiro}}'')\n*[[Maianthemum|Maianthemum japonicum]] (''{{lang|ain|pepero}}'')\n*[[Caltha palustris|Marsh-marigold]] roots (''{{lang|ain|pui}}'')\n*[[Ostrich fern]] (''{{lang|ain|sorma}}'')\n*[[Siberian onion]] (''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'') \n*[[Symplocarpus|''Symplocarpus renifolius'']] (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe kina}}'')\n*[[Thistle]] (''{{lang|ain|ancami}}'')\n\n'''Summer'''\n*''[[Cardiocrinum cordatum]]'' bulbs (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'')\n\n'''Fall'''\n*[[Amur cork tree]] berries (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe}}'')\n*[[Crimson glory vine]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|hat}}'')\n*[[Hardy kiwi]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|kutci}}'')\n*[[Hen-of-the-woods]] mushroom (''{{lang|ain|yuk karus}}'')\n*[[Japanese chestnut]]s (''{{lang|ain|yam}}'')\n*[[Quercus dentata|Japanese emperor oak]] acorns (''{{lang|ain|nisew}}'')\n*[[Rosa rugosa|Japanese rose]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|maw}}'')\n*[[Mushroom]] (''{{lang|ain|karus}}'')\n*[[Oak]] acorns (''{{lang|ain|pero}}'')\n*[[Walnut]]s (''{{lang|ain|neshiko}}'')\n*[[Water caltrop]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|pekampe}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Crops===\nFarming was already taking place in Hokkaid\u014d during the [[J\u014dmon period]], prior to the [[Satsumon culture|Satsumon period]] in which the Ainu culture first emerged. However, agriculture began to decline in the 12th century up until the Ainu period. This is thought to be caused by the increase in demand for dried fish and furs for trade with Honsh\u016b, leading to increased importance in hunting and fishing, rather than colder weather.<ref name=\"\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f294\"/> Cultivated crops changed over the years as new crops were introduced, such as potatoes, kabocha, and beans.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u535a\u7269\u9928 |title=\u3068\u308b |url=http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/nyumon/siryo/toru.htm |publisher=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u535a\u7269\u9928 |accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Bean]] varieties (''{{lang|ain|mame}}'')\n*[[Buckwheat]] (''{{lang|ain|soba}}'')\n*[[Foxtail millet]] (''{{lang|ain|munchiro}}'')\n*[[Japanese millet]] (''{{lang|ain|piyap}}'')\n*[[Potato]] (''{{lang|ain|imo}}'')\n*[[Proso millet]] (''{{lang|ain|menkul}}'')\n*[[Pumpkin]] (''{{lang|ain|kabocha}}'')\n*[[Turnip]] (''{{lang|ain|atane}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Primary dishes ==\n[[File:Ainu Set Meal.jpg|thumb|An Ainu-style meal with venison and mountain vegetable soup (''{{lang|ain|yuk ohaw}}''), fermented salmon liver (''{{lang|ain|mefun}}'') and rice mixed with grains.]]\n\n==={{lang|ain|Citatap}}===\n\n''{{lang|ain|Citatap}}'' translated from Ainu means \u201cthat which has been pounded\u201d. As the name suggests, ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'' is meat or fish that has been pounded in a way similar to the Japanese method [[tataki]].\n\n'''Making ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'''''<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|50\u201351}}\n\n#Salmon head, [[milt]], and remains from filleting are placed on a cutting board-like round piece of wood sliced from a tree trunk (''{{lang|ain|itatani}}''). The meat is chopped and beaten with a sharp heavy object, such as a hatchet.\n#The resulting paste is flavored with minced spring onion, ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'', or long-stamen chive.\n#Finally, the ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'' is seasoned with dried kelp and salt.\n\nOther than salmon, a variety of meats and fish are used to add flavor to ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'' such as Japanese dace, ''bathyraja lindbergi'', masu salmon, Japanese fluvial sculpin, deer, bear, tanuki, rabbit, and chipmunk. ''{{lang|ain|Citatap}}'' was well suited to the meat of older animals, as it made the tough meat easier to eat.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|108\u2013114}}\n''{{lang|ain|Citatap}}'' was primarily made in the winter, when food spoiled more slowly, and was eaten over a number of days. If the ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'' was not particularly fresh, it was formed into balls and added to soup.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|109}}\n\n==={{lang|ain|Ohaw}}===\n\n''{{lang|ain|Ohaw}}'' is soup made from boiling fish or meats with various vegetables. It may have the consistency of soup, or be more like a Japanese ''[[nabemono]]'' (hot pot) that contains a high ratio of ingredients to broth. As a hunter-gatherer society, the Ainu did not have a staple food as such, but ''{{lang|ain|ohaw}}'' was a central dish in their food culture. It is thought to be the roots of Hokkaid\u014d regional dishes such as Ishikari nabe and sanpei soup. There are no specific requirements of ingredients to use for ''{{lang|ain|ohaw}}'', but was generally made as described below.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|35\u201337}}\n# A stock is created by heating animal bone or small dried fish in water.\n# Roughly chopped meat or fish is added to the stock and cooked. Dried meat and fish require longer cooking times. The scum that results from cooking the meats is not removed, as it was thought to have medicinal properties.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|94}}\n# Root vegetables or those which required longer cooking times are added, followed by high fiber mountain vegetables, and finally leafy vegetables. The soup is allowed to cook further until all ingredients are soft.\n# The soup is flavored with animal or fish fats, a small amount of salt, and topped with ground dried kelp or dried ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}''.\n\nDifferent varieties of ''{{lang|ain|ohaw}}'' are named by their main ingredient such as ''{{lang|ain|cep ohaw}}'' (fish soup), ''{{lang|ain|kamuy ohaw}}'' (bear soup), ''{{lang|ain|kam ohaw}}'' (meat soup), and ''{{lang|ain|kina ohaw}}'' (vegetable soup). ''Anemone flaccida'' was particularly suited for use in soups and was therefore called ''{{lang|ain|ohaw kina}}'', which literally translates as \u201csoup grass\u201d.\n\n==={{lang|ain|Rataskep}}===\n\nTranslated literally, ''{{lang|ain|rataskep}}'' means \u201cmixed food\u201d. Wild vegetables and beans are stewed until soft and the liquid has evaporated, at which point the mixture is mashed and seasoned with bear or fish oils and a small amount of salt.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|40\u201344}} ''{{lang|ain|Rataskep}}'' was made as an everyday food, as well as for offerings at ceremonies, as it was considered a sacred food. There are unlimited varieties using different ingredients, below are a few examples.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|40\u201344}}\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Sikerpe kina rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Dried ''symplocarpus renifolius'' (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe kina}}'') is rehydrated in hot water, then boiled over low heat for hours until the water evaporates. It is cut into easy-to-eat pieces and seasoned with animal fat and salt.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Pukusa rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Beans are boiled until soft, at which point Siberian onion (''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'') stalks are added and cooked further, then seasoned with animal fat and salt.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Cihue rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Made from angelica (''{{lang|ain|cihue}}'') gathered in early summer. Beans are boiled until soft, then angelica is added and further boiled. Finally, it is seasoned with animal and fish fats.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Kabocha rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Beans are boiled until soft. Dried strips of pumpkin (''{{lang|ain|kabocha}}'') are rehydrated in water then boiled along with the beans. Once the pumpkin begins to break apart, the ''{{lang|ain|rataskep}}'' is seasoned with fish fats and salt and topped with berries from the Amur corktree (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe}}'').\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Cipor rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Also called ''{{lang|ain|cipor imo}}''. Potatoes (''{{lang|ain|imo}}'') are boiled with skin on. Salmon roe (''{{lang|ain|cipor}}'') is placed in a separate pot and cooked over low heat until it starts to break down. The skin is removed from the cooked potatoes and they are sliced thickly before placing into the pot with the salmon roe. Salt is added and everything is mixed well.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Nisew rataskep}}'''''\n\n:The hull is removed from acorns (''{{lang|ain|nisew}}'') which are then boiled and drained multiple times with the seed coat on to remove the bitter taste. They are then placed in water with beans and boiled together. The resulting broth is discarded. The water is replaced and the mixture is boiled further until soft, at which point corn flour is added. It is cooked to the desired consistency. Rice flour is added, the mixture is kneaded, and salt and animal fats are added for seasoning.\n\n==={{lang|ain|Sayo}}===\n\nA thin porridge made from boiling Japanese millet or rice. Generally, the grains are boiled alone, but occasionally gathered vegetables are added. Unlike other porridges in agricultural societies, ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' is not a staple food. Rather, Ainu would fill up on fatty soups and grilled meats then drink it like tea as a palate cleanser.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|37\u201339}} For that reason, ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' was made in a small dedicated pot so as to avoid mixing oils in from other dishes. Care was also taken to avoid mixing flavors when serving by using a separate ladle specifically for serving ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' (''{{lang|ain|sayo kasup}}''), rather than the usual ladle for serving soup (''{{lang|ain|kasup}}'').<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406\u2013420}} As the porridge used very little grains to make, a month's supply for one person was approximately 1.8 liters. 108 liters would provide plenty for a family of five for a year.<ref name=\"ainuonoukou1969\">{{cite book |last1=\u6797\u559c |first1=\u8302 |title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u8fb2\u8015\u6587\u5316 |date=1969 |publisher=\u6176\u53cb\u793e |asin=B000J9W90Q}}</ref>{{rp|158}}\n\nThe following are examples of {{lang|ain|sayo}} varieties.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|37\u201339}}\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Turep sayo}}'''''\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains ''{{lang|ain|on turep}}'', the fermented remains from the process of making ''cardiocrinum cordatum'' (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'') starch. The hard dried ''{{lang|ain|on turep}}'' is first ground with mortar and pestle, then rehydrated in water. The sediment is removed from the water then formed into dumplings approximately three centimeters in diameter, and cooked in the ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}''.\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains the ''cardiocrinum cordatum'' bulbs themselves is also called ''{{lang|ain|turep sayo}}''.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Irup sayo}}'''''\n\n:The starch from ''cardiocrinum cordatum'' bulbs is made into dumplings (''{{lang|ain|sito}}'') and placed in the ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}''.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Ento sayo}}'''''\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains ''[[elsholtzia ciliata]]'' (''{{lang|ain|ento}}''), a mountain plant. This type of ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' was favored for its particular aroma.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Satsirari sayo}}'''''\n\n:The [[Lees (fermentation)|lees]] (''{{lang|ain|satsirari}}'') left from the fermentation process of making rice wine (''{{lang|ain|tonoto}}'') is placed in ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}''.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Kikinni sayo}}'''''\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains bark of the [[Prunus padus|bird cherry tree]] (''{{lang|ain|kikinni}}'').\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Cipor sayo}}'''''\n:[[roe|Salmon roe]] (''{{lang|ain|cipor}}'') is boiled along with the grain porridge. Raw salmon roe was only eaten in the fall as a delicacy. During other seasons, salted and dried roe (''{{lang|ain|sat cipor}}'') was used.\n\n[[File:Ainu traditional house\u201dcise\u201d4.jpg|thumb|right|Lacquerware containers inside a traditional Ainu home (''{{lang|ain|cise}}''). These were used to present ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' or ''{{lang|ain|tonoto}}'' (a type of alcohol) to the gods at festivals.]]\n\n==={{lang|ain|Sito}}===\n\nA type of dumplings. The name ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' is derived from the Japanese ''{{lang|ain|shitogi}}'' which refers to dumplings or a paste made from grinding raw grains.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}}<ref name=\"shokutokokoro2003\"/>{{rp|150}} Traditionally, ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' were considered a luxury due to the time and effort necessary to produce the flour by grinding the grains with mortar and pestle. It was therefore not a usual everyday food, but one made as offerings for sacred days such as the Bear Festival (''{{lang|ain|iomante}}'') and Ancestors\u2019 Festival (''{{lang|ain|icarup}}'').<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|157\u2013158}}\n\nUsual ingredients were proso millet (''{{lang|ain|mankul}}''), foxtail millet (''{{lang|ain|munchiro}}''), and rice (''{{lang|ain|siamam}}''), though ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' made with proso millet were considered the correct form. Over the years, other ingredients were added such as pumpkin (''{{lang|ain|kabocha}}''), and potato (''{{lang|ain|imo}}''). Similar to the Japanese ''[[kusamochi]]'', the Ainu also made ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' which mixed in Japanese mugwort (''{{lang|ain|noya}}''). Their flavor was enjoyed as reminiscent of spring.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|378}}\n\n'''Making {{lang|ain|sito}}'''<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|44\u201345}}\n\n#Polished grains are left to soak overnight, then drained.\n#The grains are placed in a large mortar and multiple people sing while pounding the grain with large pestles (''{{lang|ain|iutaupopo}}'').\n#The resulting flour is kneaded with hot water and formed into round flat dumplings approximately 7 or 8 centimeters in diameter and 1 centimeter thick.\n#The dumplings are boiled in a large pot, taking care not to allow them to burn on the bottom of the pot.\n\n''{{lang|ain|Sito}}'' that were meant to be offerings were placed as is in ceremonial lacquerware boxes (''{{lang|ain|sintoko}}''), wooden bowls (''{{lang|ain|patci}}''), on small trays (''{{lang|ain|otcike}}''), or skewered with ''[[cornus controversa]]'' sticks and presented to the gods.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>  When meant to be eaten by people, the ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' were served with partially crushed salmon roe or a sauce made from mixing oils with dried and crushed kelp.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|125\u2013134}}\n\n''{{lang|ain|Sito}}'' has a long history. Dumplings made from foxtail millet have been found in archeological [[Satsumon culture|Satsumon]] remains discovered in [[Atsuma]].<ref name=\"\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f294\">{{cite book |last1=\u702c\u5ddd |first1=\u62d3\u90ce |title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f2 |date=2007 |publisher=\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e |isbn=978-4062584012 |page=94}}</ref> Traditional Ainu cuisine did not use steamed rice to make dumplings, as the Japanese did with [[mochi]]. The Ainu first came in contact with Japanese style mochi after the [[Edo period]] when more ethnic Japanese moved to live in the same areas as the Ainu under the land contract system.<ref name=\"ainuonoukou1969\"/>{{rp|171}}\n\n==Utensils and eating habits==\n[[File:WLA brooklynmuseum Ainu Parapasuy Spoons.jpg|thumb|left|Ainu spoons, ''parapasuy'']]\n\n[[File:PSM V33 D519 Ainu at home.jpg|thumb|right|A sketch of an Ainu meal scene by [[Isabella Bird]].]]\n\u201cMeal\u201d in Ainu is \u201c''{{lang|ain|ipe}}''\u201d. Traditionally, two meals were eaten per day, breakfast (''{{lang|ain|kunneywa ipe}}'') and dinner (''{{lang|ain|onuman ipe}}''), and a third meal, lunch (''{{lang|ain|tokes ipe}}''), was added during the [[Taisho period]]. A night meal (''{{lang|ain|kunne ipe}}'') was sometimes eaten during night fishing or other late activities.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|416}}\n\nFood was transferred from the cooking pot using a ladle (''{{lang|ain|kasup}}'') into a lacquerware bowl (''{{lang|ain|itanki}}'') for eating. These bowls were obtained through trade with the ethnic Japanese and were large enough to hold 400 ml worth of food. Chunks of meat or fish that were too large to fit in the bowl were placed on mats woven from reeds.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}} Items such as fish roasted on a spit or ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' were eaten by hand, but otherwise, most foods were eaten with chopsticks (''{{lang|ain|pasuy}}'') or spoons (''{{lang|ain|parapasuy}}''). ''{{lang|ain|Parapasuy}}'' translated literally means \u201cwide chopstick\u201d. Both spoons and chopsticks were carved from wood.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}}\n\nWhen guests were over for food, the head woman of the house would offer food and say \u201c''{{lang|ain|ipeyan}}''\u201d (please eat). The guest would express their gratitude, and, if it were a valuable meal such as bear meat, they would raise the food to their forehead in thanks before beginning. However, the family would not say anything before eating if there were no guests. Once finished, it was customary to say \u201c''{{lang|ain|hunna}}''\u201d to express their gratitude for the food.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|412}}\n\nSimilar to the ethnic Japanese, it was considered polite to eat all food that was provided. Because of this, it was considered polite to use one's finger to wipe the remaining sauce from inside the bowl and lick it. This custom is the reason for the Ainu name for the pointer finger, \u201c''{{lang|ain|itanki kem atsukep}}''\u201d, literally meaning \u201cbowl-licking finger\u201d.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}}<ref name=\"\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f294\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Kayano |first=Shigeru (\u8431\u91ce\u8302) |author-link=Shigeru Kayano |title=\u8431\u91ce\u8302\u306e\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u8a9e\u8f9e\u5178 (Kayano Shigeru no ainu go jiten) |publisher=Sanseid\u014d |year=1996}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Batchelor |first=John |title=Ainu-English-Japanese Dictionary: (including A Grammar of the Ainu Language |place=London |publisher=Methodist Publishing House |year=1905 |url=https://archive.org/details/anainuenglishja00batcgoog}}\n*{{citation|last1=Batchelor |first1=John |last2=Miyabe |first2=Kingo |title=Ainu economic plants |journal=Transactions of the Asiatic Society of Japan|year=1893 |volume=221 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RrYUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA198 |pages=198\u2013240}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|Japan|Food}}\n{{commons category|Ainu food}}\n*[http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/en/study/eng06.html Ainu Agriculture]\n*[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/hokkaido/ainu2.html Origins of Ainu]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050828185844/http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/english/english.html English site of the Ainu Museum]\n*[https://www.poronno.com/ Official site of an Ainu restaurant in Ainu Kotan, \"''Poron'no''\"] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.sh.rim.or.jp/~moshiri/marukibune/rest.html Official site of an Ainu restaurant in Ainu Kotan, \"''Marukibune by Moshiri''\"] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{cuisines}}\n\n[[Category:Ainu cuisine| ]]\n[[Category:Culture articles needing translation from Japanese Wikipedia]]\n[[Category:Cuisine by ethnicity]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{expand Japanese|\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6599\u7406|date=March 2013}}\n{{more footnotes|date=May 2012}}\n{{cleanup lang|date=May 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Ainu ohaw.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ohaw]], traditional Ainu soup]]\n'''Ainu cuisine''' is the [[cuisine]] of the ethnic [[Ainu people|Ainu]] in [[Japan]].  The cuisine differs markedly from that of the majority [[Yamato people]] of [[Japan]].  Raw meat like [[sashimi]], for example, is rarely served in Ainu cuisine, which instead uses methods such as [[boiling]], [[roasting]] and [[Curing (food preservation)|curing]] to prepare meat. Also unlike Japanese cuisine, traditional Ainu cuisine did not use [[miso]], soy sauce, or sugar, though these seasonings make an appearance in modern Ainu cuisine.<ref name=\"ipetaberu2014\">{{cite book |title=\u30a4\u30da\u98df\u3079\u308b |date=2014 |publisher=\u5317\u6d77\u9053\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u6587\u5316\u7814\u7a76\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc |url=http://www.hm.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/pon_kanpisosi3.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|30}}  The island of [[Hokkaid\u014d]] in northern Japan is where most Ainu live today; however, they once inhabited most of the [[Kuril islands]], the southern half of [[Sakhalin island]], and parts of northern Honsh\u016b Island.\n\nThere are very few Ainu restaurants in the world, though some do exist such as [[Ashiri Kotan Nakanoshima]] in [[Sapporo]], and [[Poron'no]] and [[Marukibune]] in [[Akan, Hokkaid\u014d|Ainu Kotan, Hokkaid\u014d]].\n\n==Overview==\nTraditional Ainu cuisine used meats obtained through fishing and hunting such as salmon and deer, wild plants gathered in the mountains such as ''[[cardiocrinum cordatum]]'' bulbs (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'') and [[acorn]]s, as well as various grains and potatoes obtained through farming. Another feature is its liberal use of oils as flavoring.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\">{{Cite book|title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u8a8c|last=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6587\u5316\u4fdd\u5b58\u5bfe\u7b56\u5354\u8b70\u4f1a|first=|publisher=\u7b2c\u4e00\u6cd5\u898f\u51fa\u7248|year=1970|isbn=|location=|asin=B000J9FZ8E}}</ref>{{rp|406\u2013420}}<ref name=\"shokutokokoro2003\">\u56fd\u5b66\u9662\u5927\u5b66\u65e5\u672c\u6587\u5316\u7814\u7a76\u6240 \u300e\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u98df\u3068\u3053\u3053\u308d - \u305d\u306e\u30eb\u30fc\u30c4\u3068\u884c\u65b9\u300f \u6176\u53cb\u793e\u30012003\u5e745\u6708\u3002{{ISBN|4874492339}}</ref> Due to the Ainu's reliance on local game and fauna, not all areas used all the same ingredients, instead utilizing what was most available.<ref name=\"ipetaberu2014\"/>{{rp|4}}\n\nIn addition to salt, the fats (''{{lang|ain|sum}}'') from cod, sardines, herring, shark, seal, whale (''{{lang|ain|humpesum}}),'' [[sika deer]] (''{{lang|ain|yuksum}}''), and bear (''{{lang|ain|pasum}}'') are used to flavor dishes.<ref name=\"ainurekishi1968\">{{cite book |page=98|last1=\u66f4\u79d1 |first1=\u6e90\u8535 |title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u6c11\u4fd7 |date=1968 |publisher=\u793e\u4f1a\u601d\u60f3\u793e |asin=B000JA5YH0}}</ref>{{rp|9}} Miso and soy sauce have also been used in modern times. Soup stocks may be made using kelp (''[[kombu]]''), animal bone, and dried fish. Seasoning and spices include ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'' (''[[allium ochotense]]''), berries from the Amur corktree (''[[phellodendron amurense]]''), and wavy bittercress (''[[cardamine flexuosa]]'').<ref>\u66f4\u79d1\u6e90\u8535 \u300e\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u4f1d\u8aac\u96c6\u300f \u307f\u3084\u307e\u66f8\u623f\u30011981\u5e74</ref>\n\n== Ingredients ==\n[[File:C.n.yesoensis--modified.jpg|right|thumb|''{{lang|ain|Yuk}}'', sika deer.]]\n\n[[File:2005 RUSSIA Ozernoy Gulf 0121 small.jpg|right|thumb|''{{lang|ain|Tukar}}'', seal. The Ainu of Sakhalin had various uses for its fat.]]\n\n[[File:Dolly 2.jpg|right|thumb|''{{lang|ain|Ciporkeso}}'', Japanese char. Native to Hokkaido, and a member of the Dolly Varden trout species.]]\n\n[[File:Allium ochotense, edible wild plants, Hokkaido Japan.jpg|right|thumb|Traditionally, women usually gathered wild plants such as ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}''.]]\n\n===Game===\n\nThe most predominate game animal was the sika deer.<ref name=\"\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u98df\u6587\u5316\">{{cite book |last1=\u5cb8\u4e0a |first1=\u4f38\u5553 |last2=\u6728\u539f |first2=\u4ec1\u7f8e |last3=\u845b\u91ce |first3=\u6d69\u662d |last4=\u4f50\u3005\u6728 |first4=\u53f2\u90ce |last5=\u624b\u585a |first5=\u85ab |last6=\u5409\u7530 |first6=\u7766 |title=\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u98df\u6587\u531620 |date=1995 |publisher=\u8fb2\u5c71\u6f01\u6751\u6587\u5316\u5354\u4f1a |isbn=978-4540050060 |pages=93}}</ref> Deer were hunted using poisoned arrows as well as by herding them off cliffs and gathering them from where they fell.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|337}} In the past, deer were so common and easily hunted in Hokkaid\u014d that it was said one could \u201cput the pot on the fire, then go hunting\u201d.<ref name=\"ainurekishi1968\"/>{{rp|89}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Brown bear]] (''{{lang|ain|kimun kamuy}}'')\n*[[Chipmunk]] (''{{lang|ain|ruop}}'')\n*[[Eurasian jay]] (''{{lang|ain|parkew}}'')\n*[[Eurasian tree sparrow]] (''{{lang|ain|amameciri}}'')\n*[[Ezo red fox]] (''{{lang|ain|cironnup}}'')\n*[[Hazel Grouse]] (''{{lang|ain|humiruy}}'')\n*[[Japanese marten]] (''{{lang|ain|hoinu}}'')\n*[[Mallard]] (''{{lang|ain|kopeca}}'')\n*[[Oriental turtle dove]] (''{{lang|ain|kusuyep}}'')\n*[[Rabbit]] (''{{lang|ain|isopo kamuy}}'')\n*[[Raccoon dog]] (''{{lang|ain|moyuk}}'')\n*[[Sika deer]] (''{{lang|ain|yuk}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Fish and sea creatures===\nThe Ainu fished at sea in [[dugout canoe]]s using harpoons to hunt a variety of large marine animals and used nets and fishing rods to bring in smaller creatures.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|136\u2013139}} Beached whales were particularly prized, as generally it was impossible to bring a whale in using canoes and harpoons. However, there were some instances of whaling in Funka Bay using harpoons coated with wolfsbane poison, aided by the gentle tides.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|356\u2013360}} The Ainu also used a number of tools including fishing rods, nets, traps (''{{lang|ain|uray}}''), and fishing baskets (''{{lang|ain|raomap}}'') to catch freshwater fish.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\">{{cite book |last1=\u8429\u4e2d |first1=\u7f8e\u679d |last2=\u85e4\u6751 |first2=\u4e45\u548c |last3=\u6751\u6728 |first3=\u7f8e\u5e78 |last4=\u7551\u4e95 |first4=\u671d\u5b50 |last5=\u53e4\u539f |first5=\u654f\u5f18 |title=\u805e\u304d\u66f8\u304d \u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u98df\u4e8b |date=1992 |publisher=\u8fb2\u5c71\u6f01\u6751\u6587\u5316\u5354\u4f1a |isbn=9784540920042 }}</ref>{{rp|136\u2013139}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*''[[Bathyraja]] lindbergi'' (''{{lang|ain|uttap}}'')\n*[[Capelin]] (''{{lang|ain|susam}}'')\n*[[Cod]] (''{{lang|ain|erekus}}'')\n*[[Crucian carp]] (''{{lang|ain|rampara}}'')\n*[[Dolphin]] (''{{lang|ain|tannup}}'')\n*[[Flounder]] (''{{lang|ain|samampe}}'')\n*[[Fur seal]] (''{{lang|ain|unew}}'')\n*[[dace|Japanese dace]] (''{{lang|ain|supun}}'')\n*[[Japanese fluvial sculpin]] (''{{lang|ain|cimikani}}'')\n*[[Japanese huchen]] (''{{lang|ain|ciray}}'')\n*[[Hypomesus japonicus|Japanese smelt]] (''{{lang|ain|tokikar}}'')\n*[[Masu salmon]] (''{{lang|ain|icankot}}'')\n*[[Ocean sunfish]] (''{{lang|ain|kinapo}}'')\n*[[Pacific herring]] (''{{lang|ain|heroki}}'')\n*[[Pond loach]] (''{{lang|ain|cicira}}'')\n*[[Salmon]] (''{{lang|ain|kamuycep}}'')\n*[[Saffron cod]] (''{{lang|ain|komay}}'')\n*[[Sardine]] (''{{lang|ain|iwashi}}'')\n*[[Sea Lion]] (''{{lang|ain|etaspe}}'')\n*[[Pinniped|Seal]] (''{{lang|ain|tukar}}'')\n*[[Shark]] (''{{lang|ain|same}}'')\n*[[Sturgeon]] (''{{lang|ain|yupe}}'')\n*[[Swordfish]] (''{{lang|ain|sirkap}}'')\n*[[Trout]] (''{{lang|ain|icaniw}}'')\n*[[Whitespotted char]] (''{{lang|ain|tuksis}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Gathered plants===\nWhile men were responsible for hunting and fishing, women were responsible for gathering edible plants, beginning in early spring. Tools used during gathering trips into the mountains included the ''{{lang|ain|saranip}}'' (a bag woven from the fibers of the [[Tilia japonica|Japanese lime tree]]), the ''{{lang|ain|menoko makiri}}'' (a small women's knife), ''{{lang|ain|itani}}'' (a type of digging stick), and the ''{{lang|ain|shitap}}'' (a small pick made from deer horn).<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|367\u2013374}} One of the most important mountain plants gathered in spring was the [[Siberian onion]] (''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}''), which is very similar to [[Allium tricoccum|wild leek]]s found in Canada and the United States in taste, texture, and appearance. Large quantities of ''[[cardiocrinum cordatum]]'' bulbs (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'') were gathered in summer as they were important as a preserved food.\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n'''Spring'''\n*''Anemone flaccida'' (''{{lang|ain|ohaw kina}}'' or ''{{lang|ain|pukusakina}}'')\n*[[Angelica]] (''{{lang|ain|cihue}}'')\n*[[Butterbur]] (''{{lang|ain|makayo}}'')\n*[[Pteridium aquilinum|Bracken]] (''{{lang|ain|warumbi}}'')\n*[[Cow parsnip]] (''{{lang|ain|pittok}}'')\n*[[Hog peanut]] (''{{lang|ain|eha}}'')\n*[[Petasites japonicus|Japanese butterbur]] (''{{lang|ain|korkoni}}'')\n*[[Japanese mugwort]] (''{{lang|ain|noya}}'')\n*[[Japanese spikenard]] (''{{lang|ain|cimakina}}'')\n*[[Codonopsis lanceolata|Lance asiabell]] roots (''{{lang|ain|topmuk}}'')\n*[[Allium macrostemon|Long-stamen chive]] bulbs (''{{lang|ain|mempiro}}'')\n*[[Maianthemum|Maianthemum japonicum]] (''{{lang|ain|pepero}}'')\n*[[Caltha palustris|Marsh-marigold]] roots (''{{lang|ain|pui}}'')\n*[[Ostrich fern]] (''{{lang|ain|sorma}}'')\n*[[Siberian onion]] (''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'') \n*[[Symplocarpus|''Symplocarpus renifolius'']] (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe kina}}'')\n*[[Thistle]] (''{{lang|ain|ancami}}'')\n\n'''Summer'''\n*''[[Cardiocrinum cordatum]]'' bulbs (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'')\n\n'''Fall'''\n*[[Amur cork tree]] berries (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe}}'')\n*[[Crimson glory vine]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|hat}}'')\n*[[Hardy kiwi]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|kutci}}'')\n*[[Hen-of-the-woods]] mushroom (''{{lang|ain|yuk karus}}'')\n*[[Japanese chestnut]]s (''{{lang|ain|yam}}'')\n*[[Quercus dentata|Japanese emperor oak]] acorns (''{{lang|ain|nisew}}'')\n*[[Rosa rugosa|Japanese rose]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|maw}}'')\n*[[Mushroom]] (''{{lang|ain|karus}}'')\n*[[Oak]] acorns (''{{lang|ain|pero}}'')\n*[[Walnut]]s (''{{lang|ain|neshiko}}'')\n*[[Water caltrop]] fruit (''{{lang|ain|pekampe}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Crops===\nFarming was already taking place in Hokkaid\u014d during the [[J\u014dmon period]], prior to the [[Satsumon culture|Satsumon period]] in which the Ainu culture first emerged. However, agriculture began to decline in the 12th century up until the Ainu period. This is thought to be caused by the increase in demand for dried fish and furs for trade with Honsh\u016b, leading to increased importance in hunting and fishing, rather than colder weather.<ref name=\"\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f294\"/> Cultivated crops changed over the years as new crops were introduced, such as potatoes, kabocha, and beans.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u535a\u7269\u9928 |title=\u3068\u308b |url=http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/nyumon/siryo/toru.htm |publisher=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u6c11\u65cf\u535a\u7269\u9928 |accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Bean]] varieties (''{{lang|ain|mame}}'')\n*[[Buckwheat]] (''{{lang|ain|soba}}'')\n*[[Foxtail millet]] (''{{lang|ain|munchiro}}'')\n*[[Japanese millet]] (''{{lang|ain|piyap}}'')\n*[[Potato]] (''{{lang|ain|imo}}'')\n*[[Proso millet]] (''{{lang|ain|menkul}}'')\n*[[Pumpkin]] (''{{lang|ain|kabocha}}'')\n*[[Turnip]] (''{{lang|ain|atane}}'')\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Primary dishes ==\n[[File:Ainu Set Meal.jpg|thumb|An Ainu-style meal with venison and mountain vegetable soup (''{{lang|ain|yuk ohaw}}''), fermented salmon liver (''{{lang|ain|mefun}}'') and rice mixed with grains.]]\n\n==={{lang|ain|Citatap}}===\n\n''{{lang|ain|Citatap}}'' translated from Ainu means \u201cthat which has been pounded\u201d. As the name suggests, ''{{lang|ain|citatep}}'' is meat or fish that has been pounded in a way similar to the Japanese method [[tataki]].\n\n'''Making ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'''''<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|50\u201351}}\n\n#Salmon head, [[milt]], and remains from filleting are placed on a cutting board-like round piece of wood sliced from a tree trunk (''{{lang|ain|itatani}}''). The meat is chopped and beaten with a sharp heavy object, such as a hatchet.\n#The resulting paste is flavored with minced spring onion, ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'', or long-stamen chive.\n#Finally, the ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'' is seasoned with dried kelp and salt.\n\nOther than salmon, a variety of meats and fish are used to add flavor to ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'' such as Japanese dace, ''bathyraja lindbergi'', masu salmon, Japanese fluvial sculpin, deer, bear, tanuki, rabbit, and chipmunk. ''{{lang|ain|Citatap}}'' was well suited to the meat of older animals, as it made the tough meat easier to eat.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|108\u2013114}}\n''{{lang|ain|Citatap}}'' was primarily made in the winter, when food spoiled more slowly, and was eaten over a number of days. If the ''{{lang|ain|citatap}}'' was not particularly fresh, it was formed into balls and added to soup.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|109}}\n\n==={{lang|ain|Ohaw}}===\n\n''{{lang|ain|Ohaw}}'' is soup made from boiling fish or meats with various vegetables. It may have the consistency of soup, or be more like a Japanese ''[[nabemono]]'' (hot pot) that contains a high ratio of ingredients to broth. As a hunter-gatherer society, the Ainu did not have a staple food as such, but ''{{lang|ain|ohaw}}'' was a central dish in their food culture. It is thought to be the roots of Hokkaid\u014d regional dishes such as Ishikari nabe and sanpei soup. There are no specific requirements of ingredients to use for ''{{lang|ain|ohaw}}'', but was generally made as described below.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|35\u201337}}\n# A stock is created by heating animal bone or small dried fish in water.\n# Roughly chopped meat or fish is added to the stock and cooked. Dried meat and fish require longer cooking times. The scum that results from cooking the meats is not removed, as it was thought to have medicinal properties.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|94}}\n# Root vegetables or those which required longer cooking times are added, followed by high fiber mountain vegetables, and finally leafy vegetables. The soup is allowed to cook further until all ingredients are soft.\n# The soup is flavored with animal or fish fats, a small amount of salt, and topped with ground dried kelp or dried ''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}''.\n\nDifferent varieties of ''{{lang|ain|ohaw}}'' are named by their main ingredient such as ''{{lang|ain|cep ohaw}}'' (fish soup), ''{{lang|ain|kamuy ohaw}}'' (bear soup), ''{{lang|ain|kam ohaw}}'' (meat soup), and ''{{lang|ain|kina ohaw}}'' (vegetable soup). ''Anemone flaccida'' was particularly suited for use in soups and was therefore called ''{{lang|ain|ohaw kina}}'', which literally translates as \u201csoup grass\u201d.\n\n==={{lang|ain|Rataskep}}===\n\nTranslated literally, ''{{lang|ain|rataskep}}'' means \u201cmixed food\u201d. Wild vegetables and beans are stewed until soft and the liquid has evaporated, at which point the mixture is mashed and seasoned with bear or fish oils and a small amount of salt.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|40\u201344}} ''{{lang|ain|Rataskep}}'' was made as an everyday food, as well as for offerings at ceremonies, as it was considered a sacred food. There are unlimited varieties using different ingredients, below are a few examples.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|40\u201344}}\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Sikerpe kina rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Dried ''symplocarpus renifolius'' (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe kina}}'') is rehydrated in hot water, then boiled over low heat for hours until the water evaporates. It is cut into easy-to-eat pieces and seasoned with animal fat and salt.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Pukusa rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Beans are boiled until soft, at which point Siberian onion (''{{lang|ain|pukusa}}'') stalks are added and cooked further, then seasoned with animal fat and salt.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Cihue rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Made from angelica (''{{lang|ain|cihue}}'') gathered in early summer. Beans are boiled until soft, then angelica is added and further boiled. Finally, it is seasoned with animal and fish fats.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Kabocha rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Beans are boiled until soft. Dried strips of pumpkin (''{{lang|ain|kabocha}}'') are rehydrated in water then boiled along with the beans. Once the pumpkin begins to break apart, the ''{{lang|ain|rataskep}}'' is seasoned with fish fats and salt and topped with berries from the Amur corktree (''{{lang|ain|sikerpe}}'').\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Cipor rataskep}}'''''\n\n:Also called ''{{lang|ain|cipor imo}}''. Potatoes (''{{lang|ain|imo}}'') are boiled with skin on. Salmon roe (''{{lang|ain|cipor}}'') is placed in a separate pot and cooked over low heat until it starts to break down. The skin is removed from the cooked potatoes and they are sliced thickly before placing into the pot with the salmon roe. Salt is added and everything is mixed well.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Nisew rataskep}}'''''\n\n:The hull is removed from acorns (''{{lang|ain|nisew}}'') which are then boiled and drained multiple times with the seed coat on to remove the bitter taste. They are then placed in water with beans and boiled together. The resulting broth is discarded. The water is replaced and the mixture is boiled further until soft, at which point corn flour is added. It is cooked to the desired consistency. Rice flour is added, the mixture is kneaded, and salt and animal fats are added for seasoning.\n\n==={{lang|ain|Sayo}}===\n\nA thin porridge made from boiling Japanese millet or rice. Generally, the grains are boiled alone, but occasionally gathered vegetables are added. Unlike other porridges in agricultural societies, ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' is not a staple food. Rather, Ainu would fill up on fatty soups and grilled meats then drink it like tea as a palate cleanser.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|37\u201339}} For that reason, ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' was made in a small dedicated pot so as to avoid mixing oils in from other dishes. Care was also taken to avoid mixing flavors when serving by using a separate ladle specifically for serving ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' (''{{lang|ain|sayo kasup}}''), rather than the usual ladle for serving soup (''{{lang|ain|kasup}}'').<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406\u2013420}} As the porridge used very little grains to make, a month's supply for one person was approximately 1.8 liters. 108 liters would provide plenty for a family of five for a year.<ref name=\"ainuonoukou1969\">{{cite book |last1=\u6797\u559c |first1=\u8302 |title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u8fb2\u8015\u6587\u5316 |date=1969 |publisher=\u6176\u53cb\u793e |asin=B000J9W90Q}}</ref>{{rp|158}}\n\nThe following are examples of {{lang|ain|sayo}} varieties.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|37\u201339}}\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Turep sayo}}'''''\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains ''{{lang|ain|on turep}}'', the fermented remains from the process of making ''cardiocrinum cordatum'' (''{{lang|ain|turep}}'') starch. The hard dried ''{{lang|ain|on turep}}'' is first ground with mortar and pestle, then rehydrated in water. The sediment is removed from the water then formed into dumplings approximately three centimeters in diameter, and cooked in the ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}''.\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains the ''cardiocrinum cordatum'' bulbs themselves is also called ''{{lang|ain|turep sayo}}''.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Irup sayo}}'''''\n\n:The starch from ''cardiocrinum cordatum'' bulbs is made into dumplings (''{{lang|ain|sito}}'') and placed in the ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}''.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Ento sayo}}'''''\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains ''[[elsholtzia ciliata]]'' (''{{lang|ain|ento}}''), a mountain plant. This type of ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}'' was favored for its particular aroma.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Satsirari sayo}}'''''\n\n:The [[Lees (fermentation)|lees]] (''{{lang|ain|satsirari}}'') left from the fermentation process of making rice wine (''{{lang|ain|tonoto}}'') is placed in ''{{lang|ain|sayo}}''.\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Kikinni sayo}}'''''\n\n:''{{lang|ain|Sayo}}'' which contains bark of the [[Prunus padus|bird cherry tree]] (''{{lang|ain|kikinni}}'').\n\n'''''{{lang|ain|Cipor sayo}}'''''\n:[[roe|Salmon roe]] (''{{lang|ain|cipor}}'') is boiled along with the grain porridge. Raw salmon roe was only eaten in the fall as a delicacy. During other seasons, salted and dried roe (''{{lang|ain|sat cipor}}'') was used.\n\n[[File:Ainu traditional house\u201dcise\u201d4.jpg|thumb|right|Lacquerware containers inside a traditional Ainu home (''{{lang|ain|cise}}''). These were used to present ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' or ''{{lang|ain|tonoto}}'' (a type of alcohol) to the gods at festivals.]]\n\n==={{lang|ain|Sito}}===\n\nA type of dumplings. The name ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' is derived from the Japanese ''{{lang|ain|shitogi}}'' which refers to dumplings or a paste made from grinding raw grains.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}}<ref name=\"shokutokokoro2003\"/>{{rp|150}} Traditionally, ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' were considered a luxury due to the time and effort necessary to produce the flour by grinding the grains with mortar and pestle. It was therefore not a usual everyday food, but one made as offerings for sacred days such as the Bear Festival (''{{lang|ain|iomante}}'') and Ancestors\u2019 Festival (''{{lang|ain|icarup}}'').<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|157\u2013158}}\n\nUsual ingredients were proso millet (''{{lang|ain|mankul}}''), foxtail millet (''{{lang|ain|munchiro}}''), and rice (''{{lang|ain|siamam}}''), though ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' made with proso millet were considered the correct form. Over the years, other ingredients were added such as pumpkin (''{{lang|ain|kabocha}}''), and potato (''{{lang|ain|imo}}''). Similar to the Japanese ''[[kusamochi]]'', the Ainu also made ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' which mixed in Japanese mugwort (''{{lang|ain|noya}}''). Their flavor was enjoyed as reminiscent of spring.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|378}}\n\n'''Making {{lang|ain|sito}}'''<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|44\u201345}}\n\n#Polished grains are left to soak overnight, then drained.\n#The grains are placed in a large mortar and multiple people sing while pounding the grain with large pestles (''{{lang|ain|iutaupopo}}'').\n#The resulting flour is kneaded with hot water and formed into round flat dumplings approximately 7 or 8 centimeters in diameter and 1 centimeter thick.\n#The dumplings are boiled in a large pot, taking care not to allow them to burn on the bottom of the pot.\n\n''{{lang|ain|Sito}}'' that were meant to be offerings were placed as is in ceremonial lacquerware boxes (''{{lang|ain|sintoko}}''), wooden bowls (''{{lang|ain|patci}}''), on small trays (''{{lang|ain|otcike}}''), or skewered with ''[[cornus controversa]]'' sticks and presented to the gods.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>  When meant to be eaten by people, the ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' were served with partially crushed salmon roe or a sauce made from mixing oils with dried and crushed kelp.<ref name=\"ainunoshokuji1992\"/>{{rp|125\u2013134}}\n\n''{{lang|ain|Sito}}'' has a long history. Dumplings made from foxtail millet have been found in archeological [[Satsumon culture|Satsumon]] remains discovered in [[Atsuma]].<ref name=\"\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f294\">{{cite book |last1=\u702c\u5ddd |first1=\u62d3\u90ce |title=\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f2 |date=2007 |publisher=\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e |isbn=978-4062584012 |page=94}}</ref> Traditional Ainu cuisine did not use steamed rice to make dumplings, as the Japanese did with [[mochi]]. The Ainu first came in contact with Japanese style mochi after the [[Edo period]] when more ethnic Japanese moved to live in the same areas as the Ainu under the land contract system.<ref name=\"ainuonoukou1969\"/>{{rp|171}}\n\n==Utensils and eating habits==\n[[File:WLA brooklynmuseum Ainu Parapasuy Spoons.jpg|thumb|left|Ainu spoons, ''parapasuy'']]\n\n[[File:PSM V33 D519 Ainu at home.jpg|thumb|right|A sketch of an Ainu meal scene by [[Isabella Bird]].]]\n\u201cMeal\u201d in Ainu is \u201c''{{lang|ain|ipe}}''\u201d. Traditionally, two meals were eaten per day, breakfast (''{{lang|ain|kunneywa ipe}}'') and dinner (''{{lang|ain|onuman ipe}}''), and a third meal, lunch (''{{lang|ain|tokes ipe}}''), was added during the [[Taisho period]]. A night meal (''{{lang|ain|kunne ipe}}'') was sometimes eaten during night fishing or other late activities.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|416}}\n\nFood was transferred from the cooking pot using a ladle (''{{lang|ain|kasup}}'') into a lacquerware bowl (''{{lang|ain|itanki}}'') for eating. These bowls were obtained through trade with the ethnic Japanese and were large enough to hold 400 ml worth of food. Chunks of meat or fish that were too large to fit in the bowl were placed on mats woven from reeds.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}} Items such as fish roasted on a spit or ''{{lang|ain|sito}}'' were eaten by hand, but otherwise, most foods were eaten with chopsticks (''{{lang|ain|pasuy}}'') or spoons (''{{lang|ain|parapasuy}}''). ''{{lang|ain|Parapasuy}}'' translated literally means \u201cwide chopstick\u201d. Both spoons and chopsticks were carved from wood.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}}\n\nWhen guests were over for food, the head woman of the house would offer food and say \u201c''{{lang|ain|ipeyan}}''\u201d (please eat). The guest would express their gratitude, and, if it were a valuable meal such as bear meat, they would raise the food to their forehead in thanks before beginning. However, the family would not say anything before eating if there were no guests. Once finished, it was customary to say \u201c''{{lang|ain|hunna}}''\u201d to express their gratitude for the food.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|412}}\n\nSimilar to the ethnic Japanese, it was considered polite to eat all food that was provided. Because of this, it was considered polite to use one's finger to wipe the remaining sauce from inside the bowl and lick it. This custom is the reason for the Ainu name for the pointer finger, \u201c''{{lang|ain|itanki kem atsukep}}''\u201d, literally meaning \u201cbowl-licking finger\u201d.<ref name=\"ainuminzokushi1970\"/>{{rp|406-420}}<ref name=\"\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u306e\u6b74\u53f294\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Kayano |first=Shigeru (\u8431\u91ce\u8302) |author-link=Shigeru Kayano |title=\u8431\u91ce\u8302\u306e\u30a2\u30a4\u30cc\u8a9e\u8f9e\u5178 (Kayano Shigeru no ainu go jiten) |publisher=Sanseid\u014d |year=1996}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Batchelor |first=John |title=Ainu-English-Japanese Dictionary: (including A Grammar of the Ainu Language |place=London |publisher=Methodist Publishing House |year=1905 |url=https://archive.org/details/anainuenglishja00batcgoog}}\n*{{citation|last1=Batchelor |first1=John |last2=Miyabe |first2=Kingo |title=Ainu economic plants |journal=Transactions of the Asiatic Society of Japan|year=1893 |volume=221 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RrYUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA198 |pages=198\u2013240}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|Japan|Food}}\n{{commons category|Ainu food}}\n*[http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/en/study/eng06.html Ainu Agriculture]\n*[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/hokkaido/ainu2.html Origins of Ainu]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050828185844/http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/english/english.html English site of the Ainu Museum]\n*[https://www.poronno.com/ Official site of an Ainu restaurant in Ainu Kotan, \"''Poron'no''\"] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.sh.rim.or.jp/~moshiri/marukibune/rest.html Official site of an Ainu restaurant in Ainu Kotan, \"''Marukibune by Moshiri''\"] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{cuisines}}\n\n[[Category:Ainu cuisine| ]]\n[[Category:Culture articles needing translation from Japanese Wikipedia]]\n[[Category:Cuisine by ethnicity]]\n", "name_user": "Erynamrod", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrimary dishes:corrected spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainu_cuisine"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Belgium", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Cleanup reorganize|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Belgium}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Belgium\n| map1            = Spread of COVID19 in Belgium.png\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of Belgium and its provinces with the spread of COVID-19 as of 1 April 2020<ref>[https://epidemio.wiv-isp.be/ID/Documents/Covid19/Meest%20recente%20update.pdf ''COVID-19 \u2013 EPIDEMIOLOGISCH BULLETIN VAN 1 APRIL 2020''], Sciensano, 1 April 2020</ref>}}\n| map2            = COVID-19_outbreak_Belgium_cases_per_capita_map.svg\n| legend2         = Confirmed cases per 100.000 inhabitants by province (as of 2 April 2020)\n{{legend|#fee5d9|< 30}}\n{{legend|#fcbba1|30-60}}\n{{legend|#fc9272|60-90}}\n{{legend|#fb6a4a|90-120}}\n{{legend|#de2d26|120-150}}\n{{legend|#a50f15|150+}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Belgium]]\n| first_case      = [[Brussels]]\n| arrival_date    = 4 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=2|day1=4|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00548-w |title=Mystery deepens over animal source of coronavirus|journal= Nature |volume=579|pages= 18\u201319 |date=26 February 2020|author=David Cyranoski|issue=7797|pmid=32127703|bibcode=2020Natur.579...18C}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases  = 2,872<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"nb01\">The official reports do not refer to ''recovered'' people but to ''discharged'' patients.</ref><ref name=\"info-coronavirus\"/>\n| deaths          = 1,143<ref name=\"info-coronavirus\"/> (=9.9 deaths per 100,000 head of population)\n| confirmed_cases = 16,770<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"nb02\">The actual number of infections is estimated to be much higher than the number of cases confirmed by a laboratory test.</ref><ref name=\"info-coronavirus\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.info-coronavirus.be/nl/news/ |title=Coronavirus COVID-19 |website=info-coronavirus.be|language=nl}}</ref> (=145 cases per 100,000 head of population)\n| website         = https://www.info-coronavirus.be/\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread from the [[People's Republic of China]] to [[Belgium]] on 4 February 2020, when its first COVID-19 case was confirmed in [[Brussels]]. The pandemic only started on 1 March, when many skiers who had spent the school holiday around carnival in the North of Italy were allowed to return to work or school.<ref>Erika Vlieghe (UZA), [https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/12/opinie-rectoren-coronavirus/ VRT Journaal] 12 March 2020.</ref> All the latest confirmed cases, deaths and recoveries on the coronavirus outbreak in Belgium can be found on the website of [[Sciensano]].\n\nEfforts to address the coronavirus outbreak in Belgium have to be managed by the nine federal and regional health ministers, [[Maggie De Block]] (Open VLD, federal government), [[Wouter Beke]] (CD&V, Flemish Community), {{ill|Christine Morreale|fr}} (PS, French Community), {{ill|Antonios Antoniadis (Belgian politician)|de|Antonios Antoniadis|lt=Antonios Antoniadis}} (SP, German-speaking Community), {{ill|B\u00e9n\u00e9dicte Linard|fr}} (Ecolo, French Community), {{ill|Val\u00e9rie Glatigny|fr}} (MR, French Community), {{ill|Alain Maron|fr}} (Ecolo, Brussels), {{ill|Elke Van den Brandt|nl}} (Groen, Brussels) and {{ill|Barbara Trachte|fr}} (Ecolo, Brussels).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/98588/heres-why-belgium-has-nine-health-ministers-regions-communities-powers-responsibilities-coronavirus/|title=Here's why Belgium has nine health ministers|publisher=[[The Brussels Times]]|date=5 March 2020}}</ref> with the support of:\n* [[Sciensano]], the national public health institute of Belgium,\n* other agencies such as the [[Agency for Care and Health (Flanders)|Agency for Care and Health]] in Flanders and the [[Agence wallonne pour une vie de qualit\u00e9]] (AViQ) in Wallonia and the [[Common Community Commission]] in Brussels\n* the Risk Assessment Group (RAG) presided by Sciensano\n* the Risk Management Group (RMG) lead by Paul Pardon MD\n* a Coronavirus Scientific Committee (Steven Van Gucht, [[Marc Van Ranst]], Nathalie Bossuyt, Erika Vlieghe and Charlotte Martin)\n* the National Crisis Centre (NCCN) lead by Bart Raeymaekers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.info-coronavirus.be/en/what-is-the-government-doing-about-it/|title=What is the government doing?|website=www.info-coronavirus.be|publisher=[[Federal Public Service Health (Belgium)]]}}</ref>\n\nUnlike most neighbouring countries ([[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands|the Netherlands]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]] and the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|UK]]), the Belgian authorities were initially not willing to provide information or statistics on where the cases are located, beyond statistics for each region: Flanders, Brussels and [[Wallonia]].<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200305_04877096|title=Waarom ons land niet zegt waar de coronapati\u00ebnten wonen|agency=De Morgen|date=5 March 2020}}</ref> Sciensano started to publish statistics per province from 18 March onwards and per municipality from 26 March onwards.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Belgium medical cases chart}}\n\n===January 2020===\nFirst reports of a [[coronavirus disease 2019|mysterious lung disease]] in the Chinese city of [[Wuhan]] started to appear in the Belgian press around 8 January.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200108_04796282|title=De longziekte waar China graag mysterieus over doet|agency=Het Nieuwsblad|date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Phase 1====\nOn 29 January, Belgium issued a travel notice advising against non-essential flights to China, Hong Kong excluded, with some travel companies cancelling all flights to China.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/01/29/buitenlandse-zaken-raadt-alle-niet-essentiele-reizen-naar-china/|title=Buitenlandse Zaken raadt alle niet-essenti\u00eble reizen naar China af wegens het coronavirus|agency=VRTnws|date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Chinese New Year celebrations were cancelled at the [[KU Leuven|University of Leuven]].<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/01/29/iedereen-aan-de-mondmaskers-wie-familie-heeft-in-china-koopt-oo/|title=Douaniers op onze luchthavens dragen voortaan mondmaskers: \"Maar hier masker dragen tegen coronavirus heeft geen zin\"|agency=VRTnws |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January the domain name \"info-coronavirus.be\" was registered by the authorities.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/dossier/epidemie-de-coronavirus/detail_le-nom-de-domaine-info-coronavirus-be-enregistre-des-le-30-janvier-chronique-d-une-crise-sanitaire?id=10470410|title=\"info-coronavirus.be\" \u00e9tait enregistr\u00e9 le 30 janvier : mais \u00e0 part \u00e7a, la Belgique \u00e9tait-elle \"vraiment pr\u00e9par\u00e9e\" \u00e0 la crise sanitaire ?|agency=RTBF|date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====Lack of masks and respirators=====\nTowards the end of January it became clear that Belgium had an insufficient stock of [[respirator]]s and [[surgical mask]]s but Jan Eyckmans of the [[Federal Public Service Health (Belgium)|Federal Public Service Health]] department claimed the Belgian hospitals had sufficient stock.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200129_04826442|title=China zuigt alle mondmaskers aan in Belgi\u00eb|publisher=De Standaard|date=29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200225_04864842 |title=Belgische apotheken kunnen vraag naar mondmaskers niet aan|publisher=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|date=25 February 2020}}</ref> On 8 March the federal minister of public health [[Maggie De Block]] stated she had a solution for the shortage of masks but was unwilling to disclose the potential vendor and the number of masks involved.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200308_04880517|title=Maggie De Block heeft oplossing klaar voor tekort aan mondmaskers in ons land: 'Nog langer wachten is geen optie'|publisher=De Standaard|date=8 March 2020}}</ref> On 15 March, it became clear that the masks had not been delivered on time,<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200129_04826074|title=Niet zeker of ziekenhuizen bestelde maskers krijgen|publisher=De Standaard|date=15 March 2020}}</ref> and the following day De Block announced that her department's order of 5 million masks might have involved fraud.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200315_04890059|title=Mogelijk fraude: kans dat mondmaskers tijdig geleverd worden aan ons land, 'is miniem'|publisher=De Standaard|date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200316_04890628|title=Alarm over mondmaskers na 'mogelijke fraude'|publisher=De Standaard|date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, hospitals such as the [[UZ Leuven]] called for the public to bring in [[FFP2]] , [[FFP3]] respirators or [[surgical mask]]s<ref>[https://www.uzleuven.be/nl/nieuws/oproep-voor-mondmaskers ''Oproep voor mondmaskers''], UZ Leuven, 16 March 2020</ref> and the next day [[De Standaard]] reported that De Block had blundered by ordering all 5 million masks from a single company (M.O.S.S.A. [[general partnership|vof]]), a consultancy firm that had no track record in the medical field and was owned by Mahmut \u00d6z, a Belgo-Turkish politician from her own political affiliation.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200316_04891726|title=Flater De Block heeft zware gevolgen|publisher=De Standaard|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March, a shipment of 100.000 FFP2 respirators arrived.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.lesoir.be/288625/article/2020-03-19/coronavirus-100000-masques-ffp2-sont-arrives-ce-jeudi-liege-et-seront|title=Coronavirus: 100.000 masques FFP2 sont arriv\u00e9s ce jeudi \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge et seront imm\u00e9diatement distribu\u00e9s|publisher=Le Soir|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, a shipment from China of 5 million masks arrived at the airport of Bierset, but these were surgical masks and not the type of respirators required to protect the medical staff.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/societe/detail_coronavirus-les-5-millions-de-masques-arrives-en-belgique-achemines-vers-les-hopitaux?id=10462764|title=Coronavirus : les 5 millions de masques arriv\u00e9s en Belgique achemin\u00e9s vers les h\u00f4pitaux|publisher=RTBF|date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/societe/detail_5-millions-de-masques-arrives-de-chine-des-masques-chirurgicaux-une-protection-insuffisante-pour-le-covid-19?id=10464202|title=5 millions de masques arriv\u00e9s de Chine : des masques chirurgicaux, une protection insuffisante pour le Covid-19|publisher=RTBF|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Hospitals such as the Centre Hospitalier Interr\u00e9gional Edith Cavell (CHIREC) reported that they were in dire need of protective masks.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://plus.lesoir.be/288954/article/2020-03-20/coronavirus-le-chirec-est-pret-pour-accueillir-le-pic-mais-il-manque-cruellement|title=Coronavirus: le Chirec est pr\u00eat pour accueillir le pic mais il manque cruellement de masques|publisher=Le Soir|date=20 March 2020}}</ref> The Belgian [[textile industry|textile sector]] was unable to produce mouth masks at short notice to make up for the shortage.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://trends.knack.be/economie/bedrijven/textielsector-hier-productie-van-mondmaskers-opstarten-is-niet-vanzelfsprekend/article-longread-1579013.html|title=Textielsector: 'Hier productie van mondmaskers opstarten, is niet vanzelfsprekend'|publisher=Knack|date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Minister [[Philippe De Backer]] was charged with coordinating the efforts of the authorities to supply masks and respirators.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200322_04898232|title=De Backer moet tekort aan mondmaskers tegengaan|publisher=De Standaard|date=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 25 March, [[Workers' Party of Belgium|PVDA]]-member of parliament {{ill|Sofie Merckx|nl}} complained that since 2009 the various governments had not renewed the strategic reserves of mouth masks due to cost cutting measures in the health care system. Upon reaching their expiration date in 2018, minister of health [[Maggie De Block]] decided to destroy and not replace 6 million face masks.\n<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.redactie24.be/news/28823/maggie-de-block-zwaar-onder-vuur-na-deze-pandemie-zal-ik-de-oprichting-van-een-parlementaire-onderzoekscommissie-vragen|title=Maggie De Block zwaar onder vuur: \"Na deze pandemie zal ik de oprichting van een parlementaire onderzoekscommissie vragen\"|publisher=Redactie 24.|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 1 February, Belgian nationals living in Hubei were repatriated on a series of evacuation flights arriving at Melsbroek Military Airport close to [[Brussels]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/93212/belgians-evacuated-from-china-arrive-in-brussels/ |title=Belgians evacuated from China amid coronavirus outbreak arrived in Brussels |author=Gabriela Galindo |date=3 February 2020 |website=The Brussel Times |url-status=live |access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref> where they were [[quarantine]]d and examined in a military hospital. All people with [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] were transferred to the Military Hospital of [[Neder-Over-Heembeek|Neder-over-Heembeek]] where they underwent a 14-day quarantine and got tested for infection with the virus.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/01/27/belgie-haalt-15-landgenoten-terug-uit-hubei-na-uitbraak-coronav/|title=Belgi\u00eb haalt landgenoten terug uit Chinese provincie Hubei na uitbraak coronavirus|agency=VRTnws|date=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/01/30/maggie-de-block-open-vld-gerepatrieerde-belgen-moeten-14-dag/|title=Maggie De Block (Open VLD): \"Gerepatrieerde Belgen moeten 14 dagen in quarantaine in Militair Hospitaal\"|date=30 January 2020|agency=VRTnws}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February, Belgium confirmed the first case.<ref name=\"BRUS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/93361/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-belgium/|title=First case of coronavirus confirmed in Belgium|date=4 February 2020|website=The Brussels Times}}</ref> The patient, an asymptomatic 54-year-old male was one of nine Belgians repatriated from China.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/wevelgem/belg-die-besmet-raakte-met-coronavirus-en-in-quarantaine-ligt-getuigt-plots-kwamen-ze-zeggen-dat-ze-slecht-nieuws-voor-me-hadden~a8cdd787|title=Belg die besmet raakte met coronavirus ...|date=4 February 2020|website=Het Laatste Nieuws}}</ref> He was transferred from the Military Hospital of Neder-Over-Heembeek to Saint-Pierre Hospital in [[Brussels]] to be quarantined there <ref name=\"BRUS\" />\n\nOn 21 February, a group of 10 Belgian citizens were allowed to return to Belgium after having been constrained on the [[MS Westerdam]] cruise ship for several days.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch |url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/vlucht-belgische-passagiers-westerdam-geland-in-nederland-hen-wacht-isolatie~a79ae26e/|title=Belgische passagiers Westerdam geland in Nederland, hen wacht isolatie|publisher=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Two couples used public transport to return home, notwithstanding the requirement to be quarantined for 2 weeks.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch |url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/buitenland/alle-belgen-weer-thuis-van-corona-cruise-twee-koppels-keerden-gewoon-met-openbaar-vervoer-terug-van-luchthaven~a1ce589f/|title=Alle Belgen weer thuis van corona-cruise: twee koppels keerden gewoon met openbaar vervoer terug van luchthaven|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, following the discovery of a COVID-19 case involving an Italian citizen, more than 100 Belgian citizens were put in [[quarantine]] in the [[H10 Hotels|H10 Costa Adeje Palace]] in [[Tenerife]] that was put on lockdown.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/25/europe/tenerife-coronavirus-hotel-intl/index.html|title=Tenerife hotel on partial lockdown as Italian tests positive for coronavirus|author1=Laura Perez Maestro |author2=Niamh Kennedy |author3=Amy Woodyatt|website=CNN|access-date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/02/29/corona-tenerife-toeristen/|title=Ongerustheid bij Belgen in quarantaine in hotel Tenerife: \"Het is hier 'tirez votre plan', er is veel onduidelijk\"|publisher=VRT|date=29 February 2020}}</ref> Fifteen people were allowed to return on 28 February. The remainder were allowed to travel back to Belgium on 5 March, without having been tested for the SARS-CoV-2 virus.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200305_04877475|title=Belgen uit 'coronahotel' op Tenerife worden niet meer getest bij aankomst in ons land|publisher=Het Nieuwsblad|date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 February, the Belgian federal minister of health Maggie De Block asserted that \"Belgium was prepared\" for the possible arrival of cases of infection with [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]].<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/02/25/de-block-over-corona/|title=Minister De Block: \"Kans is re\u00ebel dat coronavirus naar ons land komt, maar er is een plan\"|publisher=VRT|date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hospital_prefab-containers_built_next_to_the_emergency_department_for_the_COVID-19_crisis_in_%22UZA%22_Antwerp_University_Hospital_(Edegem,_Belgium),_Saturday_2020_March_14th,_14;59PM.jpg | thumb | Hospital prefab-containers built next to the emergency department for the COVID-19 crisis at the [[Antwerp University|Antwerp University Hospital]], 14 March 2020]]\n\nOn 26 February, the UZA clinic in [[Edegem]] started with the construction of containers to be able to cope with the increased influx of patients in the emergency department.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20200226_04865807/uz-antwerpen-bouwt-containerafdeling-voor-patienten-mogelijk-besmet-met-coronavirus|title=UZA test pati\u00ebnten op coronavirus in aparte containers|publisher=[[Gazet van Antwerpen]]|date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\n====Phase 2====\n\n[[File:CoViD-19 BE.svg|thumb|upright=2|left|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]].]]\n\nOn 1 March, a second case of coronavirus was confirmed in Belgium, a Dutch speaking woman who had returned from [[Cr\u00e9py-en-Valois]] in one of the regions affected in France.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/97873/new-coronavirus-infection-reported-in-antwerp/|title=New coronavirus infection reported in Antwerp|publisher=[[The Brussels Times]]|date=1 March 2020}}</ref> At the same time phase 2 of the health risk containment strategy was activated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/belgium/98009/belgium-enters-phase-2-for-coronavirus-what-does-it-mean/|title=Belgium enters Phase 2 for coronavirus: what does it mean?|publisher=[[The Brussels Times]]|date=2 March 2020}}</ref> The yearly one week [[school holiday]] around [[carnival]] lasted from 22 February until 1 March 2020 and quite a few people go on ski vacation during that period. The number of detected virus infections therefore sharply rose upon the return of people having resided in the ski resorts of the North of Italy. The mayor of [[Woluwe-Saint-Lambert|Sint-Lambrechts-Woluwe]], [[Olivier Maingain]], was one of the only mayors to take measures to prevent the spreading of the new coronavirus by restricting access to schools, preschools, sports facilities and public places for persons returning from areas at risk<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200301_04870946|title=Burgemeester Maingain neemt maatregel tegen coronavirus, De Block reageert: \"Volledig disproportioneel\"|publisher=Het Nieuwsblad|date=1 March 2020}}</ref> and only a few schools, such as the [[International School Ghent]], quarantined pupils that returned from areas at risk, such as [[Northern Italy]].<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200302_04872888|title=Verrassend dat niet alle scholen hetzelfde doen|publisher=De Standaard|date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, six additional cases, making a total of eight, had been diagnosed. Five were found in Flanders and one in Brussels, all six having come back from Northern Italy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Returns from Italy push COVID-19 tally higher |url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/02/returns-from-italy-push-covid-19-tally-higher/ |work=VRTnws|date=2 March 2020 }}</ref> Minister De Block mentioned there was no reason to panic and said Belgium could cope with the epidemic.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200301_04871378|title=Geen paniek, we kunnen dit aan|publisher=De Standaard|date=2 March 2020}}</ref> Some experts, like Marc Wathelet<ref>{{Cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/opinions/detail_lettre-ouverte-a-la-ministre-de-la-sante-publique-coronavirus-il-faut-savoir-ecouter-la-peur?id=10443799|title=Lettre ouverte \u00e0 la ministre de la Sant\u00e9 publique : \"Coronavirus, il faut savoir \u00e9couter la peur\"|publisher=[[RTBF]]|date=28 February 2020}}</ref> and professor [[Herman Goossens]] of the [[Universitair Ziekenhuis Antwerpen|UZA]] in Antwerp criticized the (lack of) measures taken by the Belgian government and called for wider screening for the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20200301_04871248/professor-van-uz-antwerpen-breder-testen-noodzakelijk-om-virus-goed-in-kaart-te-brengen|title=Experts oneens over aanpak coronavirus: \"Pati\u00ebnt was niet gevonden als we richtlijnen overheid hadden gevolgd\"|publisher=[[Gazet van Antwerpen]]|date=2 March 2020}}</ref> Pharmacists complained they did not receive clear instructions from the authorities.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200302_04872463|title=Apothekers kregen nog steeds geen specifieke instructies over corona: \"Wij zitten nochtans in de vuurlinie\"|publisher=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|date=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 3 March, six additional cases were confirmed, making a total of 14 cases. One of the infected persons was a 17-year old teenager who returned to his school in [[Tienen]] after a ski vacation in the North of Italy.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/03/coronavirus-belgie-3-maart/|title=Zes nieuwe besmettingen met het coronavirus in Belgi\u00eb|date=3 March 2020|agency=VRTnws}}</ref> Another person from [[Sint-Niklaas]] also returned from a skiing holiday.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/sint-niklaas/man-uit-sint-niklaas-heeft-geen-idee-hoe-hij-coronavirus-opliep-op-reis-liep-ik-zelfs-vaak-met-sjaal-rond-mijn-mond~afaa682f/|title=Man uit Sint-Niklaas heeft geen idee hoe hij coronavirus opliep: \"Op reis liep ik zelfs vaak met sjaal rond mijn mond\"|publisher=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=3 March 2020}}</ref> A patient from [[Verviers]] was hospitalised in a Brussels clinic,<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/buitenland/vijftiende-geval-van-coronavirus-in-ons-land-bevestigd-spanje-meldt-eerste-dode~a1432729/|title=Vijftiende geval van coronavirus in ons land bevestigd \u2013 Spanje meldt eerste dode|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=3 March 2020}}</ref> and two cases were found in {{ill|Couthuin|fr}} (part of [[H\u00e9ron]]).<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/dit-weten-we-over-de-tien-nieuwe-coronabesmettingen-in-ons-land~a93573e9/|title=Dit weten we over de tien nieuwe coronabesmettingen in ons land|publisher=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> One patient is a 65-year-old male from [[Eupen]] who presented relatively severe symptoms and had not been to any of the regions with a higher risk of infection.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200129_04826074|title=Vijftiende Belgische coronapati\u00ebnt met longontsteking overgebracht naar referentieziekenhuis|publisher=[[De Standaard]]|date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.medi-sfeer.be/nl/nieuws/beroepsnieuws/besmette-coronapatient-van-eupen-werd-niet-als-risicopatient-aanzien.html|title=Coronapati\u00ebnt Eupen zadelt zorgverleners op met quarantaine|publisher=MEDI-SFEER|date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Steven Van Gucht of the Scientific Committee predicted that in the worst-case scenario the epidemic would cause 13,000 virus infections, with 2,000 to 3,000 hospitalisations and 500 to 700 patients in intensive care.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/expert-volksgezondheid-tempert-paniek-worstcasescenario-vergelijkbaar-met-zware-seizoensgriep~a94d020a/|title=Expert Volksgezondheid tempert paniek: \"Worstcasescenario vergelijkbaar met zware seizoensgriep\"|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=3 March 2020}}</ref> In a later interview he mentioned different numbers saying that 70% of the population (approximately 8 million persons) could become infected.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200316_04890623|title=Virus stoppen niet meer aan de orde|publisher=De Standaard|date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 4 March, ten new cases were confirmed before noon, making a total of 23. Nine of the new patients recently returned from Italy. The other patient had contact with a prior case.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/04/nieuwe-gevallen-van-coronavirus-in-ons-land/|title=10 nieuwe gevallen van coronavirus in ons land, in totaal nu 23 pati\u00ebnten|date=4 March 2020|agency=VRTnws}}</ref> Four cases were in the [[Leuven]] area,<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.robtv.be/nieuws/eerste-coronabesmetting-in-leuven-besmette-personen-in-isolatie-94231 |title=Coronavirus duikt op in drie Leuvense scholen|publisher=www.robtv.be|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> one case in [[Hasselt]],<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/04/ook-leerling-school-kindsheid-jesu-in-hasselt-test-positief-op-c/|title=Leerling Kindsheid Jesu in Hasselt test positief op corona: \"Ze is na de vakantie niet in school geweest\"|publisher=VRT|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> and one in [[Pelt]].<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.tvl.be/nieuws/lerares-van-college-uit-pelt-is-besmet-met-coronavirus|title=Lerares van college uit Pelt is besmet met coronavirus|publisher=TV Limburg|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> In [[Wevelgem]] two related cases appeared. A complete family of 7 was infected upon their return from a ski holiday in the North of Italy. Initially the Belgian authorities did not want to test the family for the virus, notwithstanding the request of the family.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/wevelgem/gezin-en-liefjes-van-kinderen-keren-alle-acht-besmet-terug-van-skireis-nu-twee-weken-samen-uitzieken-in-quarantaine~a81e1f19/|title=Gezin en liefjes van kinderen keren alle acht besmet terug van skireis: nu twee weken samen uitzieken in quarantaine|publisher=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> Additionally a teacher in a primary school in Wevelgem, who was on the same ski vacation as the family of seven and even went to work for two and a half days after the school holiday became sick and was diagnosed with the covid-19 virus.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://kw.be/nieuws/samenleving/lid-coronafamilie-wevelgem-niemand-van-ons-is-echt-ziek/article-normal-423941.html?cookie_check=1583398210|title=Lid 'coronafamilie' Wevelgem: \"Niemand van ons is \u00e9cht ziek\"|publisher=De Krant van West-Vlaanderen|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Agentschap Zorg en Gezondheid]] advised the school to not close down.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200305_04876906|title=Gezin van zeven en leerkracht in Wevelgem besmet met corona|publisher=De Standaard|date=5 March 2020}}</ref> A retirement home in [[Gooik]] stopped receiving visitors as a precautionary measure, because one employee could have been in contact with the new coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/gooik/woonzorgcentrum-in-gooik-in-lockdown-nadat-medewerker-in-onrechtstreeks-contact-kwam-met-corona~a3b250b9/|title=Woonzorgcentrum in Gooik in lockdown nadat medewerker in onrechtstreeks contact kwam met corona|publisher=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> Joris Moonens, the spokesman of the Flemish Agency for Care and Health, expressed the opinion that this was not an appropriate measure.<ref>{{cite web|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/05/woonzorgcentrum-in-gooik-sluit-preventief-de-deuren-voor-alle-be/|title=Geen bezoek in woonzorgcentrum in Gooik uit schrik voor coronavirus, Zorg en Gezondheid: \"Te extreme maatregel\"|publisher=VRT|date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, the [[European Defence Agency]] (EDA) confirmed that a staff member had tested positive for coronavirus, marking the first confirmed case in the [[agencies of the European Union]].<ref name=\"euractiv.1\">{{Cite news|author=Gerardo Fortuna|date=4 March 2020|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/first-confirmed-case-of-covid-19-in-the-eu-institutions/|title=First confirmed case of COVID-19 in the EU institutions|publisher=Euractiv.com|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> The senior EDA official had returned from a trip to Italy the previous week.<ref name=\"euractiv.1\" /> After returning from Italy, he attended a roughly four-hour meeting with about thirty other European Union officials last week before he started feeling ill on Saturday (29 February).<ref name=\"euractiv.1\" /> A military staff member of the [[European External Action Service]] who attended the meeting has also begun experiencing symptoms.<ref name=\"euractiv.1\" /> The EDA has cancelled all meetings until 13 March, and other European Union institutions are also taking precautions.<ref name=\"euractiv.1\" /><ref>{{cite tweet|user=EURACTIV |number=1235134557885693952|date=4 March 2020 |title=First case of #coronavirus in the EU institutions: the European Defence Agency has cancelled all meetings until 13 March after a senior official tested positive for #COVID_19, according to an internal mail seen by EURACTIV.}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, 27 new confirmed cases were reported by the government (16 in Flanders, 9 in Wallonia and 2 in Brussels), bringing the total to 50.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/05/nieuwe-corona-patienten-in-belgie/|title=27 nieuwe corona-pati\u00ebnten in ons land, vanavond komen Belgen naar huis die in quarantaine zaten op Tenerife|date=5 March 2020|agency=VRTnws}}</ref> Of the 50 persons 1 patient recovered, 48 are quarantined in their home and 1 person is being treated in the Sint-Pietersziekenhuis.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.knack.be/nieuws/wereld/coronavirus-italie-en-vs-trekken-miljarden-uit-om-gevolgen-te-milderen/live-normal-1569303.html|title=Federale regering keurt vrijdag maatregelen|author1=Gert Segers|publisher=Knack|date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The new cases were reported to be in [[Knokke-Heist]], [[Zonhoven]], {{ill|Doomkerke|nl}} ([[Ruiselede]]) and [[Vlierzele]] (part of [[Sint-Lievens-Houtem]]).<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/27-nieuwe-coronabesmettingen-in-belgie-totaal-staat-op-50-dit-weten-we~ae86f5c2/|title=27 nieuwe coronabesmettingen in Belgi\u00eb, totaal staat op 50: dit weten we|publisher=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, 59 new cases were reported by the government, bringing the total to 109 (65 in Flanders, 12 in Brussels, 31 in Wallonia and 1 cured). The new cases were amongst others reported in [[Oosterzele]] and [[Sint-Katelijne-Waver]].<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/in-kaart-dit-weten-we-over-de-59-nieuwe-coronabesmettingen-in-belgie~ade7072ca/|title=Dit weten we over de 59 nieuwe coronabesmettingen in Belgi\u00eb|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=6 March 2020}}</ref> The Ministry of Health confirmed for the first time that infections occurred on Belgium territory.\n\nOn 7 March, 60 new cases were confirmed by the government (40 in Flanders, 5 in Brussels and 15 in Wallonia), bringing the total to 169 (105 in Flanders, 17 in Brussels, 46 in Wallonia and 1 cured). The new cases were amongst others reported in [[Houthalen]], [[Melle, Belgium|Melle]], [[Lokeren]], [[Mere, Belgium|Mere]], [[Lede, Belgium|Lede]], [[Tildonk]] and [[Poppel (village)|Poppel]].<ref>[https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/dit-weten-we-over-de-60-nieuwe-coronabesmettingen-in-belgie~a40f788e/. Dit weten we over de 60 nieuwe coronabesmettingen in Belgi\u00eb]. hln.be (7 March 2020)</ref> The [[UZ Leuven]] confirmed they were forced to limit the number of tests for the virus because of a shortage of reagents for the test.<ref name=\"Het Nieuwsblad\">{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200307_04880150|title=UZ Leuven moet tests voor coronavirus inperken vanwege tekort aan reagentia|publisher=Het Nieuwsblad|date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The ministry of public health mentioned that \"more and more infections are being contracted locally\u201d but did not provide the information on how many.<ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/99094/leuven-test-centre-has-to-limit-coronavirus-tests-shortage-reagents-triage-gosselies/|title=Coronavirus: 169 confirmed cases in Belgium|author1=Alan Hope|publisher=The Brussels Times|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 422 samples taken on 7 March 31 were tested positive on 8 March (16 in Flanders, 8 in Brussels and 7 in Wallonia), bringing the number of infections to 200. The ministry of health confirmed \"local circulation of the virus from various locations\" but did not disclose these locations.<ref>[https://www.info-coronavirus.be/en/2020/03/08/31-new-covid-19-coronavirus-infections/ 31 new Covid-19 coronavirus infections]. info-coronavirus.be (8 March 2020)</ref>\n\n=====Lack of reagents for testing=====\nOn 7 March, it became clear that Belgium lacked enough reagents to do widespread [[COVID-19 testing]] and the National Reference Centre for Pathogens (NRC)<ref>[https://www.uzleuven.be/nl/laboratoriumgeneeskunde/nationaal-referentiecentrum-pathogenen Nationaal ReferentieCentrum pathogenen]</ref> was forced to apply a system of [[triage]].<ref name=\"Het Nieuwsblad\"/> Two surgeons from the Brussels Saint Pierre hospital addressed an open letter to prime minister Wilm\u00e8s on 22 March demanding increased testing.<ref>{{Cite news|language=French|url=https://plus.lesoir.be/289156/article/2020-03-22/lettre-ouverte-de-deux-chirurgiens-sophie-wilmes-sur-le-coronavirus-la-double|title=Lettre ouverte de deux chirurgiens \u00e0 Sophie Wilm\u00e8s sur le coronavirus: \"La double peine du personnel hospitalier\"|publisher=Le Soir|date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/belgique/detail_coronavirus-des-tests-systematiques-reclames-a-la-premiere-ministre-par-deux-chirurgiens-belges?id=10464596|title=Coronavirus: des tests syst\u00e9matiques r\u00e9clam\u00e9s \u00e0 la Premi\u00e8re ministre par deux chirurgiens belges|publisher=RTBF|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Reinforced phase 2====\nOn 10 March, the total number of confirmed cases was 267;<ref>[https://www.info-coronavirus.be/fr/2020/03/10/28-nouvelles-infections-au-coronavirus-covid-19/ 28 nouvelles infections au coronavirus Covid-19]. info-coronavirus.be (10 March 2020)</ref> that day the government advised to cancel any indoor scheduled events to be attended by more than 1000 people for the month of March. Prime minister [[Sophie Wilm\u00e8s|Wilm\u00e8s]] stressed this was not an interdiction but rather a recommendation.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200310_04884455|title=Zeg alles af, of we stevenen op Italiaanse toestanden af|publisher=De Standaard|date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Schools remain open but are advised to cancel trips abroad and multi-day excursions in general. Companies are advised to have their personnel work from home as much as possible and allow flexible working times to allow a better spread of public transport use throughout the day. The authorities called this 'reinforced phase 2'.<ref>[https://www.zorg-en-gezondheid.be/versterkte-fase-2 ''Nieuwe maatregelen voor versterkte fase 2 van corona-beheersing''], Agency for Care and Health, 10 March 2020</ref>\n\n=====Confusion on the intensive care units capacity=====\nBelgium belongs to the top 5 European countries with respect to number of intensive care units (ICUs): before the outbreak of the pandemic the number of ICUs was quoted to be around 15.9<ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/charting-europes-capacity-to-deal-with-the-coronavirus-crisis/|title=Charting Europe\u2019s capacity to deal with the coronavirus crisis|publisher=Politico|date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>Rhodes et al., [https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8 ''The variability of critical care bed numbers in Europe''], Intensive Care Medicine, Volume 38, pages 1647\u20131653 (2012)</ref> to 16.5<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.medi-sfeer.be/nl/nieuws/geert-meyfrodt-wellicht-grootste-nachtmerrie-uit-mijn-carriere.html|title=Geert Meyfroidt: \"Wellicht grootste nachtmerrie uit mijn carri\u00e8re\"|publisher=MEDI-SFEER|date=16 March 2020}}</ref> ICUs per 100{{nbsp}}000 inhabitants. Around 10 March, the Belgian hospitals started to increase their number of [[intensive care unit]]s (ICU). Jan Eyckmans of the [[Federal Public Service Health]] claimed they increased it from 1900 to 2650 in two weeks time, corresponding to an increase from 16.5 to 23.0 ICUs per 100{{nbsp}}000 inhabitants.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200322_04898597|title='Chinese' krachttoer levert intensieve zorg al 40 procent extra bedden op|publisher=De Standaard|date=23 March 2020}}</ref> However, on the daily press conference of the Belgian National Crisis Centre of 28 March Dr Emmanuel Andr\u00e9 of the UZ Leuven mentioned that the number of 789 ICUs corresponded to 43% of the capacity, bringing the total capacity to 1835 instead of 2650, while Dr Steven Van Gucht quoted the capacity to be 2081 units<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/27/liveblog-28-maart/|title=Liveblog - Coronavirus eist meer dan 10.000 levens in Itali\u00eb, 64 nieuwe overlijdens in ons land|publisher=VRT|date=28 March 2020}}</ref> and De Standaard mentioned the number of 1765.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200330_04907346|title=Van Italiaans pad af, maar nog niet op Scandinavisch|publisher=De Standaard|date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, ministers De Block and Maron announced that the first death on Belgian territory due to COVID-19 occurred on 10 March,<ref>[https://www.lesoir.be/286174/article/2020-03-11/coronavirus-deux-nouveaux-deces-en-belgique Coronavirus: deux nouveaux d\u00e9c\u00e8s en Belgique]. Le Soir (11 March 2020)</ref> a 90-year-old female patient from [[Brussels]] who was being treated in [[Etterbeek]].<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200311_04885244|title=90-jarige is eerste dode door nieuw coronavirus in Belgi\u00eb|publisher=De Standaard|date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Two more patients died on the same day, one person aged 73 and one person aged 86 who died in [[Sint-Genesius-Rode]].<ref>[https://www.info-coronavirus.be/nl/2020/03/11/twee-nieuwe-overlijdens-door-covid-19/ Twee nieuwe overlijdens door Covid-19]. info-coronavirus.be (11 March 2020)</ref> Zorgnet Icuro requested minister Beke to take stronger actions with respect to visitor access at [[retirement home]]s in Flanders.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200129_04826074|title=Vlaamse rusthuizen eisen verbod op bezoek|publisher=De Standaard|date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Professors Herman Goossens and Marc Van Ranst expressed the opinion that more drastic measures were required for Belgium and questioned the limit of maximum 1000 people for indoor events set by prime minister Wilm\u00e8s on 10 March.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/11/professor-herman-goossens-draconische-maatregelen-nodig-om-cor/|title=Professoren Goossens en Van Ranst: \"Draconische maatregelen zijn nodig, zoals alle evenementen schrappen\"|author1=Ludwig De Wolf|publisher=VRT|date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, 2 new infections were detected as well as 32 suspected cases in retirement home Ter Kameren in [[Watermaal-Bosvoorde]], one of the biggest retirement homes of the Brussels region.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/12/34-rusthuis-bewoners-met-symptomen-corona-11-besmet/|title=Al zeker 2 bewoners van rusthuis Watermaal-Bosvoorde testen positief op nieuw coronavirus, in totaal 34 besmettingen gevreesd|author1=Yasmina El Messaoudi|publisher=VRT|date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases rose to 399. Approximately 20 patients (approx. 5%) out of those 399 were being treated in [[intensive care medicine|intensive care]].<ref>{{Cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/societe/coronavirus-bilan-belge-actualise-toute-la-journee-3-morts-314-cas-dont-une-vingtaine-de-personnes-hospitalisees-certaines-en-etat-critique-1203176.aspx|title=Coronavirus \u2013 BILAN BELGE: 2 cas positifs et 32 autres suspects dans une maison de repos bruxelloise|publisher=RTL|date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The Belgische Vereniging van Artsensyndicaten (BVAS/ABSyM) called for a closure of all schools at short notice and warned for a potential collapse of the [[Healthcare in Belgium|health care system in Belgium]].<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200312_04887262|title=Artsen willen alle scholen dicht, Weyts noemt dat 'niet aan de orde'|publisher=De Standaard|date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In an [[open letter]] several Flemish [[rector (academia)|rectors]], two members belonging to the Coronavirus Scientific Committee that advises the Belgian authorities and several other experts in the fields of [[epidemiology]], [[virology]], [[biostatistics]] and [[health economics]] urged the authorities to take decisive measures and to avoid non-binding instructions and guidelines.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/12/opinie-rectoren-coronavirus/|title=Open brief van Vlaamse rectoren en experts: \"Het coronavirus is ernstig, aan vrijblijvende richtlijnen hebben we niets\"|publisher=VRT|date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Many people started [[hoarding]] for the next one and a half week.<ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/25/rush-on-supermarkets-is-over/|title=Rush on supermarkets is over|publisher=VRT|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLate in the evening on 12 March, after a meeting of the [[National Security Council (Belgium)|National Security Council]], the Belgian government ordered the closure of schools, discos, cafes and restaurants, and the cancellation of all public gatherings for sporting, cultural or festive purposes from Friday 13 March at midnight onwards.<ref>[https://www.info-coronavirus.be/nl/2020/03/12/fase-2-gehandhaafd-overgang-naar-de-federale-fase-en-bijkomende-maatregelen/ Coronavirus: Phase 2 maintained, transition to the federal phase and additional measures]. info-coronavirus.be (12 March 2020)</ref> It was stressed that the measures taken were not a lockdown because people are not required to stay home.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200313_04888447|title=Waarom Belgi\u00eb niet in lockdown gaat|publisher=De Standaard|date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Earlier that day mayor Leopold Lippens already had ordered similar measures for his municipality of [[Knokke-Heist]].<ref>{{Cite news|language=fr|url=https://www.lesoir.be/286425/article/2020-03-12/coronavirus-knokke-jusquau-30-avril-en-lockdown?from_direct=true|title=Coronavirus: Knokke jusqu'au 30 avril en \"lockdown\"|publisher=Le Soir|date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The president of the [[European Commission]], [[Ursula von der Leyen]] informed the entire staff that 7 of their colleagues had tested positive, six of whom in Belgium. She also instructed \"all colleagues in non-critical functions\" to work from home with immediate effect until 5 April, while those \"who ensure critical functions\" would need to work in two shifts to minimize the risk of contagion.<ref>{{Cite news|language=en|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/all-non-critical-commission-staff-to-work-remotely-von-der-leyen-says/|title=All 'non-critical' Commission staff to work remotely, von der Leyen says|publisher=Politico.eu|date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom Friday 13 March onwards the Belgian National Crisis Centre (NCCN)<ref>[https://crisiscentrum.be/language_selection www.crisiscentrum.be]</ref> started to hold a daily press conference at 11h led by spokesmen Beno\u00eet Ramacker, Peter Mertens and Yves Stevens with doctors Steven Van Gucht and Emmanuel Andr\u00e9.\n\nExperts and authorities expressed their indignation about citizens organising or taking part in so-called 'lock-down or corona parties'.<ref>{{Cite news|language=en|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/14/outrage-at-_lock-down-parties/|title=Last night's \"lock-down parties\" trigger indignation|publisher=VRT|date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/ook-echtgenoot-van-gwendolyn-rutten-organiseerde-coronafeestje~ab42c0d5/|title=Ook echtgenoot van Gwendolyn Rutten organiseerde 'coronafeestje'|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Mayors of municipalities close to the border with the Netherlands such as Paul Van Miert of [[Turnhout]] urged their Dutch counterparts to request their national authorities in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands|Netherlands]] to implement similar measures as in Belgium.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/burgemeester-van-turnhout-aan-nederlandse-collega-s-stop-horecatoerisme~a597bba5/|title=Burgemeester van Turnhout aan Nederlandse collega's: stop \"horecatoerisme'\"|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe coronavirus pandemic sparked new debate on the ongoing [[2019\u201320 Belgian government formation|federal government formation]]. Representatives of [[New Flemish Alliance|N-VA]], [[Parti Socialiste (Belgium)|PS]], [[Open Vlaamse Liberalen en Democraten|Open Vld]], [[Mouvement R\u00e9formateur|MR]], [[Christen-Democratisch en Vlaams|CD&V]] and [[Socialistische Partij Anders|sp.a]] sat together on 14 and 15 March to talk about an emergency coalition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/15/talks-on-emergency-government-continue-this-afternoon/|title=Talks on emergency government continue this afternoon|author=Colin Claps|date=15 March 2020|website=vrtnws.be|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> This idea was however rejected by Magnette (PS) and Bouchez (MR) during the live RTL television show \"C'est pas tous les jours dimanche\" and eventually these parties (except [[New Flemish Alliance|N-VA]]) together with [[Ecolo]], [[Groen (political party)|Groen]], [[cdH]] and [[D\u00e9FI]] opted to temporarily grant more competences to the caretaker [[Wilm\u00e8s I Government]] instead, under the form of a new [[Wilm\u00e8s II Government]], which represents only 38 of the 150 [[Chamber of Representatives (Belgium)|representatives]], but no longer in caretaker status, allowing more flexibility to take quick decisions.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200316_04891143|title=Hoe corona ook de Wetstraat aanstak|publisher=De Standaard|date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/belgique/detail_en-route-vers-un-gouvernement-wilmes-2-0-suivez-la-conference-de-presse-en-direct?id=10458538|title=Le gouvernement Wilm\u00e8s va \u00eatre dot\u00e9 de pouvoirs sp\u00e9ciaux pendant 6 mois|author=Aubry Touriel|date=15 March 2020|website=RTBF Info|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200316_04890617|title=Van handshake tot dolksteek|author=Aubry Touriel|date=16 March 2020|website=De Standaard|language=nl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, [[Philippe of Belgium|King Philippe]] addressed the nation and called on all Belgians to respect the COVID-19 measures \u201cfor ourselves and for the most vulnerable among us\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|language=en|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/17/king-filip-calls-on-belgians-to-respect-the-covid-19-measures-fo/|title=King Filip calls on Belgians to respect the COVID-19 measures \"for ourselves and for the most vulnerable among us\"|publisher=VRT|date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===='Lockdown light'====\n[[File:Covid-19 Mouscron J2a.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Concrete blocks in [[Mouscron]], used to avoid all non-essential travel between France and Belgium (27 March 2020)]]\nOn the evening of 17 March, the Prime Minister broadcast a decision to impose stricter social distancing measures from noon the following day until 5 April, with non-essential travel prohibited, non-essential shops to close, gatherings banned, and penalties to force companies and individuals to abide by the rules.<ref>{{Cite web|author1=Floor Bruggeman|author2=Micha\u00ebl Torfs|author3=Ellen Maerevoet|author4=Denny Baert|author5=Freek Willems|title=Strengere maatregelen tegen coronavirus|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/17/liveblog-17-maart/|date=17 March 2020|language=nl|website=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT Nieuws]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belgium.be/en/news/2020/coronavirus_reinforced_measures|date=17 March 2020|website=belgium.be|publisher=[[Belgian Federal Government]]|title=Coronavirus: reinforced measures}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, from 3 p.m. onwards Belgium closed its borders to all non-essential travel.<ref>{{Cite news|language=en|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/20/borders-closed-to-non-essential-travel/|title=Borders closed to non-essential travel|publisher=VRT|date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Earlier that day the governor of [[West Flanders]] had complained about Dutch and French citizens coming to Belgium for tourism or shopping.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200320_04896509|title=Controles aan Belgische grenzen om Nederlanders te weren, ook in Ardennen maatregelen|publisher=De Standaard|date=20 March 2020}}</ref> That day the chairman of the Scientific Committee also expressed the hope that the measures that came into effect on 14 March would lead to a stabilisation of the number of hospitalisations starting from the mid of the week of 23 March.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200319_04895981|title=De coronapiek komt, al de rest is onzeker|publisher=De Standaard|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Prof. dr. Erika Vlieghe of the Scientific Committee mentioned that the she expected the peak of the pandemic to occur early April.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/22/erika-vlieghe-in-de-ochtend/|title=Brussel betreurt de helft van de corona-overlijdens tot nu toe, maar die cijfers geven een vertekend beeld|publisher=VRT|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====Shortage of hand sanitiser =====\nSeveral brewers,<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20200320_04897212/brouwer-stoker-schakelt-over-alcohol-voor-handgel-in-plaats-van-whisky-uit-stookketel|title=Brouwer-stoker schakelt over: alcohol voor handgel in plaats van whisky uit stookketel|publisher=Gazet van Antwerpen|date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200326_04903014|title=AB InBev maakt handgels en ontsmettingsmiddel uit restalcohol alcoholvrij bier|publisher=De Standaard|date=27 March 2020}}</ref> a pharmaceutical company<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/geel/janssen-pharma-tereos-en-filliers-starten-noodproductie-desinfecterende-ontsmettingsalcohol~a63a4a4b/|title=Janssen Pharma, Tereos \u00e9n Filliers starten noodproductie desinfecterende ontsmettingsalcohol|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=22 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Sugar refinery of Tienen]]<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200323_04899833|title=Tiense Suikerraffinaderij maakt desinfecterende handgel|publisher=De Standaard|date=24 March 2020}}</ref> started to produce [[alcohol]] for [[hand sanitiser]] from 21 March onwards in an effort to alleviate the shortage in Belgium.\n\nOn 25 March the [[Financial Times]] praised Belgium for its handling of the Wuhan coronavirus crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200325_04901764|title=Financial Times vol lof over Belgische aanpak coronacrisis|publisher=De Standaard|date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3d24b654-187e-4270-b051-acfc350498d2|title=Coronavirus crisis brings fragmented Brussels together|publisher=The Financial Times|date=25 March 2020}}</ref> From 25 March onwards people arriving at [[Brussels Airport]] were handed over a leaflet with the compelling advice to quarantine themselves for a fortnight.<ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/25/people-arriving-in-belgium-quarantined-for-a-fortnight/|title=People arriving in Belgium quarantined for a fortnight|publisher=VRT|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the daily press conference of 27 March Steven Van Gucht announced that one cat had been infected by its owner. This was a rare occurrence and only the third time an infection of a pet was observed worldwide. The cat developed respiratory and digestive issues.<ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/27/covid-19-death-toll-rises-to-289/|title=COVID-19 death toll rises to 289|publisher=VRT|date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March the National Sercurity Council and the governments decided to extend the measures taken so far until at least 19 April (until the end of the Easter vacation) with an option to extend the period with two weeks until 3 May.<ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/27/measure-to-curb-the-spread-of-the-novel-coronavirus-to-remain-in/|title=Measures to curb the spread of the novel coronavirus to remain in force until at least 19 April|publisher=VRT|date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe additional number of people that tested positive for the novel coronavirus was rather high on 28 March compared to the previous days because more persons were being tested and because a major Walloon laboratory had not reported any cases so far and reported 500 additional cases from the past days with a delay.<ref>{{Cite news|language=English|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/en/2020/03/28/covid-19-575-more-people-in-hospital-64-deaths-in-the-past-24/|title=Covid-19: almost 800 in intensive care now, 64 deaths in the past 24 hours|publisher=VRT|date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 29 March around 20{{nbsp}}000 Belgian citizens were stuck abroad due to travel restrictions worldwide, many in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Peru|Peru]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa|South Africa]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia|Australia]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand|New Zealand]].<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/29/zo-n-20-000-belgen-zitten-nog-vast-in-buitenland-door-coronacris/|title=Zo'n 20.000 Belgen zitten nog vast in buitenland door coronacrisis: 3 Vlamingen vertellen hun verhaal|publisher=VRT|date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March it was announced that because of the high burden on some hospitals in the provinces of Limburg and Hainaut, the distribution plan for ICU patients had been activated.<ref>{{Cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200330_04906592|title=536 bijkomende opnames in ziekenhuis, 'Kracht van epidemie neemt duidelijk af'|publisher=De Standaard|date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 31 March (data reported on 1st April), a drop in the daily increase of patients being treated in hospitals was observed. This can be explained by the rise of discharged patients: 436 people left hospital in the last 24 hours.\n\n==Belgian research==\nResearch to find a [[COVID-19 vaccine|vaccine against COVID-19]], medication for the lung disease or [[COVID-19 testing|new test methods]] are concentrated in Belgium amongst others at the [[KU Leuven]] (vaccine and new medication, Prof Johan Neyts),<ref>{{cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200124_04819805|title=Leuven in race naar vaccin tegen Chinees longvirus|agency=De Standaard|date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200303_04874509|title=Bill Gates bestelt grote coronastudie in Leuven|agency=De Standaard|date=4 March 2020}}</ref> at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Namur|University of Namur]] (new test method, Beno\u00eft Muylkens)<ref>{{cite news|language=English|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/100996/new-tests-to-diagnose-coronavirus-developped-by-university-of-namur/|title=New test to diagnose coronavirus developed by University of Namur|agency=The Brussels Times|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> and by private companies in collaboration with universities (new 15 minute test method detecting coronavirus [[antigen]]s, CORIS BioConcept).<ref>{{cite news|language=English|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/102707/coronavirus-belgium-develops-15-minute-virus-test/|title=Coronavirus: Belgium develops 15-minute virus test|agency=The Brussels Times|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAttempts to model and predict the progress of the SARS-CoV-2 virus spread with [[compartmental models in epidemiology|compartmental models]] are undertaken at [[Ghent University]] (Prof Jan M. Baetens)<ref>{{cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200327_04904938|title=Wat kunnen de wiskundige modellen echt voorspellen?|agency=De Standaard|date=28 March 2020}}</ref> and [[Hasselt University]] (Prof Niel Hens)<ref>{{cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/hasselt/universiteit-hasselt-leidt-europees-onderzoek-naar-verspreiding-corona~aebe3a0a/?referer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F|title=Universiteit Hasselt leidt Europees onderzoek naar verspreiding corona|agency=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>. Professor Barb\u00e9 at the [[Vrije Universiteit Brussel|Free University of Brussels-VUB]] uses a [[ordinary differential equation|first order differential equation]] with two [[proxy (statistics)|proxy variables]] (a and b):</br>\n:<math>\\frac{dy}{dt} + (at-b)y = 0</math></br>\n:with t = time</br>\n::y = a parameter such as the number of infections, number of hospitalisations or the number of intensive care cases.<ref>{{cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/aalst/voorspellingen-wiskundige-griezelig-accuraat-model-voorspelde-895-positieve-tests-voor-morgen-1-151-echt-belangrijk-om-nu-strikt-de-maatregelen-op-te-volgen~a08d5fd4/|title=Voorspellingen wiskundige griezelig accuraat: \u201cModel voorspelde 895 positieve tests, voor morgen 1.151. Echt belangrijk om nu strikt de maatregelen op te volgen\u201d|agency=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=nl|url=https://today.vub.be/nl/artikel/de-coronacurves-van-biostaticus-prof-dr-kurt-barb?fbclid=IwAR2nJCltczm81Mi_NIUvp1RPTpWaabhz3hQmtt3-3tpSfldBveUK4VD5X5E|title=De Coronacurves van biostatisticus prof. dr. Kurt Barb\u00e9|agency=VUB Today|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Secondary effects of the confinement measures==\nBelgian researchers at the [[Royal Observatory of Belgium]] noticed a drop of the background noise on the seismic data that could be the result of transport networks and other human activities being shut down.<ref>{{cite news|language=English|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00965-x|title=Coronavirus lockdowns have changed the way Earth moves|agency=Nature|date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|language=English|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/104128/belgiums-background-noise-reduces/|title=Belgium\u2019s \u2018background\u2019 noise reduces|agency=The Brussels Times|date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Belgian Institute for Space Aeronomy]] reported that the strong decrease in car and air traffic due to the confinement measures did not entail a strong decrease in air pollution.<ref>{{cite news|language=English|url=https://www.aeronomie.be/en/news/2020/corona-does-not-necessarily-imply-less-pollution?fbclid=IwAR2-LtCr_rlbPWh_9BjR5AFFTEUPSUNFiTImAN0sZo4PruKfTmguFNHKMs0|title=Corona does not necessarily imply less pollution|agency=Belgian Institute for Space Aeronomy|date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Confirmed infections===\nThe number of confirmed infections is the number of samples tested positive by a reference laboratory. It is estimated that the actual number of cases is much higher than the number of confirmed cases<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lalibre.be/planete/sante/coronavirus-pourquoi-le-nombre-de-cas-detectes-en-belgique-ne-represente-pas-grand-chose-5e67ab369978e201d8b553ac/|title=Coronavirus : pourquoi le nombre de cas d\u00e9tect\u00e9s en Belgique ne repr\u00e9sente pas grand-chose|date=2020-03-10|website=lalibre.be|language=fr|access-date=}}</ref>, the tests being limited to specific people and/or to people with severe symptoms. Diagnosed cases are an underestimate of the real number by a factor of between 5 and 10 according to Professor Marc Van Ranst.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/marc-van-ranst-werkelijk-aantal-besmettingen-ligt-waarschijnlijk-tien-keer-hoger~abf10dad/|title=Marc Van Ranst: \"Werkelijk aantal besmettingen ligt waarschijnlijk tien keer hoger\"|date=2020-03-09|website=hln.be|language=nl|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the period of 1 March to 6 March the number of detected cases [[exponential growth|grew on average exponentially]] with a doubling of the number of cases every day. In the period between 7 March and 27 March the number of confirmed cases doubled on average every 3.7{{nbsp}}days (20.9{{nbsp}}% daily increase).\n\n====By municipality====\nSciensano started to publish a map with incidence numbers per municipality starting 26 March. This map showed that the highest recorded concentrations of infections were found in [[Alken, Belgium|Alken]] and [[Sint-Truiden]] (Limburg) and [[Qu\u00e9vy]] and [[Honnelles]] (Hainaut). The hotspot in Alken is thought to have been caused by two parties that were allowed to go on in the weekend of 7 March.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.tvl.be/nieuws/tvl-nieuws-26-maart-2020-95538|title=TVL Nieuws, 26 maart 2020|publisher=TV Limburg|date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The mayor of Sint-Truiden, who was herself infected by the new corona virus, mentioned she did not understand the reason for the high incidence in her town. The only potential explanation so far were the festivities around [[carnival]] (24 February, 75th Verloure Moondagstoet).<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2020/03/24/burgemeester-van-sint-truiden-veerle-heeren-ook-getroffen-door-c/|title=Burgemeester van Sint-Truiden Veerle Heeren ook getroffen door corona: \"Mijn man ligt op intensieve zorg\"|publisher=VRT|date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The high level of cases in the affluent municipality of [[Bonheiden]] is thought to be linked with a high amount of families that returned from ski resorts in the North of Italy beginning of March.<ref>{{Cite news|language=nl|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200323_04899836|title=Imeldaziekenhuis op derde plaats qua aantal coronapati\u00ebnten|publisher=De Standaard|date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Both Qu\u00e9vy and Honnelles are located at the border with the French commune of [[Bavay]] in the [[Nord (French department)|Nord]] department. While the high incidence in Honnelles could be linked to an outbreak in a centre for disabled people, the mayor of Qu\u00e9vy had no idea what caused the high numbers in her municipality and complained about the lack of communication and protective equipment.<ref>{{Cite news|language=fr|url=https://www.7sur7.be/belgique/etat-de-sante-preoccupant-pour-quatre-pensionnaires-polyhandicapes-d-un-centre-a-honnelles~ae588e34/?referrer=https://www.google.com/|title=\u00c9tat de sant\u00e9 pr\u00e9occupant pour quatre pensionnaires polyhandicap\u00e9s d'un centre \u00e0 Honnelles|publisher=7sur7|date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|language=fr|url=https://www.lesoir.be/290485/article/2020-03-27/coronavirus-la-carte-de-levolution-des-contaminations-en-belgique-region-par|title=Coronavirus: la carte de l'\u00e9volution des contaminations en Belgique (r\u00e9gion par r\u00e9gion)|publisher=Le Soir|date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====By province====\nSciensano started to publish confirmed cases and incidence numbers per province starting 18 March. In the period between 17 March and 21 March it became clear that the province of Limburg was a hotspot for the coronavirus where the incidence grew much faster compared to the rest of the country: while on 17 March the incidence in Limburg was 1.5 times the average incidence for the country, this had already increased to 1.9 times the average incidence on 21 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epidemio.wiv-isp.be/ID/Documents/Covid19/Meest%20recente%20update.pdf|title=COVID-19 - Epidemiologische situatie|date=22 March 2020|website=Sciensano}}</ref> On 21 March it was observed that more than half of the patients in the hospital Oost-Limburg in [[Genk]] were from Turkish origin. Secretary of state [[Zuhal Demir]] urged the Turkish community in Limburg to abide by the quarantine measures.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/in-de-buurt/genk/-meer-dan-de-helft-van-coronapatienten-in-ziekenhuis-oost-limburg-in-genk-is-van-turkse-origine~a184b2da/|title=Meer dan de helft van coronapati\u00ebnten in Ziekenhuis Oost-Limburg in Genk is van Turkse origine|agency=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe daily Sciensano report of 28 March saw a spectacular rise of the incidence numbers for the province of Li\u00e8ge: from 19 confirmed cases per 100{{nbsp}}000 population on 27 March it rose to 77. This was due to underreporting by a lab in the province.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.lalibre.be/planete/sante/coronavirus-en-belgique-la-province-de-liege-apparait-desormais-fortement-touchee-le-point-region-par-region-cartes-5e7fce8b7b50a6162bd70b5d|title=Coronavirus en Belgique: la province de Li\u00e8ge appara\u00eet d\u00e9sormais fortement touch\u00e9e, le point r\u00e9gion par r\u00e9gion (CARTES)|agency=La Libre Belgique|date=28 March 2020}}</ref> On 29 March the province of Li\u00e8ge even became the second worst affected province in Belgium after Limburg.\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Belgium medical cases}}\n\n===Recoveries===\nThe official reports from the national public health institute do not refer to ''recovered'' people but only to ''discharged'' patients. The patients are discharged after resolution of symptoms, even though they are not being tested again before leaving the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/dossier/epidemie-de-coronavirus/detail_coronavirus-en-belgique-combien-y-a-t-il-de-patients-gueris?id=10464928|title=Coronavirus en Belgique : combien y a-t-il de patients gu\u00e9ris ?|publisher=[[RTBF]]|date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe number of recovered people who were tested positive but not admitted to hospital remains unknown as there is no follow-up on these cases. The total number of recoveries is therefore underestimated, particularly in a context where there are many undetected positive cases presenting mild symptoms and recovering as well.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.moustique.be/25689/le-nombre-de-personnes-gueries-autre-chiffre-sous-estime|title=Le nombre de personnes gu\u00e9ries, l\u2019autre chiffre sous-estim\u00e9|publisher=Moustique|date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The situation is similar in France.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.liberation.fr/checknews/2020/03/26/covid-19-combien-y-a-t-il-de-personnes-gueries-en-france_1781297|title=Covid-19 : combien y a-t-il de personnes gu\u00e9ries en France ?|publisher=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe first recovered case was on 15 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|url=https://www.rtbf.be/info/societe/detail_le-belge-contamine-par-le-coronavirus-peut-quitter-l-hopital-saint-pierre?id=10433696|title= Le Belge contamin\u00e9 par le coronavirus peut quitter l'h\u00f4pital Saint-Pierre|publisher=[[RTBF]]|date=2020-02-15}}</ref> As of 30 March, [[Sciensano]] reported a total of 1,527 discharged patients since the 15 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epidemio.wiv-isp.be/ID/Documents/Covid19/Meest%20recente%20update.pdf|title=COVID-19 - Epidemiologische situatie|date=30 March 2020|website=Sciensano|publisher=|language=nl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n===Deaths===\n[[File:COVID-19-EU-log-relative-deaths.svg|thumb|600px|Cumulative number of deaths per million inhabitants for European Union countries, over time. The legend is sorted in descending order of these values. Countries without COVID-19 deaths are omitted. Logarithmic vertical axis. Data source: [[ECDC]].<ref name=ECDC>{{cite web | url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/cases-2019-ncov-eueea |title = Situation update for the EU/EEA and the UK |accessdate= 15 March 2020 <!--08:00--> |website=www.ecdc.europa.eu |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> It is to be noted that it is possible that not all countries report the deaths in the same way.<ref>{{cite news |language=Dutch|title=Doden per inwoner zijn (nog) geen goede graadmeter|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20200401_04909908|accessdate=2 April 2020 |agency=De Standaard |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>]]In the period between 17 March and 21 March the number of deaths due to COVID-19 doubled on average every 1.4{{nbsp}}days (64{{nbsp}}% daily increase). Of the 289 first fatalities 3 were in the category 25 to 44 years of age, 22 were in the category 45 to 64 years of age, 58 in the category 65 to 74 years, 98 in the category 75 to 84 years and 108 in the category of 85 years and older.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} The youngest fatality overall in Belgium was a 12-year-old girl<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200331_04907911|title=Virologen aangeslagen door dood van 12-jarig meisje|publisher=Nieuwsblad|date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Belgian girl becomes Europe's youngest coronavirus victim: media |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-belgium-death/belgian-girl-becomes-europes-youngest-coronavirus-victim-media-idUSKBN21I1W8 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> while the oldest person to die was 104 years<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 1,850 new cases confirmed, 64 new deaths in Belgium|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/103161/coronavirus-1850-new-cases-confirmed-64-new-deaths/|accessdate=31 March 2020 |agency=The Brussels Times |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\nOn 25 March 2020 Belgium ranked 6th in the list of countries within the European Union with the highest amounts of casualties, while on 1 April Belgium had the third highest death toll, after Italy and Spain.\n\n===Herd immunity===\nOn 29 March an experiment at the UZ Brussel confirmed the suspicion that some Belgians are infected with the coronavirus without knowing it.\nStudies conducted by UZ Brussel on patients that are being treated for small procedures and who do not have COVID-19 symptoms, show that approximately 8{{nbsp}}% carry the virus and have an infection in the lungs.<ref>{{cite news|language=Dutch|url=https://www.hln.be/nieuws/binnenland/uz-brussel-test-alle-patienten-systematisch-8-procent-van-de-niet-covidpatienten-toch-besmet~a716f10f/|title=UZ Brussel test alle pati\u00ebnten systematisch: 8 procent van de niet-covidpati\u00ebnten toch besmet|publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws|date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Partial [[herd immunity]] can reduce the spread of the virus.\n\n===Graphs===\n{{Update|section|reason=data based on actual dates instead of report dates is now available|date=April 2020}}\n\n<div class=\"\" style=\"width:700px;\">\n'''Total cases in Belgium (cumulative)'''\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|colors=#FF6347,#0000FF, #87CEEB,#000000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Actual date\n|xAxisAngle=-60\n|xAxisMin=\n|xAxisMax=\n|x=30 Jan, 22 Feb, 24 Feb, 25 Feb, 26 Feb, 27 Feb, 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr<!--Please mention the effective date and not the date of reporting-->\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=\n|y1=1, 11, 15, 20, 23, 32, 37, 53, 69, 86, 122, 176, 257, 364, 391, 455, 549, 648, 818, 1064, 1399, 1575, 1792, 2180, 2596, 3132, 3844, 4506, 4973, 5461, 6776, 7932, 9109, 10442, 11923, 12743, 13404, 14930, 16188<!--Please use the raw data and not the numbers in daily reports-->\n|y1Title=Total cases (diagnostic date)\n|y2= ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  , 71, 161, 284, 467, 679, 974, 1306, 1596, 1874, 2308, 2848, 3338, 3913, 4542, 5087, 5572, 6132, 6716, 7294<!--Please use the raw data and not the numbers in daily reports--><!--Please mention the cumulated total of hospitalised cases and not the number of active hospitalised cases on each day-->\n|y2Title=Total hospitalisations (effective date)\n|y3= ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  