rea/>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 02583967<ref name=CensusArea/>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Belle Mead''' is an [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|unincorporated community]] and [[census-designated place]] (CDP) located within [[Montgomery Township, New Jersey|Montgomery Township]], in [[Somerset County, New Jersey|Somerset County]], [[New Jersey]], United States.<ref name=GCTPH1>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US34035 GCT-PH1 - Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County -- County Subdivision and Place from the 2010 Census Summary File 1 for Somerset County, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212201035/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US34035 |date=2020-02-12 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed February 13, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www2.census.gov/acs2010_5yr/summaryfile/UserTools/Geography/NJ.xls 2006-2010 American Community Survey Geography for New Jersey], [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed February 13, 2013.</ref><ref name=CPH232>[https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/cph-2-32.pdf New Jersey: 2010 - Population and Housing Unit Counts - 2010 Census of Population and Housing (CPH-2-32)], [[United States Census Bureau]], August 2012. Accessed February 13, 2013.</ref> As of the [[2010 United States Census]], the CDP's population was 216.<ref name=Census2010/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Belle Mead Station on the West Trenton.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Belle Mead station|Belle Mead]] railroad station located along the former [[Reading Railroad]] (proposed as a part of the [[West Trenton Line (NJ Transit)|West Trenton Line]])]]\nUp until about 1875, Belle Mead, then named Plainville, was considered to be part of the community of [[Harlingen, New Jersey|Harlingen]]. It was a quiet farming region when about that time a [[New York City]] contractor named Van Aken bought up all the local farms and set out to develop a city. He had the farms laid out into lots, some streets put through and named after the style of New York. He donated land for the railroad station that had a dining room underneath (the station was torn down in February, 1940).  There is an abandoned train station in Belle Mead. When Van Aken went broke, the property was sold to a [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]], [[John R. McPherson]], who changed the name from Vanaken to Belle Mead in honor of his daughter, Edna Belle Mead McPherson, according to one popular story.<ref name=Hillsborough>[http://www.hillsborough-nj.org/hillsborough-nj/towns/belle-mead/ Belle Mead History] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510105958/http://www.hillsborough-nj.org/hillsborough-nj/towns/belle-mead/ |date=2017-05-10 }}, Hillsborough Township. Accessed October 30, 2016.</ref>\n\nWoods Tavern in Belle Mead was a popular stop for travelers for more than 100 years and played an important social and political role. [[Horace Greeley]] spoke there in 1872 as part of his campaign for [[President of the United States]]. The tavern burned down in 1932.<ref name=Hillsborough />\n\n[[James Baldwin (writer)|James Baldwin]], the 20th-century author and civil rights advocate, lived in Belle Mead in the early 1940s.\n\nDr. [[John Summerskill]] and his wife, [[Mimi LaFollette Summerskill]] established the LaFollette Vineyard in Belle Mead in the 1970s. President [[Bill Clinton]] and 14 Democratic governors  met for a strategy session and press conference at the vineyard during the 1992 presidential campaign.\n\nThe [[Belle Mead (NJT station)|abandoned train station]] was built by [[Reading Railroad]] in the 1930s, and was removed from service in 1984. Since then, restoration projects have been announced, however, not one has progressed any further than cleaning up tree debris and graffiti.\n\nThe Belle Mead section straddles the northern portion of Montgomery Township and the southern portion of [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey|Hillsborough Township]].  For many years residents of Belle Mead had been served by the Belle Mead Post Office located on Route 206 in Montgomery Township having ZIP code 08502.  In the late 1990s, Hillsborough Township was granted its own post office serving all of its residents (ZIP code 08844), including that section of town formerly serving the Belle Mead area.  Since that time the Belle Mead post office and its associated ZIP code (08502) serves only the remaining area of Belle Mead located in the northern section of Montgomery Township.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], Belle Mead had a total area of 0.740 square miles (1.917&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>), all of which is land.<ref name=CensusArea/><ref name=\"GR1\" />\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n| 2010= 216\n| footnote=Population sources: 2010<ref name=Census2010/>\n}}\n\n===Census 2010===\n{{USCensusDemographics|year=2010|type=CDP|place=Belle Mead CDP|216|160|74.1|39|18.1|29|13.4|215|199|2|0|4|0|10|1|18|80|78|2|0.74|0.00|0.74|291.8|108.1|78|79.5|39.7|71.8|5.1|20.5|15.4|7.7|2.77|3.03|90.3|87.0|3.2|9.7|0.0|0.0|0.0|25.9|4.2|25.9|30.6|13.4|42.5|100.0|102.5}}\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Category see also|People from Montgomery Township, New Jersey}}\nPeople who were born in, residents of, or otherwise closely associated with Belle Mead include:\n* [[Wade Baldwin IV]] (born 1996), [[basketball]] player for the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]].<ref>Velazquez, Matt. [http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/sports/384030121.html \"Wade Baldwin shares interesting ties with Jason Kidd\"], ''[[Journal Sentinel]]'', June 2, 2016. Accessed July 4, 2016. \"Baldwin, a 6-foot-4 guard, grew up in Belle Mead, New Jersey.\"</ref>\n* [[Mike Ford (baseball)|Mike Ford]] (born 1992), [[first baseman]] for the [[New York Yankees]].<ref>Franklin, Paul. [https://www.nj.com/princeton/2014/04/hun_school_princeton_universit.html \"Mike Ford, Hun School and Princeton product, hitting books, balls hard in the minors; faces Lakewood this week\"], ''[[The Times (Trenton)]]'', April 21, 2014. Accessed June 26, 2019. \"Ford, a resident of Belle Mead who attended Montgomery High School as a freshman before transferring to the Hun School, has two doubles, two home runs and nine RBIs.\"</ref>\n* [[Brandon Grosso]] (born 2000), racecar driver in the [[ARCA Menards Series]].<ref>Radebaugh, Don. [https://www.arcaracing.com/articles/2009117-high-school-dirt-mod-ace-grosso-preps-for-full-pull-ahead-with-ksr High school dirt modified ace Grosso preps for full pull ahead with KSR], ARCARacing.com, Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n* [[Ricky Proehl]] (born 1968), wide receiver who played for 17 seasons in the NFL.<ref>Cavanaugh, Jack. [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/10/04/sports/crawford-hurt-in-army-loss.html \"Crawford Hurt In Army Loss\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 4, 1987. Accessed January 29, 2017. \"Then, Mike Elkins of Wake Forest and a sophomore wingback, Ricky Proehl of Belle Mead, N.J., combined on their second touchdown play with 2:46 remaining in the game, and Wilson Hoyle, who had kicked a 46-yard field-goal in the third period, added his second conversion to seal the triumph.\"</ref>\n* [[Elliott F. Smith]] (1931-1987), politician who served in the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] from 1978 to 1984, representing the [[16th Legislative District (New Jersey)|16th Legislative District]].<ref>Waggoner, Walter H. [https://www.nytimes.com/1977/10/14/archives/gop-faces-aggressive-challenge-in-central-jersey-assembly-race.html \"G .O .P . Faces Aggressive Challenge In Central Jersey Assembly Race\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 14, 1977. Accessed February 20, 2018. \"Their Republican opponents are Assemblyman Walter J. Cavanaugh of Somerville, who led the Republican ticket in the district when he was elected to his first term in 1975, and Elliott F. Smith of Belle Mead.\"</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Belle Mead}}\n\n{{Somerset County, New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Somerset County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Montgomery Township, New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Belle Mead, New Jersey\n|settlement_type          = [[Census-designated place]]\n|nickname                 =\n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Belle Mead, NJ.jpg\n|imagesize                = 250x200px\n|image_caption            = Looking north along Trent Avenue\n|image_flag               =\n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA New Jersey Somerset County#USA New Jersey#USA\n|pushpin_label_position   = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location of Belle Mead within Somerset County, New Jersey. (Inset: Location of Somerset County in New Jersey).\n|pushpin_mapsize          =\n|image_map                =\n|map_caption              =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|New Jersey}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Jersey|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Somerset County, New Jersey|Somerset]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[Township (New Jersey)|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[Montgomery Township, New Jersey|Montgomery]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=CensusArea>[http://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2010_place_list_34.txt Gazetteer of New Jersey Places], [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed July 21, 2016.</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 1.917\n|area_land_km2            = 1.917\n|area_water_km2           = 0.000\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 0.740\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 0.740\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.000\n|area_water_percent       = 0.00\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]]\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=Census2010>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3404630 DP-1 - Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data for Belle Mead CDP, New Jersey], [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed August 23, 2012.</ref>\n|population_total         = 216\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = 291.8\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Daylight Time|Eastern (EDT)]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref>{{Gnis|2583967|Belle Mead Census Designated Place}}, [[Geographic Names Information System]]. Accessed August 23, 2012.</ref>\n|elevation_m              = 30\n|elevation_ft             = 98\n|coordinates_footnotes    = <ref name=CensusArea/><ref name=\"GR1\">[https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990], [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 4, 2014.</ref>\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40.462445|-74.6744|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 08502<ref>[http://tools.usps.com/go/ZipLookupResultsAction!input.action?resultMode=0&city=belle%20mead&state=NJ Look Up a ZIP Code for Belle Mead, NJ], [[United States Postal Service]]. Accessed August 23, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/njzips.htm Zip Codes], State of [[New Jersey]]. Accessed August 27, 2013.</ref>\n|area_code                = [[Area code 609|609]] and [[Area codes 732 and 848|732/848]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 3404630<ref name=CensusArea/>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 02583967<ref name=CensusArea/>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Belle Mead''' is an [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|unincorporated community]] and [[census-designated place]] (CDP) located within [[Montgomery Township, New Jersey|Montgomery Township]], in [[Somerset County, New Jersey|Somerset County]], [[New Jersey]], United States.<ref name=GCTPH1>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US34035 GCT-PH1 - Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County -- County Subdivision and Place from the 2010 Census Summary File 1 for Somerset County, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212201035/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US34035 |date=2020-02-12 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed February 13, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www2.census.gov/acs2010_5yr/summaryfile/UserTools/Geography/NJ.xls 2006-2010 American Community Survey Geography for New Jersey], [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed February 13, 2013.</ref><ref name=CPH232>[https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/cph-2-32.pdf New Jersey: 2010 - Population and Housing Unit Counts - 2010 Census of Population and Housing (CPH-2-32)], [[United States Census Bureau]], August 2012. Accessed February 13, 2013.</ref> As of the [[2010 United States Census]], the CDP's population was 216.<ref name=Census2010/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Belle Mead Station on the West Trenton.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Belle Mead station|Belle Mead]] railroad station located along the former [[Reading Railroad]] (proposed as a part of the [[West Trenton Line (NJ Transit)|West Trenton Line]])]]\nUp until about 1875, Belle Mead, then named Plainville, was considered to be part of the community of [[Harlingen, New Jersey|Harlingen]]. It was a quiet farming region when about that time a [[New York City]] contractor named Van Aken bought up all the local farms and set out to develop a city. He had the farms laid out into lots, some streets put through and named after the style of New York. He donated land for the railroad station that had a dining room underneath (the station was torn down in February, 1940).  There is an abandoned train station in Belle Mead. When Van Aken went broke, the property was sold to a [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]], [[John R. McPherson]], who changed the name from Vanaken to Belle Mead in honor of his daughter, Edna Belle Mead McPherson, according to one popular story.<ref name=Hillsborough>[http://www.hillsborough-nj.org/hillsborough-nj/towns/belle-mead/ Belle Mead History] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510105958/http://www.hillsborough-nj.org/hillsborough-nj/towns/belle-mead/ |date=2017-05-10 }}, Hillsborough Township. Accessed October 30, 2016.</ref>\n\nWoods Tavern in Belle Mead was a popular stop for travelers for more than 100 years and played an important social and political role. [[Horace Greeley]] spoke there in 1872 as part of his campaign for [[President of the United States]]. The tavern burned down in 1932.<ref name=Hillsborough />\n\n[[James Baldwin (writer)|James Baldwin]], the 20th-century author and civil rights advocate, lived in Belle Mead in the early 1940s.\n\nDr. [[John Summerskill]] and his wife, [[Mimi LaFollette Summerskill]] established the LaFollette Vineyard in Belle Mead in the 1970s. President [[Bill Clinton]] and 14 Democratic governors  met for a strategy session and press conference at the vineyard during the 1992 presidential campaign.\n\nThe [[Belle Mead (NJT station)|abandoned train station]] was built by [[Reading Railroad]] in the 1930s, and was removed from service in 1984. Since then, restoration projects have been announced, however, not one has progressed any further than cleaning up tree debris and graffiti.\n\nThe Belle Mead section straddles the northern portion of Montgomery Township and the southern portion of [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey|Hillsborough Township]].  For many years residents of Belle Mead had been served by the Belle Mead Post Office located on Route 206 in Montgomery Township having ZIP code 08502.  In the late 1990s, Hillsborough Township was granted its own post office serving all of its residents (ZIP code 08844), including that section of town formerly serving the Belle Mead area.  Since that time the Belle Mead post office and its associated ZIP code (08502) serves only the remaining area of Belle Mead located in the northern section of Montgomery Township.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], Belle Mead had a total area of 0.740 square miles (1.917&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>), all of which is land.<ref name=CensusArea/><ref name=\"GR1\" />\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n| 2010= 216\n| footnote=Population sources: 2010<ref name=Census2010/>\n}}\n\n===Census 2010===\n{{USCensusDemographics|year=2010|type=CDP|place=Belle Mead CDP|216|160|74.1|39|18.1|29|13.4|215|199|2|0|4|0|10|1|18|80|78|2|0.74|0.00|0.74|291.8|108.1|78|79.5|39.7|71.8|5.1|20.5|15.4|7.7|2.77|3.03|90.3|87.0|3.2|9.7|0.0|0.0|0.0|25.9|4.2|25.9|30.6|13.4|42.5|100.0|102.5}}\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Category see also|People from Montgomery Township, New Jersey}}\nPeople who were born in, residents of, or otherwise closely associated with Belle Mead include:\n* [[Wade Baldwin IV]] (born 1996), [[basketball]] player for the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]].<ref>Velazquez, Matt. [http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/sports/384030121.html \"Wade Baldwin shares interesting ties with Jason Kidd\"], ''[[Journal Sentinel]]'', June 2, 2016. Accessed July 4, 2016. \"Baldwin, a 6-foot-4 guard, grew up in Belle Mead, New Jersey.\"</ref>\n* [[Mike Ford (baseball)|Mike Ford]] (born 1992), [[first baseman]] for the [[New York Yankees]].<ref>Franklin, Paul. [https://www.nj.com/princeton/2014/04/hun_school_princeton_universit.html \"Mike Ford, Hun School and Princeton product, hitting books, balls hard in the minors; faces Lakewood this week\"], ''[[The Times (Trenton)]]'', April 21, 2014. Accessed June 26, 2019. \"Ford, a resident of Belle Mead who attended Montgomery High School as a freshman before transferring to the Hun School, has two doubles, two home runs and nine RBIs.\"</ref>\n* [[Brandon Grosso]] (born 2000), racecar driver in the [[ARCA Menards Series]].<ref>Radebaugh, Don. [https://www.arcaracing.com/articles/2009117-high-school-dirt-mod-ace-grosso-preps-for-full-pull-ahead-with-ksr High school dirt modified ace Grosso preps for full pull ahead with KSR], ARCARacing.com, Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n* [[Ricky Proehl]] (born 1968), wide receiver who played for 17 seasons in the NFL.<ref>Cavanaugh, Jack. [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/10/04/sports/crawford-hurt-in-army-loss.html \"Crawford Hurt In Army Loss\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 4, 1987. Accessed January 29, 2017. \"Then, Mike Elkins of Wake Forest and a sophomore wingback, Ricky Proehl of Belle Mead, N.J., combined on their second touchdown play with 2:46 remaining in the game, and Wilson Hoyle, who had kicked a 46-yard field-goal in the third period, added his second conversion to seal the triumph.\"</ref>\n* [[Elliott F. Smith]] (1931-1987), politician who served in the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] from 1978 to 1984, representing the [[16th Legislative District (New Jersey)|16th Legislative District]].<ref>Waggoner, Walter H. [https://www.nytimes.com/1977/10/14/archives/gop-faces-aggressive-challenge-in-central-jersey-assembly-race.html \"G .O .P . Faces Aggressive Challenge In Central Jersey Assembly Race\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 14, 1977. Accessed February 20, 2018. \"Their Republican opponents are Assemblyman Walter J. Cavanaugh of Somerville, who led the Republican ticket in the district when he was elected to his first term in 1975, and Elliott F. Smith of Belle Mead.\"</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Belle Mead}}\n\n{{Somerset County, New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Somerset County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Montgomery Township, New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "No1lakersfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor area code fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belle_Mead,_New_Jersey"}
{"title_page": "Ludwig Bemelmans", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Ludwig Bemelmans\n| image        = Ludwig Bemelmans.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1898|4|27}}\n| birth_place   = [[Meran]], South Tyrol, [[Austria-Hungary]] (now Italy)\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1962|10|1|1898|4|27}}\n|death_place = [[New York City]], United States\n| resting_place = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| occupation    = Writer, illustrator\n| nationality  = \n| ethnicity    = \n| citizenship  = {{flagicon|Austro-Hungary}} Austria-Hungary<br>{{flagicon|USA}} United States (from 1918)\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = \n| period       = \n| genre        = [[Children's literature|Children's]] [[picture books]]\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = ''[[Madeline]]'' series (1939\u20131999)\n| spouse       = [[Madeleine Bemelmans]]\n| partner      = \n| children     = [[Barbara Bemelmans]]\n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = {{awd |[[Caldecott Medal]] |1954}}\n| signature    = \n| signature_alt = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n\n'''Ludwig Bemelmans''' (April 26, 1898 \u2013 October 1, 1962<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/deborahljacobs/2013/11/27/madeline-and-the-family-business-2/ |title=Madeline And The Family Business |last=Jacobs |first=Deborah L. |date=27 November 2013 |website=Forbes |language=en |access-date=2017-10-22}}</ref>) was an Austrian-born American writer and [[illustrator]] of children's books. He is known best for the ''[[Madeline]]'' picture books. Six were published since 1939.<ref name=\"CullinanPerson2005\">{{cite book|last1=Cullinan|first1=Bernice E.|last2=Person|first2=Diane Goetz|title=The Continuum Encyclopedia of Children's Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0LyutQg6mroC&pg=PA76|accessdate=August 25, 2015|year=2005|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780826417787|pages=76\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBemelmans was born to the Belgian painter Lambert Bemelmans and the German Frances Fischer in [[Meran]], [[Austria-Hungary]] (now Italy). His father owned a hotel. He grew up in [[Gmunden]] on the [[Traunsee]] in [[Upper Austria]]. His first language was French and his second German.\n\nIn 1904, his father left his wife and Ludwig\u2019s [[governess]], both of whom were pregnant with his child, for another woman,<ref name=\"The New York Times 2018\" /> after which his mother took Ludwig and his brother to her native city of [[Regensburg]], Germany. Bemelmans had difficulty in school, as he hated the German style of discipline. He was [[apprentice]]d to his uncle Hans Bemelmans at a hotel in Austria. In a 1941 ''New York Times'' interview with Robert van Gelder, he related that while an apprentice, he was regularly beaten and even whipped by the headwaiter. According to Bemelmans, he finally warned the headwaiter that if he was whipped again he would retaliate with a gun. The headwaiter ignored his warning, whipped him, and Bemelmans reportedly shot and seriously wounded him in retaliation.<ref name=\"The New York Times 2018\">{{cite web | title=How the Author of 'Madeline' Created His Most Famous Character | website=The New York Times | date=27 April 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/27/style/madeleine-author-illustrator.html | access-date=3 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Gelder|first=Robert|date=January 26, 1941|title=An Interview with Ludwig Bemelmans|url=|journal=New York Times|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Given the choice between reform school and emigration to the United States, he chose the latter.<ref name=roberts/> It is likely this was one of Bemelman\u2019s famous yarns, since in John Bemelmans Marciano\u2019s biography of his grandfather, he relates a simpler story: recognizing that Ludwig was an incorrigible boy, his uncle offered him the choice of going to America (where his father now lived), or going to reform school.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Bemelmans: The Life and Art of Madeline's Creator|last=Marciano|first=John Bemelmans|publisher=Viking|year=1999|isbn=0-670-88460-X|location=New York, NY|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780670884605}}</ref><br /><!-- supports two preceding sentences except does not locate hotel (calls Hans owner); see TALK#Austrian -->\n\n==In America==\nHe spent the next several years working at hotels and restaurants in the US. In 1917, he joined the [[U.S. Army]] but was not sent to Europe because of his German origins. He did became an officer, and was promoted to Second Lieutenant. He writes of his experiences in the Army in the book, ''My War With the United States''. <ref>{{Cite book|title=My WR with the United States|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Modern Library|year=1941|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In 1918, he became a US citizen.\n\nIn the 1920s, Bemelemans tried to become an artist and painter while working at hotels, but had substantial difficulties. In 1926, he quit his job at the Ritz Carlton in New York to become a full time cartoonist.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Bemelmans: The life and Art of Madeline's Creator|last=Marciano|first=John Bemelmans|publisher=Viking|year=1999|isbn=0-670-88460-X|location=New York, NY|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780670884605}}</ref>  His cartoon series ''The Thrilling Adventures of the Count Bric a Brac'' was dropped from the ''[[New York World]]'' after six months. He associated with [[Ervine Metzl]], a commercial artist and illustrator who is variously described as Bemelmans's friend,<ref name=\"wonderful\">{{cite book|author=Ludwig Bemelmans, Madeleine Bemelmans|title=Tell Them It Was Wonderful: Selected Writings|publisher=Viking|year=1985|accessdate=May 24, 2010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OT5aAAAAMAAJ&q=metzl+inauthor:bemelmans&dq=metzl+inauthor:bemelmans&cd=2|page=159|isbn=9780670803910}}</ref><ref name=allitsfaults /> \"agent\",<ref name=\"allitsfaults\">{{cite book|title=With All Its Faults: A Candid Account of Forty Years in Advertising|author=Fairfax M. Cone|publisher=Little, Brown|year=1969|url=https://www.google.com/#num=20&hl=en&q=%22irvin%20metzl%22&um=1&ie=UTF-8&tbo=u&tbs=bks:1&source=og&sa=N&tab=wp&fp=6f78d0ffc1b1e58c|accessdate=May 24, 2010}}</ref> and \"ghost artist\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Sixth book of junior authors & illustrators|url=https://archive.org/details/sixthbookofjunio00holt|url-access=registration|editor=Sally Holmes Holtze|year=1989|publisher=H. W. Wilson|page=[https://archive.org/details/sixthbookofjunio00holt/page/25 25]|author=Ron Barrett}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\n{{Refimprove section|date=March 2018}}\nIn the early 1930s Bemelmans met [[May Massee]], the children's book editor at [[Viking Press]], who became a sort of partner.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Bemelmans: The Life and Art of Madeline's Creator|last=Marciano|first=John Bemelmans|publisher=Viking|year=1999|isbn=0-670-88460-X|location=New York, NY|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780670884605}}</ref> He began to publish children's books, beginning with ''Hansi'' in 1934.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Hansi|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Vintage|year=1934|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> He published the first ''Madeline'' book in 1939; after being rejected by Viking, it was published by [[Simon & Schuster]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/article/63258-madeline-in-new-york-ludwig-bemelmans-at-the-new-york-historical-society.html|title=Madeline in New York: Ludwig Bemelmans at the New-York Historical Society|work=PublishersWeekly.com|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en}}</ref>  The book was a great success. Bemelmans did not write a second Madeline book until 1953, when he published ''Madeline\u2019s Rescue''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Madeline's Rescue|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Viking|year=1953|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Four more books in the series were subsequently published while he was alive, and one more was published posthumously in 1999. \n\nUp until the early 1950s, the artistic media he worked in were pen and ink, water color, and gouache. As he describes in his autobiographical ''My Life in Art'',<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Life in Art|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Harper & Brothers|year=1954|isbn=|location=New York, NY|pages=}}</ref> he had avoided oil painting because it did not permit him to produce artistic pieces quickly. But at this point in his life, he wanted to master the richness of oil painting. To this end, he set out to buy a property in Paris that would serve as a serious, full-blown art studio. In 1953, he fell in love with a small [[bistro]] in Paris, {{ill|La Colombe (cabaret)|lt=La Colombe|fr}} in the ''[[Ile de la Cit\u00e9]]'', and bought it, intending to convert it into a studio. He painted [[mural]]s therein, but the project was a disaster owing to French bureaucracy, and after two years of frustration and disappointment, he unloaded it by selling it to [[Michel Valette]], who converted it into a notable [[cabaret]].\n\nBemelmans also wrote a number of adult books, including travel, humorous works and novels, as well as movie scripts. The latter included ''[[Yolanda and the Thief]]''. While spending time in [[Hollywood]], he became a close friend of interior decorator [[Elsie de Wolfe|Elsie de Wolfe, Lady Mendl]].\n\nA mural on the walls of the [[Carlyle Hotel]]'s Bemelmans Bar in New York City, ''Central Park'', is his only artwork on display to the public. He painted the children's dining room on [[Aristotle Onassis]]'s yacht ''Christina'' (now the ''[[Christina O]]''), for the young daughter of the magnate, [[Christina Onassis]].\n\n===Madeline series===\nEach Madeline story begins: \"In an old house in Paris, that was covered with vines, lived twelve little girls in two straight lines... the smallest one was Madeline.\" The girls are cared for by Miss Clavel. She is likely a nun, as some French orders called themselves Madames, particularly that of St. [[Madeleine Sophie Barat]],<ref>[http://sofie.org/resources/founding-mothers/madeleine-sophie-barat St. Madeleine Sophie Barat], founder of the order</ref> after which this convent school seems to be modeled; and \"Mrs.\" would not be an appropriate equivalent in English. Some have argued that Miss Clavel's apparel looks more like that of a nurse (although why a nurse is working in what appears to be a Paris convent school is not explained).\n\nOther characters include Pepito, son of the Spanish ambassador, who lives next door; Lord Cucuface, owner of the house; and Genevieve, a dog who rescues Madeline from [[drowning]] in the second book. Bemelmans published six Madeline stories in his lifetime, five as picture books and one in a magazine. A seventh was discovered after his death and published posthumously:\n\n#''[[Madeline (book)|Madeline]]'', 1939: in which Madeline must have her appendix removed\n#''[[Madeline's Rescue]]'', 1953: in which Madeline is rescued from drowning by a dog (later named Genevieve). Winner of the [[Caldecott Medal]] for U.S. [[picture book]] illustration\n#''[[Madeline and the Bad Hat]]'', 1956: in which the \"bad hat\" is Pepito, the Spanish ambassador's son, whose cruel antics outrage Madeline.\n#''[[Madeline and the Gypsies]]'', 1959: in which Madeline and Pepito have an adventure at a circus.\n#''[[Madeline in London]]'', 1961: in which Pepito moves to London, and Madeline and the girls go to visit him.\n#''[[Madeline's Christmas]]'', 1985: in which everyone in the house catches cold, except Madeline. (First published in ''[[McCall's]]'' in 1956).\n#''[[Madeline in America and Other Holiday Tales]]'', 1999: in which Madeline inherits a fortune from her American great-grandfather. The book also reveals Madeline's full name, Madeline Fogg.\n\n===Adaptations===\n*The first book, ''Madeline'', was adapted as an [[Academy Award]]-nominated 1952 [[short subject|short]] [[Animation|animated]] cartoon directed by Robert Cannon for [[United Productions of America|UPA]] and released by [[Columbia Pictures]], also titled ''[[List of UPA cartoons#Theatrical filmography - 1952: Madeline \u2013 Academy Award Nominee|Madeline]]''.\n*Between 1988 and 2002, an animated ''[[Madeline (TV series)|Madeline]]'' series was made for television (plus one direct-to-video film ''[[Madeline: Lost in Paris]]''), with the narration in rhyming style read by [[Christopher Plummer]].\n* A [[live-action]] ''[[Madeline (1998 film)|Madeline]]'' film based on several of the books appeared in 1998, directed by [[Daisy von Scherler Mayer]] and starring [[Hatty Jones]] as Madeline, [[Frances McDormand]] as Miss Clavel, and [[Nigel Hawthorne]] as Lord Covington.\n* Bemelmans's first novel, ''Madeline'', was briefly satirized on a February 2020 episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' by comedian and drag performer [[Ru Paul]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/snl-rupaul-gives-remedial-drag-lesson/606295/|title=RuPaul's Remedial Queer Comedy on Saturday Night Live|date=February 8, 2020|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=David|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/09/arts/television/saturday-night-live-rupaul.html|title='SNL' takes aim at Democratic presidential debate in New Hampshire|date=February 9, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBemelmans is said to have met his future wife, Madeleine \"Mimi\" Freund, as a model in Metzl's studio.<ref name=\"namesfamiliar\">{{cite book|author=Laura Lee|title=The Name's Familiar II|publisher=Pelican Publishing Co.|year=2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dwf1YYxQmRsC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=metzl+bemelmans#v=onepage&q=metzl%20bemelmans&f=false|accessdate=May 22, 2010|pages=25|isbn=9781455609178}}</ref> They had one daughter, Barbara, and three grandchildren, Paul Marciano, James Marciano, and [[John Bemelmans Marciano]].<ref name=\"Madelineandfamilybusiness\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/deborahljacobs/2013/11/27/madeline-and-the-family-business-2/|title=Madeline And The Family Business|first=Deborah L.|last=Jacobs|date=November 27, 2013|accessdate=July 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBemelmans died in New York of pancreatic cancer, aged 64 and was buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. <ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/21771/ludwig-bemelmans</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* 1934: ''Hansi''\n* 1936: ''The Golden Basket''\n* 1937: ''My War with the United States''\n* 1937: ''The Castle Number Nine''\n* 1938: ''Life Class'' \u2013 An autobiographical sketch.\n* 1938: ''Quito Express'' (travel book)\n* 1939: ''Madeline''\n* 1939: ''Small Beer'' (humorous memoirs based on his experiences in Europe and Hollywood)\n* 1940: ''Fifi''\n* 1941: ''At Your Service''\n* 1941: ''Hotel Splendide''\n* 1941: ''The Donkey Inside''\n* 1942: ''Rosebud''\n* 1942: ''I Love You, I Love You, I Love You''\n* 1943: ''Now I Lay Me Down to Sleep''\n* 1945: ''The Blue Danube''\n* 1946: ''Hotel Bemelmans''\n* 1947: ''A Tale of Two Glimps''\n* 1947: ''Dirty Eddie''\n* 1948: ''The Best of Times: An Account of Europe Revisited''\n* 1949: ''The Eye of God''\n* 1950: ''Sunshine: A Story about the City of New York''\n* 1952: ''How to Travel Incognito''\n* 1952: ''The Happy Place''\n* 1953: ''Father, Dear Father''\n* 1953: ''Madeline's Rescue''\n* 1953: ''The Borrowed Christmas''\n* 1954: ''The High World''\n* 1955: ''Parsley''\n* 1955: ''To the One I Love the Best'' \u2013 Bemelmans narrates his friendship with [[Elsie de Wolfe|Elsie de Wolfe, Lady Mendl]].\n* 1956: ''Madeline and the Bad Hat''\n* 1957: ''The Woman of My Life''\n* 1958: ''My Life in Art''\n* 1959: ''Madeline and the Gypsies''\n* 1960: ''Welcome Home!''\n* 1960: ''Are You Hungry, Are You Cold''\n* 1960: ''How to Travel To Europe All to Yourself''\n* 1961: ''Italian Holiday''\n* 1961: ''Madeline in London''\n* 1962: ''Marina''\n* 1962: ''On Board Noah's Ark''\n* 1963: ''The Street Where the Heart Lies'' <!-- completed by Bemelmans? -->\n* 1964: ''La Bonne Table''. Excerpts and essays involving food and drink, edited by Donald and Eleanor Friede\n* 1966: ''The Elephant Cutlet'' <!-- completed by Bemelmans? -->\n* 1985: ''Tell Them It Was Wonderful: Selected Writings'' (compilation of various autobiographical stories, published posthumously)\n* 1985: ''Madeline's Christmas'' (published 1956 in ''[[McCall's]]'')\n* 1999: ''Madeline in America and Other Holiday Tales''\n* 2004: ''Hotel Bemelmans'' (introduction by Anthony Bourdain) <Overlook Press, New York>\n{{colend}}\n\n* 2004: When You Lunch With The Emperor: The Adventures Of Ludwig Bemelmans (introduction by Andrew Goodfellow) Overlook Press, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist |refs=\n<ref name=roberts>\n[http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/16664887/food \"At the old Ritz\u2013Carlton the best tables went to society snobs, not to celebrities\"]. Food: [[Mich\u00e8le Roberts]]. ''[[New Statesmen]]''. April 11, 2005. Page 57. [http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/16664887/food Abstract at EBSCOhost:food]; article available from some libraries.<!-- PDF retrieved 2013-02-15 but used only to expand the bare URL and discount the source for calling him \"Austrian\" --></ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Commons category|Ludwig Bemelmans}}\n{{Portal|Children's literature |Visual arts }}\n* [http://www.smithsonianmagazine.com/issues/1998/july/bemelman.php \"The Man Who Dreamed Up Madeline\"], ''Smithsonian Magazine''\n* {{IMDb name|id=0069840|name=Ludwig Bemelmans}}\n* [http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/lbemelmans.htm Ludwig Bemelmans] at the [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n* [http://lccn.loc.gov/n50007160 Ludwig Bemelmans] at [[Library of Congress]] Authorities \u2014 with catalog records\n\n{{Madeline}}\n{{Society of Illustrators' Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bemelmans, Ludwig}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]] <!-- see TALK#Austrian -->\n[[Category:Writers who illustrated their own writing]]\n[[Category:Caldecott Medal winners]]\n[[Category:American children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Newbery Honor winners]]\n[[Category:Madeline]]\n[[Category:Austro-Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Austrian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Belgian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Gmunden]]\n[[Category:People from Merano]] <!-- merely born there -->\n[[Category:People from the County of Tyrol]] <!-- merely born there -->\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Ludwig Bemelmans\n| image        = Ludwig Bemelmans.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1898|4|27}}\n| birth_place   = [[Meran]], South Tyrol, [[Austria-Hungary]] (now Italy)\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1962|10|1|1898|4|27}}\n|death_place = [[New York City]], United States\n| resting_place = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| occupation    = Writer, illustrator\n| nationality  = \n| ethnicity    = \n| citizenship  = {{flagicon|Austro-Hungary}} Austria-Hungary<br>{{flagicon|USA}} United States (from 1918)\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = \n| period       = \n| genre        = [[Children's literature|Children's]] [[picture books]]\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = ''[[Madeline]]'' series (1939\u20131999)\n| spouse       = [[Madeleine Bemelmans]]\n| partner      = \n| children     = [[Barbara Bemelmans]]\n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = {{awd |[[Caldecott Medal]] |1954}}\n| signature    = \n| signature_alt = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n\n'''Ludwig Bemelmans''' (April 26, 1898 \u2013 October 1, 1962<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/deborahljacobs/2013/11/27/madeline-and-the-family-business-2/ |title=Madeline And The Family Business |last=Jacobs |first=Deborah L. |date=27 November 2013 |website=Forbes |language=en |access-date=2017-10-22}}</ref>) was an Austrian-born American writer and [[illustrator]] of children's books. He is known best for the ''[[Madeline]]'' picture books. Six were published since 1939.<ref name=\"CullinanPerson2005\">{{cite book|last1=Cullinan|first1=Bernice E.|last2=Person|first2=Diane Goetz|title=The Continuum Encyclopedia of Children's Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0LyutQg6mroC&pg=PA76|accessdate=August 25, 2015|year=2005|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780826417787|pages=76\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBemelmans was born to the Belgian painter Lambert Bemelmans and the German Frances Fischer in [[Meran]], [[Austria-Hungary]] (now Italy). His father owned a hotel. He grew up in [[Gmunden]] on the [[Traunsee]] in [[Upper Austria]]. His first language was French and his second German.\n\nIn 1904, his father left his wife and Ludwig\u2019s [[governess]], both of whom were pregnant with his child, for another woman,<ref name=\"The New York Times 2018\" /> after which his mother took Ludwig and his brother to her native city of [[Regensburg]], Germany. Bemelmans had difficulty in school, as he hated the German style of discipline. He was [[apprentice]]d to his uncle Hans Bemelmans at a hotel in Austria. In a 1941 ''New York Times'' interview with Robert van Gelder, he related that while an apprentice, he was regularly beaten and even whipped by the headwaiter. According to Bemelmans, he finally warned the headwaiter that if he was whipped again he would retaliate with a gun. The headwaiter ignored his warning, whipped him, and Bemelmans reportedly shot and seriously wounded him in retaliation.<ref name=\"The New York Times 2018\">{{cite web | title=How the Author of 'Madeline' Created His Most Famous Character | website=The New York Times | date=27 April 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/27/style/madeleine-author-illustrator.html | access-date=3 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Gelder|first=Robert|date=January 26, 1941|title=An Interview with Ludwig Bemelmans|url=|journal=New York Times|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Given the choice between reform school and emigration to the United States, he chose the latter.<ref name=roberts/> It is likely this was one of Bemelman\u2019s famous yarns, since in John Bemelmans Marciano\u2019s biography of his grandfather, he relates a simpler story: recognizing that Ludwig was an incorrigible boy, his uncle offered him the choice of going to America (where his father now lived), or going to reform school.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Bemelmans: The Life and Art of Madeline's Creator|last=Marciano|first=John Bemelmans|publisher=Viking|year=1999|isbn=0-670-88460-X|location=New York, NY|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780670884605}}</ref>\n\n<br /><!-- supports two preceding sentences except does not locate hotel (calls Hans owner); see TALK#Austrian -->\n\n==In America==\nHe spent the next several years working at hotels and restaurants in the US. In 1917, he joined the [[U.S. Army]] but was not sent to Europe because of his German origins. He did became an officer, and was promoted to Second Lieutenant. He writes of his experiences in the Army in the book, ''My War With the United States''. <ref>{{Cite book|title=My WR with the United States|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Modern Library|year=1941|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In 1918, he became a US citizen.\n\nIn the 1920s, Bemelemans tried to become an artist and painter while working at hotels, but had substantial difficulties. In 1926, he quit his job at the Ritz Carlton in New York to become a full time cartoonist.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Bemelmans: The life and Art of Madeline's Creator|last=Marciano|first=John Bemelmans|publisher=Viking|year=1999|isbn=0-670-88460-X|location=New York, NY|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780670884605}}</ref>  His cartoon series ''The Thrilling Adventures of the Count Bric a Brac'' was dropped from the ''[[New York World]]'' after six months. He associated with [[Ervine Metzl]], a commercial artist and illustrator who is variously described as Bemelmans's friend,<ref name=\"wonderful\">{{cite book|author=Ludwig Bemelmans, Madeleine Bemelmans|title=Tell Them It Was Wonderful: Selected Writings|publisher=Viking|year=1985|accessdate=May 24, 2010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OT5aAAAAMAAJ&q=metzl+inauthor:bemelmans&dq=metzl+inauthor:bemelmans&cd=2|page=159|isbn=9780670803910}}</ref><ref name=allitsfaults /> \"agent\",<ref name=\"allitsfaults\">{{cite book|title=With All Its Faults: A Candid Account of Forty Years in Advertising|author=Fairfax M. Cone|publisher=Little, Brown|year=1969|url=https://www.google.com/#num=20&hl=en&q=%22irvin%20metzl%22&um=1&ie=UTF-8&tbo=u&tbs=bks:1&source=og&sa=N&tab=wp&fp=6f78d0ffc1b1e58c|accessdate=May 24, 2010}}</ref> and \"ghost artist\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Sixth book of junior authors & illustrators|url=https://archive.org/details/sixthbookofjunio00holt|url-access=registration|editor=Sally Holmes Holtze|year=1989|publisher=H. W. Wilson|page=[https://archive.org/details/sixthbookofjunio00holt/page/25 25]|author=Ron Barrett}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\n{{Refimprove section|date=March 2018}}\nIn the early 1930s Bemelmans met [[May Massee]], the children's book editor at [[Viking Press]], who became a sort of partner.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Bemelmans: The Life and Art of Madeline's Creator|last=Marciano|first=John Bemelmans|publisher=Viking|year=1999|isbn=0-670-88460-X|location=New York, NY|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780670884605}}</ref> He began to publish children's books, beginning with ''Hansi'' in 1934.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Hansi|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Vintage|year=1934|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> He published the first ''Madeline'' book in 1939; after being rejected by Viking, it was published by [[Simon & Schuster]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/article/63258-madeline-in-new-york-ludwig-bemelmans-at-the-new-york-historical-society.html|title=Madeline in New York: Ludwig Bemelmans at the New-York Historical Society|work=PublishersWeekly.com|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en}}</ref>  The book was a great success. Bemelmans did not write a second Madeline book until 1953, when he published ''Madeline\u2019s Rescue''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Madeline's Rescue|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Viking|year=1953|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Four more books in the series were subsequently published while he was alive, and one more was published posthumously in 1999. \n\nUp until the early 1950s, the artistic media he worked in were pen and ink, water color, and gouache. As he describes in his autobiographical ''My Life in Art'',<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Life in Art|last=Bemelmans|first=Ludwig|publisher=Harper & Brothers|year=1954|isbn=|location=New York, NY|pages=}}</ref> he had avoided oil painting because it did not permit him to produce artistic pieces quickly. But at this point in his life, he wanted to master the richness of oil painting. To this end, he set out to buy a property in Paris that would serve as a serious, full-blown art studio. In 1953, he fell in love with a small [[bistro]] in Paris, {{ill|La Colombe (cabaret)|lt=La Colombe|fr}} in the ''[[Ile de la Cit\u00e9]]'', and bought it, intending to convert it into a studio. He painted [[mural]]s therein, but the project was a disaster owing to French bureaucracy, and after two years of frustration and disappointment, he unloaded it by selling it to [[Michel Valette]], who converted it into a notable [[cabaret]].\n\nBemelmans also wrote a number of adult books, including travel, humorous works and novels, as well as movie scripts. The latter included ''[[Yolanda and the Thief]]''. While spending time in [[Hollywood]], he became a close friend of interior decorator [[Elsie de Wolfe|Elsie de Wolfe, Lady Mendl]].\n\nA mural on the walls of the [[Carlyle Hotel]]'s Bemelmans Bar in New York City, ''Central Park'', is his only artwork on display to the public. He painted the children's dining room on [[Aristotle Onassis]]'s yacht ''Christina'' (now the ''[[Christina O]]''), for the young daughter of the magnate, [[Christina Onassis]].\n\n===Madeline series===\nEach Madeline story begins: \"In an old house in Paris, that was covered with vines, lived twelve little girls in two straight lines... the smallest one was Madeline.\" The girls are cared for by Miss Clavel. She is likely a nun, as some French orders called themselves Madames, particularly that of St. [[Madeleine Sophie Barat]],<ref>[http://sofie.org/resources/founding-mothers/madeleine-sophie-barat St. Madeleine Sophie Barat], founder of the order</ref> after which this convent school seems to be modeled; and \"Mrs.\" would not be an appropriate equivalent in English. Some have argued that Miss Clavel's apparel looks more like that of a nurse (although why a nurse is working in what appears to be a Paris convent school is not explained).\n\nOther characters include Pepito, son of the Spanish ambassador, who lives next door; Lord Cucuface, owner of the house; and Genevieve, a dog who rescues Madeline from [[drowning]] in the second book. Bemelmans published six Madeline stories in his lifetime, five as picture books and one in a magazine. A seventh was discovered after his death and published posthumously:\n\n#''[[Madeline (book)|Madeline]]'', 1939: in which Madeline must have her appendix removed\n#''[[Madeline's Rescue]]'', 1953: in which Madeline is rescued from drowning by a dog (later named Genevieve). Winner of the [[Caldecott Medal]] for U.S. [[picture book]] illustration\n#''[[Madeline and the Bad Hat]]'', 1956: in which the \"bad hat\" is Pepito, the Spanish ambassador's son, whose cruel antics outrage Madeline.\n#''[[Madeline and the Gypsies]]'', 1959: in which Madeline and Pepito have an adventure at a circus.\n#''[[Madeline in London]]'', 1961: in which Pepito moves to London, and Madeline and the girls go to visit him.\n#''[[Madeline's Christmas]]'', 1985: in which everyone in the house catches cold, except Madeline. (First published in ''[[McCall's]]'' in 1956).\n#''[[Madeline in America and Other Holiday Tales]]'', 1999: in which Madeline inherits a fortune from her American great-grandfather. The book also reveals Madeline's full name, Madeline Fogg.\n\n===Adaptations===\n*The first book, ''Madeline'', was adapted as an [[Academy Award]]-nominated 1952 [[short subject|short]] [[Animation|animated]] cartoon directed by Robert Cannon for [[United Productions of America|UPA]] and released by [[Columbia Pictures]], also titled ''[[List of UPA cartoons#Theatrical filmography - 1952: Madeline \u2013 Academy Award Nominee|Madeline]]''.\n*Between 1988 and 2002, an animated ''[[Madeline (TV series)|Madeline]]'' series was made for television (plus one direct-to-video film ''[[Madeline: Lost in Paris]]''), with the narration in rhyming style read by [[Christopher Plummer]].\n* A [[live-action]] ''[[Madeline (1998 film)|Madeline]]'' film based on several of the books appeared in 1998, directed by [[Daisy von Scherler Mayer]] and starring [[Hatty Jones]] as Madeline, [[Frances McDormand]] as Miss Clavel, and [[Nigel Hawthorne]] as Lord Covington.\n* Bemelmans's first novel, ''Madeline'', was briefly satirized on a February 2020 episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' by comedian and drag performer [[Ru Paul]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/snl-rupaul-gives-remedial-drag-lesson/606295/|title=RuPaul's Remedial Queer Comedy on Saturday Night Live|date=February 8, 2020|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=David|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/09/arts/television/saturday-night-live-rupaul.html|title='SNL' takes aim at Democratic presidential debate in New Hampshire|date=February 9, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBemelmans is said to have met his future wife, Madeleine \"Mimi\" Freund, as a model in Metzl's studio.<ref name=\"namesfamiliar\">{{cite book|author=Laura Lee|title=The Name's Familiar II|publisher=Pelican Publishing Co.|year=2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dwf1YYxQmRsC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=metzl+bemelmans#v=onepage&q=metzl%20bemelmans&f=false|accessdate=May 22, 2010|pages=25|isbn=9781455609178}}</ref> They had one daughter, Barbara, and three grandchildren, Paul Marciano, James Marciano, and [[John Bemelmans Marciano]].<ref name=\"Madelineandfamilybusiness\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/deborahljacobs/2013/11/27/madeline-and-the-family-business-2/|title=Madeline And The Family Business|first=Deborah L.|last=Jacobs|date=November 27, 2013|accessdate=July 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBemelmans died in New York of pancreatic cancer, aged 64 and was buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. <ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/21771/ludwig-bemelmans</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* 1934: ''Hansi''\n* 1936: ''The Golden Basket''\n* 1937: ''My War with the United States''\n* 1937: ''The Castle Number Nine''\n* 1938: ''Life Class'' \u2013 An autobiographical sketch.\n* 1938: ''Quito Express'' (travel book)\n* 1939: ''Madeline''\n* 1939: ''Small Beer'' (humorous memoirs based on his experiences in Europe and Hollywood)\n* 1940: ''Fifi''\n* 1941: ''At Your Service''\n* 1941: ''Hotel Splendide''\n* 1941: ''The Donkey Inside''\n* 1942: ''Rosebud''\n* 1942: ''I Love You, I Love You, I Love You''\n* 1943: ''Now I Lay Me Down to Sleep''\n* 1945: ''The Blue Danube''\n* 1946: ''Hotel Bemelmans''\n* 1947: ''A Tale of Two Glimps''\n* 1947: ''Dirty Eddie''\n* 1948: ''The Best of Times: An Account of Europe Revisited''\n* 1949: ''The Eye of God''\n* 1950: ''Sunshine: A Story about the City of New York''\n* 1952: ''How to Travel Incognito''\n* 1952: ''The Happy Place''\n* 1953: ''Father, Dear Father''\n* 1953: ''Madeline's Rescue''\n* 1953: ''The Borrowed Christmas''\n* 1954: ''The High World''\n* 1955: ''Parsley''\n* 1955: ''To the One I Love the Best'' \u2013 Bemelmans narrates his friendship with [[Elsie de Wolfe|Elsie de Wolfe, Lady Mendl]].\n* 1956: ''Madeline and the Bad Hat''\n* 1957: ''The Woman of My Life''\n* 1958: ''My Life in Art''\n* 1959: ''Madeline and the Gypsies''\n* 1960: ''Welcome Home!''\n* 1960: ''Are You Hungry, Are You Cold''\n* 1960: ''How to Travel To Europe All to Yourself''\n* 1961: ''Italian Holiday''\n* 1961: ''Madeline in London''\n* 1962: ''Marina''\n* 1962: ''On Board Noah's Ark''\n* 1963: ''The Street Where the Heart Lies'' <!-- completed by Bemelmans? -->\n* 1964: ''La Bonne Table''. Excerpts and essays involving food and drink, edited by Donald and Eleanor Friede\n* 1966: ''The Elephant Cutlet'' <!-- completed by Bemelmans? -->\n* 1985: ''Tell Them It Was Wonderful: Selected Writings'' (compilation of various autobiographical stories, published posthumously)\n* 1985: ''Madeline's Christmas'' (published 1956 in ''[[McCall's]]'')\n* 1999: ''Madeline in America and Other Holiday Tales''\n* 2004: ''Hotel Bemelmans'' (introduction by Anthony Bourdain) <Overlook Press, New York>\n{{colend}}\n\n* 2004: When You Lunch With The Emperor: The Adventures Of Ludwig Bemelmans (introduction by Andrew Goodfellow) Overlook Press, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist |refs=\n<ref name=roberts>\n[http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/16664887/food \"At the old Ritz\u2013Carlton the bes